<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-EasternEurope Bjt   11-13 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Eastern Europe, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Congressional Cheers Come Easier Than Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to restore Bjt designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Walesa, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the House and Senate are likely to
cheer themselves hoarse when Solidarity leader Lech Walesa
addresses a joint meeting of Congress on Wednesday.
   But the rush of events in Walesa's Poland and across Eastern
Europe has taken on a life of its own and there's little American
lawmakers can do but shout encouragement.
   Like sports fans jamming a coliseum, they are able to cheer
their team but unable to get into the game. The one exception, an
aid package for Poland and Hungary, has been debated for months but
could be approved just in time for Walesa's speech.
   In many respects, the flood of events in Eastern Europe has
stunned the capital like the sudden crumbling of a giant dam, long
thought to be indestructible but revealed as old and poorly
maintained.
   The events:
   _The symbolic destruction of the ultimate icon of communism's
grip on Eastern Europe, the Berlin Wall.
   _The mass exodus of East German citizens and tumultuous
anti-government demonstrations on East German streets.
   _The Democratic tide in Hungary and the removal of its section
of the Iron Curtain.
   _The advance of democratic institutions in Poland under Walesa's
Solidarity union.
   _The reform program of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
with its underpinnings of economic restructuring and a new openness
in thought and speech.
   The cheers came quickly, but with them came words of caution.
   ``We should be clear, but prudent, in our own actions,'' said
Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``We should not do
anything at this point which might needlessly add fuel to the
fire.''
   The one issue rushing to the surface in the aftermath of the
East German decision to open its borders to all wanting to leave is
the possibility that it will prove the first step toward the
reunification of the two Germanies.
   Many members of Congress believe that's an issue far too hot for
American involvement.
   The future of East and West Germany is something Congress should
think hard about, Dole said, adding that it's far too early to do
more than think.
   ``They are not issues for heated rhetoric right now,'' Dole said.
   Another caution came from Senate Majority Leader George
Mitchell, D-Maine.
   ``This is a historic event,'' he said of the decision to open
East German borders. ``It can be made even more so if the East
German government now acts to tear the wall down. Only then will we
know that their decision has lasting substance and meaning.''
   Some in Congress believe the time is coming to address the issue
of drastically reducing the American troop presence in Eastern
Europe.
   Many others say that is decidedly premature.
   They point out that the military forces of the Soviet Union, and
of the Warsaw Pact for that matter, remain intact and formidable.
   Arms control negotiations, both in nuclear and conventional
arms, are said to be making important progress. But they are far
from complete.
   Reducing U.S. troop strength, or lowering NATO's military
shield, are unlikely events short of stunningly successful arms
control negotiations and stability on the European continent.
   In the one area where Congress is prepared to do something
concrete _ aid to Poland and Hungary _ the rhetoric has been strong
and the action slow.
   By the time Walesa takes the podium in the House, Congress may
have passed legislation authorizing several hundred million dollars
in aid to Poland's non-communist government and to Hungary as well.
   But in contrast to the dazzling speed of events in Eastern
Europe, the aid bill has been traveling through the Capitol's
marble halls with the pace of an overweight snail, its passage
marked with partisan haggling over the price.
   By and large, Democrats have advocated far higher spending
levels than Republicans.
   The two days before Walesa's speech will be marked by Senate
debate over a three-year Democratic plan costing nearly $1 billion
and a more modest Republican package a little more than half as
expensive.
   Democrats have criticized President Bush as being ``overly
timid'' on the whole subject.
   Many Senate Democrats said the Republicans had embarrassed
Congress by attempting, for a time, to tie the Poland-Hungary aid
package to a totally unrelated domestic political controversy _ the
capital gains tax cut.
   But if Poland's staunchest supporters on Capitol Hill have their
way, Walesa and the aid package will arrive together.
</TEXT>
