<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CosmicExplorer Bjt   11-13 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cosmic Explorer, Bjt,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA's Last Unmanned Rocket to Launch Satellite to Study Early Universe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA this month plans to embark on a $400
million mission during which a satellite will study radiation left
from the ``big bang,'' the 15-billion-year-old blast that
scientists say created the universe.
   The space agency hopes the launch will produce the most
comprehensive observations ever of the early universe and the
processes that shaped it to form stars and galaxies.
   The $150 million Cosmic Background Explorer, a 16-by-28-foot
satellite, will be boosted into orbit 559 miles above Earth by
NASA's last unmanned rocket, said George Diller, an agency
spokesman.
   The Vandenberg Air Force Base launch had been scheduled for
Friday but has been delayed until at least Nov. 19 to replace a
malfunctioning guidance computer on the two-stage Delta rocket.
   The 116-foot rocket that will lift the 5,000-pound Explorer into
orbit will be the 184th Delta launched by the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration and the last expendable rocket NASA will
ever launch, Diller said.
   NASA stopped buying rockets in the early 1980s, deciding to
launch payloads from shuttles after its booster inventory was
exhausted. After the 1986 Challenger explosion, NASA said it was
wrong to rely on the shuttle. Then President Reagan ordered the
agency to stop launching commercial payloads and give such business
to private industry.
   After a 30-day shakedown, the solar-powered Explorer will spend
up to two years using three sensitive detectors to study how the
universe and its stars and galaxies developed, program scientist
Larry Caroff said from Washington.
   The instruments will measure ``cosmic background'' radiation.
Such radiation is different than dangerous ionizing radiation. It
includes microwaves, infrared light and ``submillimeter'' radiation
left over from the big bang _ the gargantuan explosion that
scientists believe was the fireball of creation.
   ``If God created the universe, he or she did it about 15 billion
years ago _ and did it with a bang,'' Caroff said.
   In an instant, a single point of matter expanded explosively
into a hot, dense and extraordinarily uniform sphere of gas
containing electrically charged particles, according to the theory.
   ``Think of a sphere with us at the center,'' Caroff said. The
surface ``is moving away from us very fast, glowing and emitting
radiation. That sphere is the hot gas characteristic of the early
universe. We have to look very, very far back in time, which means
very far out in the universe, to see that hot surface.''
   By measuring cosmic background radiation, the Explorer will look
back to certain times in the history of the universe, he explained.
   One of Explorer's instruments will measure infrared light, or
heat, emitted when the first atoms are believed to have formed
500,000 years after the big bang. That will help scientists learn
if, between three minutes to 500,000 years after the big bang, the
universe was shaped by exotic phenomena such as black holes, which
are so dense their gravity sucks in light.
   The satellite's microwave sensor will look for differences in
the brightness of cosmic background radiation to determine if the
big bang's fireball was equally bright in all directions.
   ``Out of that extraordinarily uniform collection of hot matter
eventually had to come galaxies and stars _ what is obviously a
very lumpy distribution of matter,'' Caroff said. ``The seeds of
that lumpiness must have been present in the early universe, and
the (microwave) instrument is meant to look for those seeds.''
   Explorer's third sensor will search for a burst of luminous
infrared and submillimeter radiation that scientists believed was
produced when the first stars and galaxies formed 200 million years
after the big bang.
   Telescopes ``can see distant galaxies a few billion years back
in time, but nothing like this,'' Caroff said. ``This will be the
first time anyone will be able to see evidence of the formation of
the first galaxies.''
   Caroff said the Explorer mission's cost includes $150 million
for the satellite and sensors, $70 million for the rocket and
launch and $160 million for manpower at NASA's Goddard Space Flight
Center in Maryland. About $20 million is for operations and data
analysis through the end of the mission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-CaliforniaDreamin' Bjt   11-13 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-California Dreamin', Bjt,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Primary Prophets Address Scenario: Early California Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Hampshire primary watchers, always wary
of threats to their state's earliest-in-the-nation presidential
primary, have turned their eyes westward toward the
biggest-in-the-nation: California.
   Rich, hip and populated, California is tired of having little
say in the presidential nominating process because the nominees
usually have been chosen long before Californians vote in June.
   Come January, legislators in the delegate-loaded state will
reconsider a proposal to move the state's primary to early March,
shortly after New Hampshire's.
   Will California's 27 million people mute New Hampshire's 1
million? Will its multiple media markets lure commentators'
attention from the grass roots, person-to-person struggle here?
   ``Absolutely not. It will have just the opposite effect,'' said
Robert Craig, a University of New Hampshire political analyst.
``All you have to do is ask yourself whether you'd like to be on
the cover of Time or Newsweek four days before the California
primary.''
   State Democratic Chairman Joseph Grandmaison and his Republican
counterpart, Rhona Charbonneau, agree.
   ``We're a small, close state,'' Charbonneau said. ``The media
will still be here. It's tradition ... and maybe superstition.''
   Since 1952, no one has been elected president without winning
New Hampshire.
   Supporters say New Hampshire's primary _ and, more recently,
Iowa's party caucuses _ should come early because personal contacts
are more effective than sound bytes in small states.
   They say the grassroots campaigning that has catapulted
long-shots to victory is impossible in a huge state like California
or a regional primary like ``Super Tuesday'' in the South in 1988.
   ``People make a mistake thinking that the only thing New
Hampshire has going for it is its early date,'' said Concord lawyer
Thomas Rath, who ran Bob Dole's 1988 primary campaign in New
Hampshire.
   He said the willingness of people in New Hampshire to get
involved early, their tightknit communities and the ``earned''
media exposure makes a victory worth billions in advertising in
California.
   ``You can't break through in a state like California,'' Rath
said. ``If you're a Jimmy Carter or a Bob Dole running against the
quasi-incumbent figure, you need a place that's going to dent that
front-runner's armor. George McGovern did it in 1972 and Gary Hart
did it in 1984.''
   Robert Beckel, campaign manager for Democratic presidential
nominee Walter Mondale in 1984, also has said a California switch
would discourage long-shots and attract nationally well-known
candidates.
   Democratic National Committee Chairman Ron Brown didn't go that
far. But in a recent visit to New Hampshire, he said the influence
of New Hampshire and Iowa was ``grossly overrated'' and praised
California's efforts to have its contest earlier.
   Beckel maintains that having the option of scoring a major
victory in California might make a candidate less inclined to sweat
it out in Iowa and New Hampshire.
   Rath dismissed the notion that candidates would campaign in
California on New Hampshire time.
   ``The week between the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire
primary (in 1988) was probably the political Super Bowl of all time
in this state,'' he said. ``And California a week after won't
change anything.''
   New Hampshire, Rath said, ``is too riveted in the nation's
political consciousness.''
   Dayton Duncan, press secretary for Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis in the latter part of his 1988 campaign and a top Mondale
spokesman in 1984, agrees.
   ``Obviously, they'll have to spend a lot of time in California,
but it's too big a state to campaign intensively the way you can in
New Hampshire,'' he said. ``The best way for you to get a head
start in California is to do well in New Hampshire.''
   Duncan said California and Super Tuesday are too big to organize
at the grassroots level and too expensive to advertise in. The
shortest route to becoming known is to win the caucuses and
primaries before them, he said.
   Ron Kaufman, regional political director for George Bush's 1988
campaign, said an early California primary will go much the same
way as Super Tuesday. That was meant to diminish the impact of New
Hampshire and Iowa.
   But Kaufman, now a White House aide, said it had the opposite
effect.
   ``The biggest single thing that helped Michael Dukakis in Super
Tuesday was winning New Hampshire,'' Kaufman said.
</TEXT>
