<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     11-13 0903</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Grain Production Linked to U.S. Output</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department analysis shows total
U.S. grain production is so huge that year-to-year changes in the
pattern send tremors throughout the world.
   When U.S. crop production falters, there is a good chance that
global figures also will show a decline. And when there are bumper
U.S. harvests, particularly of feed grains, the world stockpile is
fatter.
   Last week the USDA estimated this fall's corn harvest _ the
keystone of total U.S. grain output _ at 7.59 billion bushels, up
54 percent from the drought-savaged 1988 harvest.
   Put into international terms, the U.S. corn crop was 192.8
million metric tons. Allowing for about 2,205 pounds per ton, there
are approximately 39.4 bushels of corn in each ton _ or 36.7
bushels of wheat or soybeans.
   A related supply-and-demand report showed total U.S. grain
production this year at more than 283.8 million metric tons, which
includes corn output. That is up sharply from 204.1 million tons in
1988.
   The total includes wheat, coarse grains such as corn, sorghum,
oats and barley and milled rice. It does not include U.S. soybean
production, estimated at 52.7 million tons this year.
   According to the analysis, global production of grain in the
1989-90 year _ a composite of dates for various crops _ is
projected at about 1.671 billion tons, of which the U.S. share of
283.8 million would represent about 17 percent.
   Last year, when world grain output was 1.559 billion tons, the
U.S. share was 204.1 million, or 13 percent, which reflected the
drought reductions of 1988.
   After totaling all production and deducting how much grain will
be used in the year ahead, the USDA report said that by the end of
the current season in 1990 the world will have about 292.4 million
tons of grain left over.
   That would be down from 308.7 million tons left in the global
pantry this year and 403.9 million tons remaining in inventories in
1988.
   Of the total year-end grain stockpiles, the United States is
expected to have almost 74 million tons in 1990, or about 25
percent of the world total.
   This year, with a global inventory of 308.7 million tons of
grain, the United States accounted for 86 million tons, or 28
percent. And in 1988, with a world inventory of 403.9 million tons,
the U.S. share was 169.4 million tons _ 42 percent of the world's
total.
   As the figures show, the United States has borne the brunt of
grain stockpile reduction, while inventories in other countries
have dropped only slightly.
   This year, for example, the global reduction in year-end stocks
from 1988 was about 95.2 million tons. The United States accounted
for 85.4 million tons of the year-to-year decline.
   If the 1990 projection holds true, there will be a further
global reduction of 16.3 million tons, with the United States
accounting for 12 million.
   Thus, for the moment, at least, the major burden of holding
surplus grain inventories has been shifted from the United States
to other countries. How that stacks up a year or two from now will
depend on the weather and farmers' reactions to market developments.
   It will also depend on trade policies that affect exports and
domestic consumption of grains in scores of countries that buy from
American farmers or compete with them for export markets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says plans are
being made for agricultural trade and development missions to
Pakistan and Bangladesh.
   Undersecretary Richard Crowder said a mission also will be sent
to India, which had been visited earlier under trade mission
program. No dates have been set, he said.
   ``These three South Asian countries imported $1 billion worth of
U.S. agricultural products last year,'' Crowder said in his recent
announcement.
   ``In addition, Pakistan and Bangladesh are two of our largest
food aid recipients. These missions offer an excellent opportunity
to review all U.S. trade and development programs and make
recommendations for improved coordination with the three
countries.''
   The missions will include representatives from the departments
of Agriculture and State, and the U.S. Agency for International
Development. Three to six private representatives also will be
selected for each team.
   Congress authorized the missions program two years ago to
encourage greater U.S. private sector and foreign country
participation in U.S. agricultural trade and development
activities. Sixteen countries have been visited or are planned
under the program.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is asking for
public comments on procedures used to set government support prices
for ``pulled'' wool and mohair for the 1990 marketing year.
   Under current law, the support for pulled wool taken from
slaughtered lambs must be set a level relative to the support for
shorn wool from live sheep. In the past, this has been carried out
through payments based on the weight of live, unshorn lambs
marketed.
   The support for mohair, which is clipped from goats, also is
based on the comparable level for shorn wool.
   And the support for shorn wool is derived under a formula
prescribed in the law. Based on current readings, the 1990 support
for shorn wool will be $1.82 per pound, compared with $1.77 this
year.
   Comments may be sent by Dec. 26 to: Director, Commodity Analysis
Division, USDA-ASCS, Room 3741-S, P.O. Box 2415, Washington, D.C.
20013. More information may be obtained by calling 202-447-6734.
</TEXT>
