<FIRST>r w PM-Abortion-Capital     11-13 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Capital,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Activist Target '90 Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Abortion Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion-rights activists are pledging to
channel their energy from last week's election victories into 1990
political campaigns to assure that women continue to have freedom
of choice.
   ``This will be the issue of 1990,'' Molly Yard, president of the
National Organization for Women, told more than 150,000
abortion-rights activists who rallied Sunday in the nation's
capital.
   The Washington gathering was the largest in a string of
pro-choice rallies and other events held nationwide Sunday.
   ``Anti-choice is our Berlin Wall, and together, we will make it
fall forever,'' author and activist Gloria Steinem told about 1,300
people in Atlanta.
   In Washington, pro-choice Democratic and Republican politicians
joined a parade of entertainers to lead a nearly five-hour rally on
a sunny, mild autumn day. The crowd of demonstrators, waving signs
and shouting pro-choice slogans, stretched from the steps of the
Lincoln Memorial, along the Reflecting Pool to the Washington
Monument.
   Galvanized by election victories for pro-choice candidates
earlier this month in Virginia and New Jersey, demonstrators were
encouraged that politicians wouldn't be able to ignore them in the
next round of elections.
   ``I urge all of you to turn up the heat across the nation,''
said Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., who said a bill would be
introduced in Congress later this year to prohibit states from
interfering with women's right to abortion.
   He and other pro-choice lawmakers from Capitol Hill and
statehouses across the country urged activists to work for
candidates who pledge to preserve abortion rights for women.
   ``The action is in the states, and we are on board there and
ready,'' said Iowa Lt. Gov. Joann Zimmerman, a Democrat running for
governor. ``We will fight to see that we have pro-choice candidates.
   There are 34 Senate seats and 36 governor's offices up for
election next year.
   Rally organizers said the police count of 150,000 attending the
rally was low, estimating the crowd at twice that number. Among the
celebrities at the rally were singers Helen Reddy, Pete Seeger,
Peter Yarrow and Mary Travers and actress Ruby Dee.
   About 30 anti-abortion demonstrators gathered near the Lincoln
Memorial in an area roped off from the pro-choice demonstrators. A
few carried signs and one demonstrator used a megaphone to address
abortion-rights activists, who drowned him out with their own
``pro-choice'' chants.
   Across the country, thousands of other pro-choice activists
gathered at similar rallies and other events, including a sunrise
service in Kennebunk, Maine, near President Bush's vacation retreat.
   An abortion-rights demonstration in April drew hundreds of
thousands _ 300,000 by police estimates and 600,000 by the
organizers' count _ to the capital in anticipation of a Supreme
Court ruling in a Missouri abortion case.
   Soon after, the court gave broad authority to states to restrict
women's rights to terminate their pregnancies, though it left
intact its landmark 1973 decision legalizing abortion.
   The court will hear three cases later this month and in December
seeking to further restrict a woman's right to abortion.
   ``The Supreme Court did us a great favor,'' said Mary Ann Baker
of Youngstown, Ohio. ``It got us off our complacent behinds.''
</TEXT>
