<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-OutTooLate     11-13 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Out Too Late,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Berliner Savors Freedom, Though It May Be Too Late</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 55, East Berliner Hedda Zenter plans to apply
for her first passport. It may never take her any further than
another day trip to West Berlin, but it will mark the end of nearly
30 years of frustrated hopes.
   ``My dream is to see Paris, to buy an English newspaper,'' said
Mrs. Zenter. ``But to be here, that too was unbelievable.''
   Mrs. Zenter was one of about 1 million East Germans who took
their first chance Sunday to pass freely to the Western side of her
city.
   She visited the gravesites of departed friends, strolled through
the zoo, stopping to nibble a sandwich brought in her bag, then
crowded with thousands of others for a glimpse of West German
President Richard von Weizsaecker outside West Berlin's historic
Gedaechtniskirche, the memorial church.
   With no immediate relatives in West Berlin, Mrs. Zedda is among
millions of East Germans for whom the Berlin Wall was impenetrable.
   Applications to visit an elderly cousin last seen a few weeks
before the Wall went up in 1961 were repeatedly turned down by the
East German authorities who say a cousin does not qualify as a
close relation.
   Before East Germany scrapped travel restrictions last week,
family ties were one of the few grounds for applying to make a trip.
   Mrs. Zenter will never see her cousin now. He died six months
ago.
   The prospects of seeing Paris are also remote.
   A university-trained physical education teacher, now working as
a therapist at a clinic in East Berlin, Mrs. Zenter earns 840 East
German marks a month.
   At the exchange rate set by East Germany, that's about $450 a
month. At the unofficial rate that reflects its actual worth, the
sum is about $45.
   As for many others, the Communist government's momentous
political change of heart may have come too late for Mrs. Zenter.
   ``The thirty years that have gone were the prime of my life,''
she said. ``I wouldn't try to live outside East Germany now, I have
a house, my daughter is there, my job is there. These are the
things that tie. But I can, perhaps, travel.''
   That will need another revolution, a transformed East German
economy, to turn her earnings into hard currency.
   But Mrs. Zenter still has hopes. For nearly a decade, she has
studied English at home, listening to British Broadcasting Corp.
programs.
   On Sunday, she'd had her first chance to try it out on a native
English-speaker. ``You understand me? That's marvellous,'' she told
a reporter.
   For years too, she's been writing to a pen pal in Canada in
English.
   Most of the friend's replies never reached her. Now she thinks
the authorities will stop interfering with the mail.
   And if she never goes any further, walking through a checkpoint
in the Berlin Wall after simply waving an identify card at East
German border guards spelled freedom.
   ``I feel much freer,'' she said. ``Everything has changed, and
the change came from the bottom, from the people and it was hard
and bitterly fought for.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
