<DOCNO> AP891113-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IndianColleges     11-13 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Colleges,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scant Federal Funding Has Tribal Colleges Strapped</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Four grafs after 9th graf, `But the ... ' is EMBARGOED for release
at 10 a.m. EST, time set by source; publishable editor's is at end.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal support for the nation's 24 tribally
controlled colleges has steadily dwindled during the 1980s and is
now ``woefully insufficient,'' according to a study.
   Many such colleges, serving about 4,400 reservation Indians,
``are forced to carry on their work in trailers and abandoned
government buildings that other colleges would have hauled away or
bulldozed over 20 years ago,'' the Carnegie Foundation for the
Advancement of Teaching concluded in a report released Sunday.
   ``Such poor facilities not only restrict learning, but also make
a powerful statement of neglect,'' said the report, ``Tribal
Colleges: Shaping the Future of Native Americans.''
   The report by Paul Boyer, a journalism instructor at California
State University at Sacramento, is the first study of tribal
colleges, which appeared 21 years ago at the height of the
civil-rights movement.
   Tribal colleges today suffer from low faculty salaries, a high
teacher turnover rate and poorly equipped libraries and other
facilities, largely because Washington has consistently failed to
provide all the funds it had promised, Boyer wrote.
   Nevertheless, tribal colleges quickly have become pillars of
strength and hope for the Indian community, providing social and
economic counseling and giving students who dropped out of
mainstream colleges a second chance in a more nurturing
environment, the report said.
   Eighty-six percent of tribal college students who transfer to
mainstream colleges complete their education. In contrast, the
approximately 90,000 students who start college in non-Indian
schools have a 90 percent dropout rate.
   The oldest and largest, Navajo Community College in Tsaile,
Ariz., was founded in 1968 and enrolls more than 1,000 students.
The others are in Montana, North Dakota, South Dakota, California,
Oregon, Nebraska, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Illinois and elsewhere in
Arizona. Nearly all are two-year colleges.
   According to the report, the federal government has had a policy
of ``benign neglect'' toward these institutions. The report also
called on states and private foundations to help the colleges.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Following material EMBARGOED for release 10 a.m. EST:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Some private groups are helping. In Washington today, the
MacArthur Foundation announced a $5.7 million grant to help improve
educational and economic opportunities for Indians, including $3
million to 18 tribally-controlled colleges.
   ``American Indians are among the nation's poorest citizens, yet
their welfare generally has been overlooked by private
foundations,'' said Adele Simmons, foundation president.
   ``A small amount of money goes a long way at the tribal
colleges, and this new support is a real morale booster,'' said
Janine Windy-Boy, president of Little Big Horn College in Crow
Agency, Mont.
   U.S. West, another private foundation, announced plans to send
tribal college presidents for a training program at Harvard
University's Institute of Educational Management.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End embargoed material</NOTE>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   Eleven years ago, Congress authorized $4,000 for each full-time
equivalent student at tribal colleges, later raising it to $5,825.
But actual appropriations never approached those figures, the
report said.
   It said that in 1980, when there were only about 1,700 students
in tribal colleges, the federal government distributed $5 million _
about $3,000 per student _ under the Tribally Controlled Community
College Act.
   By 1989, with enrollments up nearly threefold, ``the
appropriation climbed to $8.5 million, but the amount generated for
each student declined to $1,900. In effect, tribal colleges are
being penalized for their own success,'' the study said.
   Twelve of the colleges are fully accredited and eight are
candidates for accreditation, according to the report.
   ``Clearly, tribal colleges are not marginal institutions that
have been `given a break,''' it said.
   Unlike past education efforts that have frequently encouraged
Indians to deny their heritage, a central mission of tribal
colleges has been to help tribes ``reclaim their cultural
heritage,'' wrote foundation president Ernest L. Boyer in a
foreword to the study.
   Since their beginnings, many have offered tutoring programs in
building basic skills and provide active counseling.
   Typical students are over age 30, female, and nearly all live on
reservations. Many attend tribal colleges after failing at
traditional colleges.
   College presidents are nearly all Indians, and all are chartered
and controlled by tribal advisory and governing boards.
   But most faculty are non-Indian, and low pay and isolation have
led to a high turnover, the report said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Copies of the report are available for $8 from
Princeton University Press, 3175 Princeton Pike, Lawrenceville,
N.J. 08648.
</TEXT>
