<FIRST>r a PM-MilitaryJetCrash     11-13 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military Jet Crash,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Flights Resume Three Days After Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military jets resumed flights over this
Atlanta suburb three days after a Navy attack plane crashed into an
apartment complex, killing two people and critically injuring two.
   Officials of Naval Air Station Atlanta had said pilots were
taking a few days off from training flights.
   But Petty Officer Linda Herring said Sunday the Navy considered
the crash an ``isolated incident'' and was not suspending any
flight operations.
   ``If an investigation indicates that changes should be made, we
will of course make them,'' she said. The investigation into
Thursday's A-7E Corsair II crash is expected to take at least 30
days.
   Funerals will be paid by the Navy, The Marietta Daily Journal
reported today, quoting unidentified officials.
   Killed were Richard Dick, 24, and Margie Padovani, who was 28
years old and two months pregnant. Dick's body will be transported
to Mississippi and Ms. Padovani's to New York.
   Her 5-year-old daughter, Jacquelyn, suffered burns over about
half of her body and was in critical condition today at Grady
Memorial Hospital.
   The 37-year-old pilot, Lt. Cmdr. Robert M. Conlyn Jr., also was
in critical condition today, at Kennestone Hospital in Marietta.
   Conlyn was the only person aboard the unarmed plane and ejected
just before it crashed into the Pine Village apartment complex,
engulfing it in flames.
   The jet was returning to the station adjacent to Dobbins Air
Force Base 15 miles from downtown Atlanta when it went down.
   On Saturday, residents of the 76-unit complex received $140,000
in interim compensation from the Navy and displaced families began
retrieving possessions that survived the fire.
   Twelve families whose apartments were destroyed have been
relocated. Twenty other apartments were heavily damaged, said
Kathie Barton, Smyrna's director of community relations.
</TEXT>
