<FIRST>r a PM-FreighterAground     11-13 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Freighter Aground,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Suing in Third Grounding in Florida Keys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is suing the owners of a Greek
freighter that ran aground on a fragile coral reef in the Florida
Keys, blaming negligence for the third such grounding in less than
three weeks.
   The U.S. Attorney's office filed the lawsuit Sunday with a
federal magistrate.
   Today, a Coast Guard board of inquiry was scheduled to begin
taking testimony from officers and crew, said Justice Department
spokeswoman Diane Cossin.
   Federal agents already have seized the 470-foot freighter MV
Elpis, which smashed living corals when it grounded Friday night on
Elbow Reef in the Key Largo National Marine Sanctuary.
   ``At this point, we're alleging negligence on behalf of those in
charge of the vessel,'' Ms. Cossin said. The U.S. District Court
suit will demand payment of recovery costs and compensation for
damage to the ocean ecosystem, but the amount hasn't been decided,
Ms. Cossin said.
   A similar suit in one of the earlier groundings seeks $9 million
in damages.
   The Elpis ran aground as its crew deliberately steered close to
the reef, away from the northward currents of the Gulf Stream, to
save time and fuel, said Michael White, manager of the Key Largo
National Marine Sanctuary.
   ``They were a little bit confused by the (navigation) lights,''
said sanctuary officer Jayson Horadam. ``They knew something was
wrong, but as they were rechecking their position, they went
aground.''
   The ship, carrying sugar and fuel oil, floated free at high tide
Saturday. There were no reports of fuel leaking.
   Federal agents boarded the vessel and moved it to an anchorage
off Miami Beach, Ms. Cossin said.
   The grounding did serious damage, said Billy Causey, a federal
marine biologist who inspected the site Sunday to help prepare
estimates for the lawsuit.
   ``Some of the major framework of the reef has been fractured and
damaged considerably,'' Causey said.
   Horadam said he spoke with the crew seven hours after the
accident, and they were cooperative.
   ``At first they weren't comprehending what the big to-do was
about,'' he said. ``We explained to them it was like somebody
destroying the Acropolis, and that totally got their attention.''
   The Elpis grounded about 4 miles south of the spot where the
155-foot freighter Alec Owen Maitland ran aground Oct. 25, cutting
a 200-foot swath through the sanctuary's reef.
   Five days later, the 475-foot cargo ship Mavro Vetranic got
stuck on a reef off the Dry Tortugas in the far western Keys. The
government is seeking $9 million in damages for the destruction of
a 500-foot strip of coral.
   The sanctuary is designed to preserve parts of the world's third
largest living reef, which extends about 200 miles from Miami to
the Dry Tortugas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
