<DOCNO> AP891113-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Deng     11-13 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Deng,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Says No More Official Meetings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deng Xiaoping, retired from his final Communist
Party post but still China's paramount leader, told a group of
Japanese today that they would be the last official delegation he
meets, sources at the session said.
   Deng, in the meeting with the Japanese business group, said he
was determined to make a clean break with official functions to
realize his goal of ending lifetime office-holding by senior
officials, the sources said.
   The Communist Party Central Committee on Thursday accepted
Deng's resignation as chairman of the party's Central Military
Commission, a powerful body that oversees military policy.
   Deng's handpicked successor, new party General Secretary Jiang
Zemin, was named to replace him on the commission.
   Deng, 85, resigned from most of his party and government
positions two years ago, leading a drive to force aging politicians
out of office and rejuvenate the Chinese leadership.
   However, he has remained the ultimate arbiter of policy through
his powerful links to those officially in power. He is expected to
remain China's most powerful man as long as he is in good health.
   At the meeting today, Deng expressed confidence in the abilities
of 63-year-old Jiang, who was plucked from the relative obscurity
of party boss in Shanghai to head the 48 million-member party after
the ouster of reformist leader Zhao Ziyang in June.
   Zhao was removed during the crackdown on the pro-democracy
movement, which was crushed June 4 with a military assault in
central Beijing that claimed the lives of hundreds of unarmed
civilians.
   Deng today acknowledged that Jiang, who has no strong power base
in Beijing, lacks experience. But he said Jiang was an intellectual
with impressive knowledge and ability and he felt reassured with
Jiang in power.
   Deng was speaking to Eishiro Saito, president of the Japan
Federation of Economic Organizations and head of the 35-member
business delegation.
   The meeting was held at the Great Hall of the People, the seat
of government. A day after his retirement was announced Deng met
former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger at the Great Hall.
   Deng today implied that the talks would be his last at the Great
Hall, although he would continue meeting foreign visitors in a
private capacity elsewhere.
</TEXT>
