<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flood Threat Recedes in Northwest; Record Highs in South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The return of colder temperatures helped ease the flood threat
in the Pacific Northwest, but it was more like summer again today
in the south central and southeastern United States.
   Warm weather that melted mountain snow, combined with days of
heavy rain, had led to flooding that caused millions of dollars in
damage in Washington state. But even though more rain was predicted
today, colder temperatures were expected to prevent further
snowmelt in the mountains.
   High mountain passes in Washington got up to four inches of snow
Sunday night, while Browning, Mont., got 11 inches of snow.
Northwestern Montana also had some flooding during the weekend from
storms that dropped up to five inches of rain in some areas.
   Farther south, 30 cities had record high temperatures Sunday as
readings soared into the 70s and 80s from the High Plains to the
southern and middle Atlantic Coast.
   Readings of 81 degrees at Chattanooga, Tenn., and 76 degrees at
Rapid City, S.D., were the warmest on record for so late in the
season. Early this morning temperatures remained in the 60s in much
of the South and central parts of the country.
   Except for the Northwest, dry weather prevailed across the
nation.
   The high for the nation Sunday was 89 degrees at Borrego
Springs, Calif., Gila Bend, Ariz., and Mcallen, Texas.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EST:
   _East: Albany, N.Y. 33 partly cloudy; Atlanta 57 fair; Boston 35
fair; Charleston, S.C. 56 fair; Chattanooga 45 fair; Cincinnati 53
fair; Cleveland 39 partly cloudy; Detroit 35 partly cloudy;
Hatteras 66 fair; Jacksonville 50 fair; Key West 75 partly cloudy;
Knoxville 44 fair; Macon 48 foggy; Miami 75 fair; New York 41
partly cloudy; Philadelphia 38 fair; Pittsburgh 35 fair; Portland,
Maine 29 fair; Richmond 45 fair; Tampa 64 fair; Washington, D.C. 45
fair.
   _Central: Birmingham 48 fair; Bismarck 34 windy; Chicago 50
fair; Denver 58 fair; Des Moines 60 fair; Indianapolis 44 fair;
Kansas City 65 windy; Little Rock 55 fair; Louisville 51 fair;
Memphis 57 fair; Nashville 55 fair; New Orleans 61 foggy; North
Platte 32 fair; Oklahoma City 64 fair; Omaha 52 fair; Rapid City 39
windy; St. Louis 60 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 35 partly cloudy;
Sault Ste. Marie 34 cloudy; San Antonio 69 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 41 fair; Anchorage 02 partly cloudy; Boise 44
partly cloudy; Casper 32 fair; Fairbanks 32 fair; Great Falls 22
cloudy; Honolulu 76 cloudy; Las Vegas 55 fair; Los Angeles 59
foggy; Medford 46 foggy; Pendleton 41 cloudy; Phoenix 62 fair;
Portland, Ore. 45 cloudy; Reno 38 fair; Salt Lake City 46 fair; San
Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 55 partly cloudy; Seattle 42 partly
cloudy; Spokane 34 cloudy.
   _International: Mexico City 55 fair; Acapulco 77 fair. No other
data available.
