<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0615EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Kohl-Poland     11-13 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kohl-Poland,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germany Leader Assures Poles That Bonn Remains Committed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-East Germany, Bjt ^By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl tried today to
allay concerns that events in East Gemany could affect the future
of West German commitments to Poland.
   Kohl continued a grueling program, traveling by bus in dense fog
to the southeastern city of Lublin, where he was awarded an
honorary doctorate by the prestigious Catholic University.
   In his address, Kohl assured his Polish hosts that ``We wish to
support these (Polish) reforms from the outside through a
prospective form of cooperation ... We are ready for such
dialogue.''
   West Germany has already pledged about $1.5 billion in aid, but
Finance Minister Leszek Balcerowicz has said that is still not
enough and does not correspond to West Germany's ability to help.
   The chancellor was to meet with lawmakers in Warsaw this
afternoon.
   Kohl held ``unusually intense and open'' talks with Communist
President Wojciech Jaruzelski and Solidarity Prime Minister Tadeusz
Mazowiecki on Sunday night, said Hans Klein, the chancellor's
spokesman.
   He told reporters the talks centered on the ``dramatic
developments'' in East Germany and the reform movement in Poland.
   The talks in Warsaw took place after Kohl and Mazowiecki
attended Mass in a former German village where members of the Nazi
resistance met during the war.
   The two men embraced in a sign of reconciliation before a crowd
of about 5,000 worshippers, many of whom are ethnic Germans who
decided to remain in their native region of Silesia.
   After the war, large parts of East Prussia and Silesia were
awarded to Poland and the border issue remains extremely sensitive
for both countries.
   West Germany pledged to respect the Oder and Neisse rivers as
Poland's western border in a 1970 Warsaw treaty, but a reunified
Germany might not be committed to those terms.
   West German conservatives recently have suggested seeking
reunification within the 1937 borders, which include about
one-third of present-day Poland.
   Kohl alluded to the pain of those Germans expelled as a result
of the postwar settlement in a speech in Warsaw on Thursday. Poland
also lost large areas of territory, which were incorporated into
the Soviet Union.
   Polish television on Sunday broadcast two panel discussions
devoted to the explosion of events in East Germany and the
consequences for Poland of Germany reunification.
   Some of the participants welcomed the dismantling of the Berlin
Wall, saying it brought Poland as well as East Germany closer to
Western Europe.
   But any tampering with the postwar order that would alter affect
Polish security was out of the question.
   ``I would like to hear a clear assurance that our western border
is untouchable, said Jacek Maziarski, a journalist at Tygodnik
Solidarnosc, the weekly edited by Mazowiecki until he became prime
minister on Aug. 24.
   ``I want to believe Germans will also understand there is more
sense in business than in initiation of new fights,'' Maziarski
said.
   Klein said Kohl had raised the issue of a concentration of
assistance for East Germany, but the spokesman appeared to indicate
that would not jeopardize help for Poland.
   The two countries signed agreements that pledge $1.5 billion in
aid for Poland before Kohl interrupted his visit Friday for one day
to attend an emergency Cabinet meeting in Bonn on the East German
situation.
   The Solidarity-led government said aid is needed for the country
to make the transition to a market economy and secure democratic
reforms now under way.
</TEXT>
