<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths     11-13 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: PMs separate planned on Ibarruri</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Dolores Ibarruri</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legendary Communist leader Dolores
Ibarruri, nicknamed ``La Pasionaria'' for her fiery oratory during
the Spanish Civil War, died Sunday. She was 93.
   She died at 7:30 p.m. in Madrid's Ramon y Cajal Hospital, a
statement from the hospital director said. Dr. Juan Beltran said
Mrs. Ibarruri died of pneumonia ``with respiratory insufficiency.''
   At her bedside was her sole surviving child _ her daughter Amaya
_ and other relatives.
   During the 1936 siege of Madrid by rebel forces led by Gen.
Francisco Franco, Mrs. Ibarruri's defiant pharse ``No pasaran!''
(``They shall not pass''), became the rallying cry of the loyalist
Republican army.
   Her speeches made her an anti-fascist heroine to millions during
the 1936-39 war.
   The daughter and granddaughter of northern Basque coal miners,
she was a founding member of the Spanish Communist Party. At the
time of her death, she was the party's honorary president.
   After Franco's nationalists won the war in 1939, she fled to the
Soviet Union, returning to Madrid in 1977, two years after Franco's
death.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Willard Worcester</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willard C. ``Bill'' Worcester, a retired
executive with the Pulliam newspapers and one of the organizers of
Phoenix Newspapers Inc., died Saturday at his home. He was 86.
   In 1946, Worcester was named general manager and a director of
Indianapolis-based Central Newspapers Inc., the parent Pulliam
corporation, and executive vice president and publisher of the
chain's papers in Muncie, Ind.
   That year, Worcester participated in Central's purchase of The
Arizona Republic and The Phoenix Gazette from the Arizona
Publishing Co. Central set up a subsidiary, Phoenix Newspapers, to
publish the newspapers and Worcester became first vice president
and a director of the corporation.
   He served as acting publisher of the Republic and the Gazette in
1952 and 1953. Worcester later served a stint as general manager of
Phoenix Newspapers before again becoming publisher of the Muncie
newspapers.
   In 1977, Worcester was named executive-in-residence in the
Arizona State University College of Business Administration.
   He is survived by his wife, Idona; his daughter, Nancy W. Chase;
one son, Willard M.; and six grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>John Takawira</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sculptor John Takawira, who carved
folklore into stone, died after a long illness, it was announced
Saturday. He was 51.
   The National Gallery of Zimbabwe, where Takawira's carvings were
often displayed, said he died Wednesday and will be buried this
week.
   The Vukutu Art Foundation, where Takawira often worked, said he
he was born in the rural town of Chegutu (formerly Hartley) near
Harare in 1938 and learned his craft from other artists in the
1960s.
   Takawira's subjects were drawn mainly from traditional folklore
and the legends surrounding animals and birds.
</TEXT>
