<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jet safely aborted takeoff
at O'Hare International Airport after a warning light went on in
the cockpit. No one was injured, officials said.
   The Chicago-to-Stockholm Flight 80 was speeding down a runway
Sunday when the warning light for a landing gear door went on, said
Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Mort Edelstein.
   He said the pilot aborted the takeoff, causing the brakes on the
Boeing 767 to overheat and smoke.
   None of the 168 people aboard was reported injured, said airline
spokesman Jim Brown.
   The plane was towed to a maintenance hangar, where passengers
got off and boarded buses back to the terminal, Brown said. A few
hours later, they were put on another plane.
   Brown said late Sunday that mechanics hadn't determined why the
warning light had gone on.
