<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-13 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher, Gold Stronger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against most major foreign
currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices rose as
much as $5.40 an ounce.
   Currency dealers said the dollar was fluctuating in a narrow
range in quiet trading, and that attention had shifted to cross
rate trading.
   They said the market was still trying to digest the sweeping
reforms in East Germany, but said most traders expect the rapid
changes in relationships between the two Germanies to have a
positive impact on the West German mark.
   ``The German thing is throwing everything else into the shadows
right now,'' said a trader at a West German bank in Frankfurt.
   ``A lot of people abroad were assuming this would somehow be bad
for the (West) German economy and knocked the mark lower Friday.
They're apparently skeptical about the changes.''
   ``I think, when all is said and done, people will see this as a
positive rather than a negative factor for the mark,'' she said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.80 yen to a closing 143.55 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 143.68 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday:
   _1.8625 West German marks, unchanged
   _1.6420 Swiss francs, up from 1.6370
   _6.3175 French francs, up from 6.3135
   _2.1008 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0950
   _1,359.00 Italian lire, up from 1,354.75
   _1.1680 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1694
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5760 to buy one pound, slightly cheaper for buyers than $1.5765
late Friday.
   Spot gold was higher but below earlier peaks in lively trading
this morning in London, as fresh investor interest gave the
precious metal a boost.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $386.10 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $386.00. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $389.05.
   A wave of buying out of Zurich helped gold surge to $389.90
there, up from $384.50 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.25 to close at a bid $387.17.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.31 a troy
ounce, up from Friday's $5.25.
</TEXT>
