<FIRST>r a PM-AmericanKilled     11-13 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-American Killed,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokane Teacher Killed in Salvadoran Fighting, Mother Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Spokane woman says her 25-year-old son,
a social studies and English teacher, was killed in El Salvador
over the weekend by a grenade.
   Kay Babcock said Sunday she was told that her son, Christopher,
who had taught at the American High School in San Salvador for two
years, apparently was struck by a grenade fragment in the head late
Saturday.
   Mrs. Babcock said she was informed of her son's death Sunday by
Spokane police. In San Salvador, U.S. Embassy spokesman Barry
Jacobs said a U.S. citizen who taught at the school was killed, but
did not identify him.
   ``He always said he was in a place where Americans weren't
really at risk,'' Mrs. Babcock said in an interview with the
Spokane Chronicle and Spokesman-Review. ``I don't suppose he ever
really thought about it.''
   In San Salvador, government forces fought today for control of
the capital after leftist rebels, in their biggest offensive since
1981, seized parts of the city and attacked military posts in the
provinces.
   Carlos Mendoza, spokesman for the Salvadoran Red Cross, said at
least 20 civilians were killed in the fighting.
   At least 139 people were killed and 317 wounded, hospitals and
the military officials said, in fighting that began Saturday night
and prompted rightist President Alfredo Cristiani to declare a
state of siege.
   Babcock and his roommate apparently lived a few doors away from
the home of Christiani, his mother said.
   As he and a fellow American teacher were about to enter their
rented home late Saturday, a rifle grenade exploded somewhere near
them, his mother said she was told. She didn't know any other
details or the condition of her son's roommate.
   Students at the private school where Babcock taught were
primarily children of the country's ruling class, his mother said.
   Mrs. Babcock said her son felt a duty to teach El Salvador's
young people to be aware of what was happening around them.
   ``He knew they were going to be the country's leaders someday,''
she said. ``He was very idealistic.''
   In a telephone conversation last week, Babcock told his mother
``how he couldn't hear the bombing anymore,'' adding that ``he
didn't seem to indicate there was unrest'' in the air.
</TEXT>
