<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0859EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China     11-13 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Committee Formally Ousts Zhao</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party Central Committee has
formally ousted former party chief Zhao Ziyang from its ranks,
sources said today, nearly six months after he was accused of
supporting the student-led democracy movement.
   The Nov. 6-9 plenary session of the committee voted that Zhao,
who was ousted from office in June, would be removed from all his
duties in the committee, according to sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The Central Committee, meeting for the first time since the June
session during which Zhao was purged, did not mention Zhao in its
final communique, leaving open the question of how the party would
handle his case.
   Some party hard-liners reportedly hoped to put Zhao on trial on
charges of fomenting counter-revolutionary rebellion, but others,
including senior leader Deng Xiaoping, are believed to have
resisted.
   It was unclear whether Zhao had been stripped of his party
membership as well or would be allowed to remain a member of the
47-million-member party he once headed.
   Zhao, 70, one of the architects and main proponents of the
market-oriented reforms that have brought prosperity to millions of
Chinese, still commands wide popular support.
   He has not been seen in public since an emotional meeting with
student hunger strikers on May 19, and is believed to be under
house arrest.
   The June 24 Central Committee meeting that accused him of making
serious mistakes in the ``anti-party, anti-socialism turmoil''
approved his dismissal from all his party posts, including his seat
on the 170-member Central Committee.
   Last week's vote apparently gave a formal stamp to that decision.
   China's crackdown on political dissent continued with a report
today of a man arrested in southeastern China for painting
``reactionary slogans'' on buildings and portraits of Mao Tse-tung.
   Police arrested factory official Sun Xiongying in late September
for defacing public property and portraits of China's revolutionary
leader in the coastal city of Fuzhou, the Legal Daily News said.
   Sun smeared ``reactionary slogans'' on buildings at the May 1st
Factory, Workers' Cultural Palace and City Hall as well as on
pictures of Mao, the paper said.
   It did not further identify Sun, say what the slogans were or
explain the delay in reporting his arrest, adding only that the
case was being tried.
   Arrests continue nationwide in the wake of the widespread
pro-democracy protests of this spring. Authorities are continuing
their searches for ``counterrevolutionaries'' accused of fomenting
the unrest and plotting to overthrow China's communist government.
   Earlier this month police in the southern province of Guizhou
reported arresting 10 members of an underground group allegedly
conspiring to overthrow the government.
   Last week police in Chongqing, central Sichuan province, were
reported to have broken up a ``counterrevolutionary clique'' and
arrested four members who planned to organize underground armed
forces and tried to steal firearms and ammunition.
</TEXT>
