<FIRST>r a PM-SlainCouple     11-13 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Slain Couple,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Teen-agers Held in Slaying of Auto Exec and Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities believe two teen-agers
held in the killings of a General Motors Corp. executive and his
wife chose their victims at random.
   The bullet-riddled bodies of Glenn E. Tarr, 53, and his wife,
Wanda, 58, were found in a park in nearby Pontiac on Friday, a day
after their home was ransacked and robbed and their two cars stolen.
   A 17-year-old Pontiac boy and a 16-year-old boy from Waterford
Township were arrested Saturday. They were scheduled to be
arraigned today in the killings.
   One of the teen-agers was seen driving one of the Tarrs' cars
Saturday in Rochester Hills, said Sgt. Maurice McAllister, of the
county Sheriff's Department. The car was later found abandoned in
Bloomfield Township. The Tarrs other car was found Friday night in
Rochester.
   A gun found inside one of the cars was believed to have been
used in the killings, McAllister said.
   Investigators believe the teen-agers abducted Wanda Tarr at
random when she stopped at an automatic teller machine at the
National Bank of Detroit in Rochester Hills, then forced her to
return home, Sheriff's Capt. Lewis Doyle said.
   Guns, liquor, jewelry and part of a coin collection were taken
from the home, said sheriff's Lt. Gerard Carlin.
   Glenn Tarr, a 25-year GM employee, was assistant manager of
marketing information and research for the Chevrolet Division
headquarters in Warren, GM spokesman Jim Crellin said. Wanda Tarr
sold life insurance for Christian Memorial Cultural Center in
Rochester Hills.
</TEXT>
