<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia     11-13 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jakes Urges Changes In Communist Leadership, But Not Communist Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Milos Jakes
urged changes within the party to bring in younger members more
likely to initiate change, official media reports said today.
   But the hard-line leader said the government would not tolerate
street protests nor engage in dialogue with groups advocating that
Czechoslovakia abandon communism.
   Jakes spoke Sunday to a conference of official Communist youth
where speakers were unusually critical of the regime, accusing
leaders of losing the trust of Czechoslovakia's young people.
   ``We must introduce the new generation in the process of
change,'' Jakes told about 9OO delegates to the conference
sponsored by the Socialist Youth Union, the sole official
representative of young people in Czechoslovakia.
   The two-day session, which ended here Sunday, came at a time of
breathtaking reforms in neighboring East bloc countries and amid
increasing calls for changes in the Czechoslovak leadership.
   ``The cadre policy will probably constantly be subject to great
changes,'' because the older generation is ``leaving,'' the
official CTK news agency quoted Jakes as saying.
   Most of the country's leaders were installed after the
Soviet-led invasion that crushed the Prague Spring reforms of
Alexander Dubcek in 1968. They have been reluctant to implement the
kind of politicl changes sweeping the Soviet bloc from Moscow to
Berlin.
   Czechoslovakia, which enjoys one of the highest standards of
living of the seven Warsaw Pact nations, has taken one of the
hardest lines against dissent.
   Baton-wielding police in Prague last month dispersed up to
10,000 demonstrators who called for freedom and a new government,
highlighting major differences among the East-bloc allies on free
expression and reform.
   Jakes indicated this tough line would not change, saying, ``a
dialogue cannot be conducted ... through such street demonstrations
whose aim is to provoke, ... violate pubic order and ... to strive
in fact for abandoning'' communism, CTK reported.
   Pressure on Jakes, 67, and President Gustav Husak, 76, is
believed to be growing, analysts said. Husak served as Communist
Party leader after the Warsaw Pact invasion until December 1987
when Jakes replaced him.
   Communist youth leader Vasil Mohorita criticized the leadership
and said the government's course of ``restructuring'' which
foresees some economic changes but few political reforms ``does not
fit the expectations of young people,'' CTK reported.
   Some youths are losing faith in the possibility for communist
renewal, Mohorita said.
   ``The reason for the weakening of trust is that an atmosphere of
self-satisfaction has ruled in this country,'' he said, adding that
the party had covered up mistakes and refused to accept criticism.
   Jakes said a restructuring of the party apparatus had already
begun and pledged that it would continue.
</TEXT>
