<FIRST>r a PM-CampBombing     11-13 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Camp Bombing,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Misses Target, Nearly Bombs Campers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DESERT CENTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S. Navy jets mistakenly
dropped a dozen bombs about 300 yards from a campsite, leaving six
campers shaken, including one who was slightly injured by shrapnel.
   Two A-6 attack bombers from the Naval Air Facility in El Centro
accidentally dropped the round of explosives three miles north of
the Chocolate Mountain Aerial Gunnery Range, a Navy spokesman said
Sunday.
   ``It was definitely a mistake, but as to why I don't know,''
said Mike Ray, public affairs officer for the El Centro station.
Saturday's bombing was under investigation and Ray said he had no
further comment.
   The bombing left a half-dozen craters 10 to 12 feet in diameter
and about a foot deep.
   The jets apparently overshot the target area and dropped the
250-pound bombs, igniting small fires over four acres of the
California Desert Conservation Area, said Tom Biller, a U.S. Bureau
of Land Management ranger who investigated the accident Sunday with
Navy officials. The fires posed no threat in the desert scrubland.
   ``We're really lucky no one was seriously injured,'' said
Biller, of the bureau's Palm Springs office. The aircraft's bombs
came within 300 yards of the campsite before the error was detected
and the mission aborted, he said.
   ``It was unreal. It just pulverized the area,'' said George
Hurley, 46, an off-road motorcycle rider who was staying at the
campsite with five friends.
   Hurley, an Air Force veteran from Moreno Valley, said he and his
companions were about to make lunch when a plane passed overhead
and dropped the bombs.
   Hurley's brother-in-law, Bob Koch of Hacienda Heights, was
struck in the chest with shrapnel. Koch said the injury became
swollen, red and bruised.
   ``I'll tell you, it was the most frightening experience I've
ever had,'' said Koch.
   The camp site is about 150 miles southeast of downtown Los
Angeles.
</TEXT>
