<FIRST>r a PM-AshlandOil     11-13 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ashland Oil,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Company Agrees To $4 Million Settlement for Fuel Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil's pricetag for a massive fuel
spill into Pittsburgh's two rivers last year has risen to more than
$27 million with the latest settlement of $4 million for the state
of Pennsylvania.
   The Pittsburgh Press reported Sunday that Ashland reached
agreement with the state Department of Environmental Resources for
the $4 million payment to cover alleged violations of state
environmental law. The payment also covers damages to drinking
water, fish, waterfowl and other natural resources.
   More than 700,000 gallons of diesel fuel flowed into the
Monongahela and Ohio rivers when a storage tank ruptured at
Ashland's Floreffe Terminal in Jefferson, south of Pittsburgh, on
Jan. 2, 1988.
   The Ashland, Ky., company also has agreed to reimburse
Pennsylvania agencies for overtime expenses, equipment purchases
and other costs stemming from the spill under a separate settlement
not yet made public, the Press said.
   Officials said that sum would be in the six-figure range but
would not be more specific.
   The settlement would bring to about $27.25 million the amount
Ashland has spent or committed itself to spend on damage and
expense claims by individuals, businesses and government agencies,
on civil penalties, for a criminal fine and for cleanup.
   The figure consists of about $14 million for damages, expenses
and civil penalties, including the $4 million Pennsylvania
agreement; $11 million for cleanup; and $2.25 million for a
criminal fine.
   The company agreed to pay up to $16 million more under the terms
of a class-action settlement filed in U.S. District Court in
Pittsburgh last week.
   The costs haven't had a significant impact on the company's
finances, Ashland spokesman Roger Schrum said. Ashland had to pay a
$2.5 million deductible, but insurance covered the rest, he said.

</TEXT>
