<FIRST>r a PM-GeneticScreening     11-13 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Genetic Screening,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: New Technique Helps Prevent Genetic Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women who are carriers of genetic diseases may be
able to avoid bearing defective fetuses through a newly developed
technique for screening human eggs before fertilization, Chicago
researchers say.
   Under the process developed at the Reproductive Genetics
Institute of Illinois Masonic Medical Center, doctors remove eggs
from the woman's body as they would in any test-tube pregnancy.
   The eggs are inspected for mutations. Then, healthy eggs are
fertilized in a petri dish with sperm and returned to the woman's
womb.
   The technique was discovered by embryologist Yury Verlinsky,
director of the cell genetics laboratory, who said he was able to
spot mutations in human ova ready for in vitro fertilization.
   ``In the future,'' Verlinsky said, ``it could become routine for
those disorders for which there is a well-defined gene because it
decreases risk to an embryo.''
   A report on the technique was to be presented today at the
annual meeting of the American Society of Human Genetics in
Baltimore.
   ``This procedure is for couples who already know they're
carriers of genetic diseases but won't consider an abortion,'' said
Dr. Charles Strom, chief of medical genetics at the center. ``These
people already may have lost a child, or have an aversion to
abortion or the psychological trauma that can go along with it.''
   Current genetic tests are conducted after pregnancy and hold
some risk to the developing fetus.
</TEXT>
