<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Funerals     11-13 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Funerals,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Allows States to Ban Door-to-Door Solicitation for Funerals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today allowed states to ban
door-to-door and telephone solicitation for pre-arranged funerals
and burial.
   The court, without comment, left intact a West Virginia law
challenged by a funeral service company as an infringement of
free-speech rights.
   The West Virginia Legislature in a 1983 law enacted extensive
new regulations of the funeral service industry.
   The law barred companies from making unsolicited sales pitches,
either door-to-door or over the phone, to potential customers.
   National Funeral Services Inc. sells pre-arranged, or pre-need,
funeral and burial services. The company is a West Virginia
subsidiary of Legacy One Inc., which owns funeral homes and
cemeteries througout the Southeast and Midwest.
   The company said it seeks to promote competition in the industry
by offering its services before they are needed.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last March said West
Virginia's ban on door-to-door and telemarketing sales does not
violate the free-speech protections of the Constitution's First
Amendment.
   The state has a legitimate interest in ``the protection of
consumers from overreaching and high-pressure sales tactics of this
most unique product,'' the 4th Circuit court said. ``West
Virginia's ban on solicitation is supported by the substantial
interest of protecting privacy.''
   The appeals court said the free-speech restrictions are minimal,
noting that the state permits direct-mail and newspaper
advertisements for funeral services.
   The Supreme Court on Oct. 2 left intact a similar Virginia law
prohibiting telephone solicitation for pre-arranged funerals.
   The case acted on today is National Funeral Services vs.
Rockefeller, 89-639.
</TEXT>
