<FIRST>u i BC-Lebanon-Hoss     11-13 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lebanon-Hoss,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoss Named Prime Minister Four Times Since 1976</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who has been a
voice of moderaton through 14 years of civil war, returns to the
prime minister's office for the fourth time in 13 years to try to
end the fighting.
   The 59-year-old economist, designated by President Rene Mouawad
on Monday to form a new government, is a firm backer of democracy,
a free-wheeling economy and Christian-Moslem coexistence. He is
married to a Christian.
   Formidable obstacles stand before Hoss as he attempts to head a
government slated to introduce political reforms giving the Moslem
majority an equal share of power with the dominant Christian
minority.
   Foremost is the defiant Christian army commander, Gen. Michel
Aoun, who insists that a three-man interim military Cabinet he
headed for the past 13 months is the sole legitimate authority in
Lebanon.
   Hoss' main asset is the wide respect he commands among
Christians and Moslems. Even the caustic Aoun spared Hoss in his
tirades against local, Arab and foreign leaders.
   ``He is a clean and honest man whom I respect,'' Aoun once said
of Hoss during the height of the general's ``war of liberation'' to
drive Syria's 40,000 troops from Lebanon.
   Hoss' previous tenure in office began June 2, 1987, a day after
Prime Minister Rashid Karami was assassinated. Hoss was named
acting prime minister by President Amin Gemayel.
   Hoss, who served as education minister under Karami for three
years, clashed with Aoun when Gemayel named the general head of an
interim military Cabinet on Sept. 22, 1988, the day Gemayel's
six-year term expired and Parliament was unable to agree on a
successor.
   Moslems pledged allegiance to Hoss, who eventually tendered the
resignation of his Cabinet when Mouawad was elected president Nov.
5.
   Hoss was born Dec. 20, 1929, to a middle-class Sunni family in
west Beirut. His father died while he was very young and the family
sacrificed heavily to see him through his studies at the American
University of Beirut.
   After graduating in 1952 with a degree in economics and business
administration, he worked for the American-owned Trans-Arabian
Pipeline Co.
   He then transferred to the Beirut Chamber of Commerce in 1954,
where his future wife, Leila Pharoan, worked as his secretary.
   In 1955, Hoss left the Chamber of Commerce to teach at the
American University and to continue his studies. He received his
masters in 1957, the same year he married.
   Christian-Moslem marriages were very rare in Lebanon at the
time. Mrs. Hoss has been quoted as saying her parents strongly
opposed the union, ``But they gave in when Salim and I convinced
them nothing can break our marriage.''
   The tall, balding, bespectacled Hoss does not smoke or drink and
normally goes to bed early. He prefers Oriental food and likes to
spend evenings listening to classical music.
   The couple left for the United States in 1959, where Hoss
obtained a doctorate in economics and business administration from
the the University of Indiana at Bloomington.
   His only child, daughter Wadad, 30, was born in the United
States.
   On his return to Lebanon, Hoss taught business management at the
American University of Beirut, and from 1964 to 1966 he worked in
Kuwait as financial adviser to the Kuwait Fund for Arab Economic
Development.
   He returned to the university in 1966, but the following year
his close friend, Elias Sarkis, became governor of Lebanon's first
banking commission.
   The banking system had been shaken by the crash of Intra Bank,
then Lebanon's largest, and Hoss and Sarkis worked together to
shore up the system.
   With this accomplished by 1973, Hoss was appointed chairman and
general manager of Lebanon's semi-public Development Bank.
   He remained at this post until Sarkis, who had been elected
president, named him prime minister in December 1976, 19 months
after the outbreak of the civil war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
