<FIRST>r a PM-FreePressSuspensions     11-13 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Free Press Suspensions,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists Suspended For Buying Stereo, Sausage From Addict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Detroit Free Press reporter and a Pulitzer
Prize-winning photographer have been suspended after revealing that
the photographer bought items from a drug addict who was a source
for a report on drugs.
   Photographer Manny Crisostomo bought a Sony Walkman and a
sausage from a crack addict referred to as Tim in a story
accompanied by photographs published Oct. 15, according to Free
Press executives.
   Crisostomo said he bought the items because he was afraid the
addict might become violent. The addict used the money to buy
crack, Executive Editor Heath J. Meriwether said.
   Crisostomo was suspended without pay for three days and reporter
Pat Chargot for two days for ``violating ethical standards,''
Meriwether said in a memo distributed to the staff Friday.
   In the memo, Meriwether said Chargot revealed the purchases
Monday as she was working on a follow-up story. The story was
canceled.
   Crisostomo and Chargot originally told their editors that Tim
asked for money but they refused. The story said the addict begged
for money but wasn't given any.
   ``This serious breach of ethics is painful for everybody at this
newspaper who, like Chargot and Crisostomo, poured themselves into
that project and were extremely proud of it. All of us suffer for
this mistake,'' Meriwether said in Saturday's newspaper.
   Crisostomo won a Pulitzer Prize in April for photos that
documented a year in the life of Detroit's Southwestern High
School. Crisostomo and Chargot did not return phone calls made to
their homes.
</TEXT>
