<HEAD>Pakistanis Summon Indian Ambassador Over Hindu-Moslem Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with throughout with Gandhi comment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pakistan Foreign Ministry
summoned India's ambassador today to express Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto's concern about plans by Indian Hindus to build a temple at
a site held sacred by Moslems.
   A brief statement issued by the Foreign Ministry said Indian
High Commissioner J.N. Dixid assured the Pakistanis his government
had taken steps to protect the sanctity of the site.
   At the same time, Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi today told
foreign countries to stay out of the dispute. He did not refer to
any particular country but said ``interference was aimed at
fomenting'' sectarian violence in India, United News of India
reported.
   On Sunday, an Indian magistrate temporarily blocked the Hindus'
plans to build the temple at the site of the 17th century Babri
Masjid, or Mosque of Babar, in the northern Indian town of Ayodhya.
   The dispute has prompted a number of demonstrations in Moslem
Pakistan, India's western neighbor.
   Officials said two people were injured Sunday in the southern
Pakistani city of Sukkur when police fired tear gas at youths
protesting the arrest of 27 people the day before for allegedly
damaging two Hindu temples and three Hindu-owned shops.
   Demonstrators chanted and burned effigies of Gandhi in other
Pakistani cities, but authorities said the protests generally were
peaceful.
   Hindus comprise less than 2 percent of Pakistan's 107 million
people. The overwhelming majority are Moslems.
   Indian Foreign Ministry officials accused Ms. Bhutto of
``malicious meddling'' in the country's internal affairs when she
condemned construction of the Ayodhya temple on Saturday.
   About 300 people have been killed in Hindu-Moslem violence in
three Indian states since August when plans for the temple were
announced.
   Pakistan was carved out of mainly-Hindu India at the end of
British colonial rule in 1947. The countries have fought each other
three times since then, with India emerging the victor.
</TEXT>
