<HEAD>Monticello Optometrist to Appeal Board's Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTICELLO, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An optometrist says he plans to appeal
an administrative decision putting him on probation for having some
women patients strip to the waist during eye exams.
   The Iowa Board of Optometry Examiners last month placed Gary
Fisher on three years' probation and ordered him to stop asking
patients to strip to the waist during examinations.
   Fisher said he was checking for scoliosis, or curvature of the
spine, because he thought it was linked to some eye disorders.
   The board said ``the evidence did not show there was any
voyeuristic or any other kind of sexual motivation.''
   Fisher's lawyer, John McClintock of Des Moines, said the board's
decision will be appealed in Polk County District Court.
   Fisher said the board members ``succumbed to the contamination
of the judicial process by political medicine and the
sensationalistic media.''
