<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-AFL-CIOConvention 1stLd-Writethru a0446 11-13 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AFL-CIO Convention, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Federation Celebrates Solidarity's Success, Mulls Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with convention opening, Kirkland keynote comments;
picks up at pvs 4th graf, Welesa's appearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO opened its biennial convention
today, savoring its role in the success of Poland's Solidarity
union and determined to end what may be the American labor
movement's worst decade on a positive note.
   In his keynote address this morning, Lane Kirkland, president of
the labor federation, invoked the convention theme of solidarity in
promising a rebound for labor in the 1990s.
   ``Solidarity has been our shield against the most primitive and
the most sophisticated attacks by the agents of avarice and
exploitation,'' Kirkland said, sounding a more militant stance
toward future organizing and bargaining.
   ``We will not take no for a permanent answer,'' he said. ``And
we will not pull away from any struggle.''
   Kirkland also invoked the words of his predecessor, George
Meany, in defining labor's objective.
   ``The key role of the trade union is to see that the big guys
don't kick the little guys around,'' Kirkland told the more than
900 delegates. ``They need it now more than ever when the legacy of
the Reagan years exacting its cost in all walks of life.''
   Delegates to the 14.1 million-member federation's convention
will have a busy week: welcoming Solidarity leader Lech Walesa,
plotting future support for several major strikes and hearing from
a U.S. president for the first time in a decade.
   Also on tap are addresses by Democratic congressional leaders
and the election of the federation's officers, with Kirkland a
shoo-in for a sixth two-year term as president.
   Walesa's appearance to thank U.S. unions for their support in
Solidarity's struggle will be by far the most captivating public
event.
   Walesa will finally receive the George Meany Human Rights Award,
which the union bestowed on him eight years ago. He was not allowed
to leave Poland to receive it.
   Labor leaders will meet privately with Walesa to determine how
the AFL-CIO can assist Solidarity now that Poland has a
sympathetic, non-communist government, and how to emulate the
success of the Polish labor movement in other European countries,
such as East Germany, Hungary and Lithuania.
   ``We don't have to seek out our clients,'' Kirkland said in an
interview last week. ``They come to us. We are, in spite of what
our detractors say in this country, the largest, in many ways the
strongest, the most unified and the most deeply involved trade
union federation around the world.''
   The federation provided Solidarity with an estimated $5 million
worth of communications and other equipment and support.
   ``Wherever working people are trying to lift themselves up and
form free trade associations, they always come to us for help,''
Kirkland said. ``As these movements are developing in central and
Eastern Europe we are going to have increasing demands upon us and
we'll do our best to respond.''
   The celebration of the success abroad comes at a time of
uncertainty at home for the labor movement, which has struggled
throughout the 1980s with the losses in the industrial sector _ its
traditional organizing strength _ and its battle with the Reagan
administration over issues ranging from the minimum wage to child
care to plant closings.
   Kirkland just a month ago referred to President Bush as ``Reagan
Lite,'' but last week said the president's willingness to strike a
compromise on raising the minimum wage showed there had been some
improvement over the strained relations with the Reagan White House.
   ``We have channels of communication that I think are superior to
those that we had during the Reagan years,'' he said. ``Things are
not so ideologically hostile.''
   Bush has agreed to address the convention Wednesday.
   Reagan refused to speak in 1981 and was never invited again.
Jimmy Carter was the last president to address a federation
convention, in 1979.
   The celebration of Walesa's first visit to the United States
will be coupled with welcoming back the United Mine Workers,
rejoining the federation 40 years after the legendary John L. Lewis
pulled out because of a political fight.
   The reception of the UMW, however, also serves to underscore the
renewed move toward militancy by major unions.
   The UMW's strike against Pittston Coal Group is one of four that
will receive the attention of the delegates, beginning today when
the convention's theme of Solidarity is underscored by a procession
of workers on strike against Pittston, Eastern Airlines, NYNEX
Corp. and Boeing.
   Kirkland and other labor leaders believe unions have turned the
corner in organizing the growth sectors of the economy _
particularly health care and the service industries _ but
increasingly are supporting hard-line stands to prevent further
erosion of labor's numbers in the areas of its traditional strength.
   ``I think we're coming out of a very difficult period in
remarkably good shape and with the highest degree of internal
solidarity and cohesiveness than we've ever had,'' Kirkland said in
the interview.
   In his report to the delegates, however, he sounded a more
strident and militant note: ``If we are to advance in this hostile
climate, there is only one way for trade unionists to turn, and
that is to each other.''
</TEXT>
