<SECOND>PM-Successful Project,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Project Touted as Success Story in Drug War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Rhode Island congresswoman today led a
deputy to national drug czar William Bennett through a housing
project that is being touted as a success story in the war on drugs.
   ``This (project) is a clear example of leadership _ cooperation
among tenants ... and pride,'' said Rep. Claudine Schneider,
R-R.I., after officials presented a 15-minute videotape about the
Galago Court Housing Project's $6 million renovation.
   Housing project residents peered out of their doors as the
government officials and reporters pulled up for a news conference
and tour. Some joked about their status as a success story.
   ``How many times have we seen this?'' one tenant asked as the
tape was shown.
   Judge Reggie Walton, deputy director of the Office of National
Drug Control Policy, praised the housing authority's efforts.
   ``Any initiative regarding public housing has to take into
account the drug and crime problem,'' Walton said.
   Galago Court will receive an award from the U.S. Department of
Housing and Urban Development for the improvements during the past
three years there, Schneider said.
   The videotape outlined the 164-unit project's crime problems
before the renovations, including seven drug-related deaths in
seven years. The tape mentioned the ``cocaine dealers, thieves and
night people'' that frequented the area.
   Galago Court now has a security post at the entrance and
stricter review of those seeking apartments to keep dealers and
criminals from renting there. The review includes checking the
applicants' names with police records.
</TEXT>
