<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Mail     11-13 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Mail,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postmaster General Lauds Letter-Writing President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postmaster General Anthony Frank presented
President Bush with a letter carrier's cap and bag today as a
tribute to Bush's prolific letter-writing, then delivered a jesting
notice about the bill to taxpayers for the postage.
   ``One of the traits for which you've become well known is
writing brief congratulatory thank-you messages,'' Frank told Bush
after the president gave opening remarks to an international postal
conclave.
   ``In fact, during your first year as the nation's chief
executive, you've generated more personal correspondence than many
other presidents during their entire administrations,'' Frank added.
   ``I'd like to point out, that every one of those has been
franked,'' said the postmaster general. A postal frank is free
postage provided by the taxpayers for the president and for members
of Congress.
   Bush, in his speech to the Universal Postal Union, noted that
``every week, I receive up to 60,000 letters from every state in
the union and from nearly every country in the world. You can get a
lot of free advice in this job.''
   The president also rattled off a few anecdotes of U.S. postal
history, including: ``In 1916, a 40,000-ton brick building was
mailed across Utah, brick by brick, because it was cheaper than the
freight charges.''
   But Frank later told the audience: ``I hope that people don't
remember your brick story. We really can't afford that.''
</TEXT>
