<FIRST>u a PM-KittyDukakis     11-13 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kitty Dukakis,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Describes Kitty Dukakis' Drinking Rubbing Alcohol as `A
Slip'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis today described his wife's
ingestion of rubbing alcohol as ``a slip'' and said decisions would
be made in the next few days about further treatment for her.
   Kitty Dukakis is a recovering alcoholic who has received
treatment for chemical dependency. ``Slip'' is a term used by
recovering alcoholics to describe a lapse back into drinking.
   ``Obviously my principal concern is making sure Kitty has the
opportunity to pursue her recovery with some privacy and some
space,'' said Dukakis, briefing reporters about his wife's health.
``The important thing is to get back on track.''
   The governor also said he had visited his wife at Brigham and
Women's Hospital today and that ``she is feeling much better.'' He
refused to answer reporters' questions.
   Dukakis said no decisions had been made yet as to further
treatment, but his wife would make them after consultation with her
doctors. ``Recovery is a lifelong process,'' he said.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 52, was brought to Brigham and Women's hospital by
ambulance Nov. 6. Her doctor said she suffered a ``severe
reaction'' from drinking rubbing alcohol.
   Experts on alcoholism say it is not unusual for an alcoholic to
drink rubbing alcohol, hair spray or other products containing
alcohol when the craving hits and liquor is not available.
   Hospital officials referred all calls about Mrs. Dukakis'
condition to the governor's press office. Last week, her doctor,
Gerald Plotkin, said Mrs. Dukakis was ``completely out of danger.''
   Dukakis' press secretary, Mindy Lubber, said today she did not
know when Mrs. Dukakis would be released.
   Plotkin said shortly after she was hospitalized that Mrs.
Dukakis was taking prescription anti-depressants. But Plotkin said
no other drugs, medication, or alcoholic beverages were involved in
her recent hospitalization.
   Mrs. Dukakis was treated for alcoholism at a Rhode Island
treatment center in March. At the beginning of her husband's
presidential campaign, Mrs. Dukakis disclosed a 26-year addiction
to diet pills.
   Plotkin said fall has always been a bad time for Mrs. Dukakis,
who has suffered from depression for years.
</TEXT>
