<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Prostitution,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Draws Up Plans For Major Crackdown On Prostitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government plans a major crackdown on
prostitution and ``other repulsive deeds,'' China's top security
official was quoted as saying Monday.
   Public Security Minister Wang Fang said the wide-ranging program
will punish all who copy or sell pornography; engage in
prostitution; produce, sell or use drugs; gamble, or conduct
superstitious activities for a profit.
   ``Foreign visitors will also be punished if they are found to be
involved in prostitution and other repulsive deeds,'' Wang was
quoted as saying the the official Xinhua News Agency.
   Wang did not disclose details of the planned sweep but said it
would go into effect soon.
   ``It has got to the point that such bad things must be wiped
out,'' Xinhua quoted Liu Gan, secretary general of the State
Council, China's Cabinet, as saying.
   Chinese prosecutors have approved the arrests of 11,503
criminals involved in such illegal activities in the first nine
months of 1989, Xinhua said.
