<FIRST>u w PM-SeabrookEvacuation 1stLd-Writethru a0530 11-13 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seabrook Evacuation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Panel Approves Massachusetts Evacuation Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf, Although Massachusetts, to CORRECT figure to
$6.3 billion sted $6.5 billion; inserts 2 grafs of background on plant
after 6th graf, Shannon has</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal advisory panel said today it has
approved evacuation plans for Massachusetts communities near the
Seabrook, N.H., nuclear power plant and recommended that the
embattled facility receive a full-power license.
   The Atomic Safety and Licensing Board overruled the objections
of Massachusetts officials and environmental groups and said
evacuation plans for residents of six northeastern Massachusetts
communities are adequate to protect public safety.
   The board also ruled that an evacuation exercise conducted last
year in Massachusetts and New Hampshire ``was adequate in scope and
revealed no fundamental flaw.''
   Although Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon can appeal
the decision within 10 days, the $6.3 billion reactor could receive
a full-power license even before the appeals run their course, said
Nuclear Regulatory Commission spokesman John Kopeck. Seabrook
officials have said they expect the plant to be licensed around the
first of next year.
   The next step in the complex process involves a 30-day review
period by the NRC, a public hearing held by the full commission at
which the NRC staff makes its recommendations on the plant and a
final decision on issuing a license by the commission.
   Shannon has already said he would appeal a ruling by the
licensing board to the higher-level Atomic Safety and Licensing
Appeal Board and from there to the full NRC. If, as Shannon said he
expects, the NRC decides to issue a full-power license, he has said
he will challenge that ruling in federal court.
   Completion of the plant was delayed by nearly a decade by legal
challenges by environmentists, cost overruns, changes required
during construction and financial problems encountered by the
facility's principal owner, Public Service Co. of New Hampshire.
   The plant originally was projected to cost $1 billion and go
into service in 1979.
   In its 571-page ruling dated Nov. 9 and made public today, the
three-member licensing board found ``reasonable assurance that
adequate protective measures can and will be taken in the event of
a radiological emergency at the Seabrook station, in accordance
with the commission's emergency planning regulations and precedents
....''
   The licensing board cleared away another potential obstacle to
swift issuance of a full-power license by ruling that a recent
appeal board decision on the New Hampshire evacuation plans posed
no major problem in the licensing process.
   Several flaws in the New Hampshire plans found by the appeal
board, ``do not preclude the immediate issuance of an operating
license for the Seabrook station,'' the board said.
   Plant spokesman Ron Sher called the decision a ``major
development that brings Seabrook closer to a full-power license.''
   He added: ``The emergency plans for Seabrook have been evaluated
by the experts _ the Federal Emergency Management Agency, the staff
of the NRC and the Advisory Committee on Reactor Safeguards _ and
their conclusions are that Seabrook's emergency plans are among the
best in the country.''
   Sher said that only in the event of a highly unlikely site
emergency or general emergency at the plant would the plans
involving warning sirens, radio broadcasts and possible evacuation
of school children, residents and tourists swing into action.
   The evacuation plans for Massachusetts involve six communities
in the northeastern corner of the state, just south of the Seabrook
plant: Amesbury, Merrimack, Newbury, Newburyport, Salisbury and
West Newbury. Total population of the region is about 50,000 with a
peak of about 90,000 during the summer months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
