<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Germany-Poll     11-13 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Poll,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Respondents Say Gorbachev Most Responsible for Wall's Demise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans and West Germans give Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev the most credit for the moves that
led to the opening of the Berlin Wall last week, new polls say, but
skepticism remains strong about the future of reform in Eastern
Europe.
   Polls in the United States and West Germany conducted for USA
Today found citizens in both countries are splintered over whether
reforms should lead to the withdrawal of U.S. troops from Europe.
   Asked who should get the most credit for bringing about the
opening of the Berlin Wall, West Germans were emphatic: 70 percent
named the Soviet leader. Gorbachev was most often named by
Americans as well, picked by 43 percent.
   Among Germans, East German leader Egon Krenz was named by six
percent; West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl by 5 percent; President
Bush, 3 percent; and former President Reagan, 2 percent. Among
Americans, Reagan was picked by 14 percent; Krenz, 9 percent; Kohl,
6 percent; and Bush, 5 percent. The remainder in both cases named
others or did not give a choice.
   The poll in the United States was conducted by telephone by
Gordon S. Black Corp., and is based on interviews with 805 adults.
   The poll in West Germany is based on interviews with 1,005
adults and was conducted by EMNID Institut. The U.S. poll has a
sampling error margin of 4 percentage points. The Germany survey
has a 3 percentage point margin.
   Citizens of both countries are optimistic about the changes in
East Germany, but a substantial number of Germans think the
Communists will crack down. Fifty-one percent of the West Germans
think recent events in the East are the beginning of an open
society, but 39 percent said the communists are ``buying time
before a crackdown.''
   Among Americans, 70 percent think the moves are the beginning of
an open society and only 15 percent expect a crackdown. The rest in
each case didn't know.
   Asked whether the United States should withdraw its troops from
Europe if the reforms continue, half of the Americans and 42
percent of the Germans said U.S. troop levels should not be
changed. Forty-four percent of the Americans and 52 percent of the
Germans said at least some reductions should be made in troop
levels.
</TEXT>
