<FIRST>r a PM-DoubleShooting     11-13 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Double Shooting,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspapers Cite Possible Suspect in Couple's Abduction-Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say no arrests have been made in the
shootings of a pregnant woman and her husband, whose car phone led
police to the couple, but published reports say a key suspect in
the case is in custody for other crimes.
   William Bennett, 39, of Boston's Mission Hill section, where
Carol and Charles Stuart were abducted and shot last month, has
been identified by police sources as a suspect in that shooting,
newspapers said.
   Mrs. Stuart and her infant son, delivered prematurely by
Caesarian section, both died. Stuart remains hospitalized.
   Bennett was arrested Saturday on a traffic violation and
appeared in court in Charlestown and Brookline today.
   The Charlestown case was postponed and Bennett then was taken to
Brookline, where he is a suspect in a video store holdup. At the
Brookline arraignment he pleaded innocent and was held in lieu of
$350,000 bond.
   Joel Goodman, Bennett's attorney in the Brookline case, said
``not a word has been said to me by the police or district
attorney's office as to whether my client is a suspect in the
Stuart shooting.''
   Judith Lindahl, who represented Bennett on the Charlestown
traffic charge, declined to comment when asked if her client were a
suspect in the Stuart shooting.
   ``There is sufficient publicity in the case to deny my client a
fair trial,'' she said.
   The Boston Sunday Globe said both Stuart and the victims at the
video store told police the gunman had a distinctive raspy voice
and a scruffy, spotty beard, and gave similar discriptions of the
handgun he used.
   Police spokesman Jim Jordan said it was department policy not to
comment on suspects until someone is charged.
   The Boston Sunday Herald cited unidentified police sources as
saying Bennett was a chief suspect in the Stuarts' shooting.
   Joseph Dunford, deputy chief of detectives for Boston Police,
said Sunday he had no comment on the Herald article.
   Pauline Bennett, the man's mother, said her son was a suspect in
the Stuarts' shooting, the Herald said.
   ``They say he's a suspect. He's been in trouble before. He knew
he was a suspect. He was nervous and upset about it,'' Ms. Bennett
said.
   Bennett's girlfriend, Faye Nelson, of Burlington, told the Sun
of Lowell in a telephone interview that he didn't attack the
Stuarts. ``He was here when everything occurred,'' she said.
   The Stuarts were abducted just as they were leaving Brigham and
Womens' Hospital, where they had attended a birthing class, and
forced to drive to a street where they were robbed and shot. Stuart
called police on his car's cellular phone, and when he lost
consciousness emergency operators located him by listening for
police car sirens heard over the phone.
   Stuart, 29, was listed in stable condition in intensive care
after surgery Saturday at Boston City Hospital; hospital officials
would not give a reason for the surgery.
</TEXT>
