<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1401EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Scene Bjt   11-13 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Scene, Bjt,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Berliners Wake to Reality of a Gray Monday After Epic Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BER7,BER13,BER17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For East Berliner Peter Normann, Monday was a
return to reality after a heady weekend of freedom celebrations.
   ``Now things must go back to normal,'' the 32-year-old
construction worker said as he took a cigarette break on the site
of a new office complex and glanced at the Berlin Wall less than
100 yards away.
   Other East Berliners braving the gray morning chill on their way
to the office, work bench or factory floor shared Normann's view
that the party was over.
   In all, more than 3 million East Germans headed west during the
weekend, and officials said 99 percent of them then returned home.
   The euphoria of the weekend _ many young East Berliners had
never been to the West until then _ was tinged with worry for some.
Money and the East German economy were among common concerns.
   ``I really don't know whether I should be happy or pensive,''
said Michael Werner, gunning his massive Volga taxi through a
yellow light shortly after picking up a Western visitor on a
near-deserted main thoroughfare.
   Most streets appeared normally quiet, but there was lively
traffic going both ways at the Checkpoint Charlie crossing point.
Werner pointed to long lines at several banks and police precinct
stations as evidence that things were not the same.
   People were filling out forms for visas to go west or queuing to
buy the annual allotment of 15 West German marks allowed them by
the state for visits to West Berlin.
   Werner was born Sept. 21, 1961 _ a little more than a month
after East German military and paramilitary units began work on the
wall. He crossed over to West Berlin for the first time early
Friday, just hours after the Communist East Berlin government eased
travel restrictions.
   After queuing in West Berlin for more than an hour, he was given
100 West German marks ($54) in ``welcome money.'' That was a small
treasure compared with the annual entitlement allowed by his
government, but Werner didn't spend a pfennig.
   ``I didn't know what to do,'' he confided sheepishly. ``Things
cost so much over there, and then there are differences in prices
depending on which store you go to. It's not like over here.''
   Money for the West also was carpenter Dieter Voelcov's worry, as
he finished a hearty breakfast of Bauernschmaus _ an omelette with
diced ham and potatoes _ at the Nordring Bier Bar in the heart of
the city.
   While the East German mark is not freely convertible, many West
Berlin stores accepted them over the weekend. But their rate of one
West mark to 10 East marks irritated some East Berliners.
   ``What am I going to do with 100 West marks a year, if I can go
over as often as I want,'' he groused, wiping beer foam off his
mustache. ``The freedom to travel is our main theme at work, but we
always come back to the same thing, where to get hard currency.''
   Co-worker Dieter Boy agreed, suggesting that East Germany was at
the mercy of the economic powerhouse of the West _ one of the
excuses offered by the Communists for building the wall in the
first place.
   ``If this continues, the West is going to buy us out!''
exclaimed Boy, a stocky 28-year-old. ``We're either all going to
end up working over there, or we'll spend anything we make here on
the other side of the wall.''
   The everyday frustrations of Monday in East Berlin came home to
a man in line for oranges _ brought in once a year from Spain in
time for Christmas _ who was told the oranges had run out.
   ``This is what socialism looks like!'' he exclaimed bitterly to
those standing behind him. ``We still have a long way to go,
despite the weekend.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0565 11-13 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0565,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoss Named Prime Minister, Aoun Calls Choice Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs with later Aoun comment; picks up 9th `Mouawad,
64'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon's new president designated
veteran Moslem politician Salim Hoss as prime minister Monday and
Gen. Michel Aoun, the Christian army commander, rejected the choice.
   Hoss and Aoun have led rival Moslem and Christian governments
since the six-year term of President Amin Gemayel ended in
September 1988 with Parliament unable to agree on a successor.
   Aoun issued a statement Monday saying the Hoss nomination was
``as unconstitutional as the election'' Nov. 5 of President Rene
Mouawad.
   The session at which Parliament elected Mouawad and endorsed a
peace plan was held in Syrian-controlled north Lebanon because Aoun
threatened to shell the parliament building in Beirut.
   Mouawad, a Christian, instructed Hoss to form a national
reconciliation government with the mission of ending the
14-year-old sectarian civil war, in which more than 150,000 people
have been killed.
   Police reported exchanges of artillery and small-arms fire
across Beirut's sectarian dividing line between Aoun's Christian
army units and Moslem militias backed by Syria. Each side accused
the other of starting the battle and no casualty reports were
available.
   A six-month artillery war between Aoun's men and a Moslem
alliance led by the Syrians killed at least 930 people and wounded
2,744 before a truce arranged by the Arab League ended it in
September.
   Syria has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate issued in 1976, the year after the war began.
Aoun calls the Syrians an occupation force and has declared a ``war
of liberation'' to drive them out.
   Later Monday, Aoun said: ``This will be an unconstitutional
government. It will not be a national reconciliation government; it
will represent one side. ``Even if the whole world recognizes it,
Hoss' government will be a government operating in the shadow of
Syrian occupation. Governments cannot survive only on foreign
recognition.''
   Aoun spoke to The Associated Press in his bunker beneath the
shattered presidential palace in Baabda, east of Beirut, which he
has refused to leave since Mouawad's election.
   Mouawad, 64, designated Hoss, 59, a Sunni Moslem, after three
days of consultations with political leaders.
   Hoss accepted the job for the third time in 13 years and said
the 55th government since independence from France in 1943 would
implement the peace accord worked out in Taif, Saudia Arabia, which
includes a plan for sharing power between Christians and Moslems.
   Christians were the majority in 1943 and have controlled the
government, army and judiciary, but Moslems now account for about
55 percent of the population and have demanded an equal role in
running the country.
   Mouawad, Hoss and Hussein Husseini, the Shiite Moslem who is
speaker of Parliament, received about 50 foreign ambassadors at the
president's temporary headquarters _ the prime minister's office in
Moslem west Beirut.
   ``I call upon all of you to join our march toward peace,''
Mouawad said in a seven-minute address. ``We consider the Taif
accord an introduction to peace and a launching pad for a new
republic based on equality among all Lebanese.
   ``I pledge to whole world to consolidate the unity and
sovereignty of Lebanon and to rebuild its constitutional
institutions.''
   The United States was not represented at the meeting, which
underscored international recognition of Mouawad, because its
embassy was closed Sept. 6 after Aoun supporters put it under siege.
   Iran boycotted the meeting. The Iranians and the Hezbollah
militia, their main ally in Lebanon, have rejected the Taif accord
because it does not give the major say in government to the 1.2
million Shiites, the largest sect in Lebanon.
   Hoss first became prime minister under the late President Elias
Sarkis, soon after the Syrian army intervention in 1976. He
returned to the post when Prime Minister Rashid Karami was
assassinated in June 1, 1987.
</TEXT>
