<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-EastGermany 1stLd-Writethru a0427 11-13 0965</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-East Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Says Most East German Won't Move</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 15 grafs new with White House, Quayle comments tdoay; picks
up 3rd graf pvs, ``Tonight, Bush; cuts from bottom to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House today hailed the ``glorious''
sight of people exercising new freedoms in East Germany, but said
``we can understand and even expect'' that most East Germans will
stay and help rebuild their country rather than flee.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater also virtually ruled out any
possibility that President Bush will add a stopover in Berlin to
next month's shipboard meeting with Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev in the Mediterreanean off Malta.
   The White House has emphasized the informality of that meeting.
Fitzwater said today the leaders will use it ``to give a push to
all the talks'' on both nuclear and conventional arms control.
   However, ``we do not intend to have this emerge as a second
Yalta,'' he said, referring to the 1945 meeting where Franklin
Roosevelt, Winston Churchill and Josef Stalin met to carve up the
boundaries of post-war Europe.
   On the dramatic events in East Germany, Fitzwater said, ``One of
the most glorious aspects of this weekend's activities was seeing
so many people not only discover but exercise those freedoms for
the first time.''
   But when asked by reporters what advice Bush would give the
masses of East Germans who eventually returned to their side of the
border, the spokesman replied:
   ``We won't encourage them one way or another, except as the
president did last Friday and say in these times of dramatically
changing reform, events are so exciting and so many possibilities
on the horizon, we can certainly understand and even expect that
most East Germans would want to be a part of this change.''
   Meanwhile today, Vice President Dan Quayle told a gathering of
Republican governors on Hilton Head Island, S.C., that the eventual
reunification of Germany is inevitable and that when it comes, the
rejoined nation will be ``allied with the forces of freedom and
democracy, which is the West.''
   Quayle disputed complaints by Democrats that Bush has been timid
in dealing with change at home and abroad, contending that all they
want to do is spend more money.
   ``The Democrats haven't offered one creative idea on how to
manage the evolving situation in Eastern Europe or the Soviet Union
except to criticize the president,'' Quayle said in an interview
after his speech. He said the administration has been properly
cautious but still ``out front on this issue.''
   On the Dec. 2-3 meeting with Gorbachev, Fitzwater said, ``We do
not intend to have this emerge as a second Yalta. And we do not
intend to engage in the kinds of decision-making that would lead
you to that kind of conclusion.''
   But he added, ``I think they want to give a push to all the
talks. ... You're going to see them emerge and urge progress on CFE
(conventional forces in Europe) and START (strategic arms
reduction) and all the arms control talks.''
   ``It clearly is an effort to provide progress in these areas.
But that's far different than negotiating specific points,''
Fitzwater said.
   Asked about the possibility that Bush would visit Berlin, the
spokesman said, ``We can't foresee any set of circumstances at this
moment that would induce him to go.''
   He said the president is still weighing a reply to a message
Gorbachev sent Friday backing the changes made by East Germany's
new leaders and expressing hope that the situation will remain
peaceful.
   Tonight, Bush will present Lech Walesa with the Presidential
Medal of Freedom in a White House ceremony. Walesa is the
Solidarity leader whose labor movement propelled Poland into the
vanguard of the shift toward democracy in the communist East Bloc.
   On Sunday, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennadi Gerasimov
said of Bush's response to the joyous tumult in East Berlin: ``I
think he's handling it as a real statesman.''
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III emphasized that the
administration wants ``to encourage this move toward openness in
Eastern Europe,'' but ``to do so in a way that doesn't seek
unilateral advantage and ... doesn't promote instability.''
   Gerasimov, interviewed on CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation,''
predicted that Bush and Gorbachev, at their Dec. 2-3 shipboard
summit off Malta, ``may come to a common ground ... that both
countries _ and actually everybody _ is interested in stability, in
not too much upheaval in Europe.''
   Baker, on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley,'' called the
opening of East Germany's borders ``historic,'' but said, ``it
doesn't mean a whole lot in economic terms.''
   For the United States to consider coming to the economic aid of
East Germany, Baker said, it first must be convinced the rulers of
the once hard-line communist state are moving toward a free-market
system.
   ``It would be wrong to have a different standard for East
Germany than we do for Poland and Hungary,'' Baker said. ``We are
somewhat constrained in what we can do before there is clear
evidence that they want to reform their economic system.''
   Baker said he believes Moscow would draw the line at any attempt
by its East Bloc allies to withdraw from the Warsaw Pact, the
communist alliance's counterpart to the West's North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
   But, Baker said, ``they have made it very clear to us ... that
they will not use force in Eastern Europe.''
   Baker said the United States would welcome the eventual
reunification of the two Germanies ``as long as that reunification
comes about on the basis of Western values.'' But he stressed it is
too soon ``to make the great leap ... from right of free travel on
the part of East Germans to the question of reunification.''
</TEXT>
