<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Trial     11-13 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Trial,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial of Four Activists in Bratislava Opened</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four prominent human rights
activists went on trial Monday in Bratislava on charges of sedition
for urging Slovaks to lay flowers in memory of those killed in the
1968 Warsaw Pact invasion.
   Miroslav Kusy, Hana Ponicka, Anton Selecky and Vladimir Manak
were charged with sedition in August together with fellow human
rights activist Jan Carnogursky. The face as many as five years in
jail.
   The five signed a statement urging Slovaks to mark the 21st
anniversary of the Soviet-led Aug. 21, 1968 invasion, which crushed
Communist reform in Czechoslovakia.
   Kusy, a former Communist Party Central Committee secretary
during the 1968 Prague Spring reform period who was later expelled
from the party, also is charged with subversion.
   Carnogursky, who also faces sedition and subversion charges,
went on trial Nov. 6, but the proceedings were adjourned because
his defense lawyer suffered a circulatory collapse and could not
attend. No date was set for a new trial.
   Emigre sources in Vienna said that the defense on Monday asked
that the four be tried together with Carnogursky. The official CTK
news agency said the court heard the defendants but then adjourned
the proceedings until Tuesday.
   The trials epitomize a crackdown on dissent in Czechoslovakia,
whose hard-line Communist leaders have refused to follow the reform
path taken by other Warsaw Pact countries. Most Czechoslovak
leaders were installed after the 1968 invasion.
   In Poland, Hungary, the Soviet Union and now in East Germany,
Communists have either agreed to share power or at least permitted
opposition groups to publicize their opinions and hold large
demonstrations.
   Czechoslovakia has taken one of the hardest lines against
dissent. Last month, baton-wielding police in Prague dispersed up
to 10,000 demonstrators who called for freedom and a new government.
   Still, active opposition is growing slowly. The activists'
trials in Bratislava have sparked considerable protest even from
some establishment intellectuals and last week about 200 people
demonstrated outside Bratislava's Palace of Justice to demand
Carnogursky's release. They also chanted calls for freedom and
human rights.
</TEXT>
