<FIRST>u a PM-ValukasResigns     11-13 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Valukas Resigns,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anton Valukas, U.S. Attorney for Northern Illinois, Stepping Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas announced today that
he will resign next month to return to private practice.
   Valukas, 45, appointed federal prosecutor for northern Illinois
in 1985 by President Reagan, oversaw the cases against 46 traders
accused earlier this year of fradulent trading practices at the
Chicago Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   He also oversaw a probe of City Hall corruption in Chicago and
the recent wave of indictments against El Rukn gang members. He
also directed a follow-up of many of the cases stemming from
Operation Greylord, an extensive probe of Cook County court
corruption.
   Valukas said in a statement he will resign effective Dec. 3 to
return to the law firm Jenner and Block, where he practiced before
taking the federal post.
   He could not be reached immediately for comment at his office. A
secretary said he was not in.
   No successor has been named by President Bush.
