<FIRST>u w AM-DrugPlane Bjt   11-13 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Plane, Bjt,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Says Customs Should Fix Planes or Refuse New Ones</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Customs Service should not buy any more
frontline radar planes for detecting drug-ferrying aircraft until
electronics problems are resolved, the chairman of a Senate
appropriations panel said Monday.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, chairman of the Appropriations
subcommittee that funded the purchase of P-3 airborne early warning
aircraft, said Customs must get the two planes already in service
operating fully by March or refuse delivery of a third plane in
April.
   ``If they don't fix it, I'm going to come down on them hard,''
said DeConcini, D-Ariz., chairman of the Senate Appropriations
subcommittee on Treasury, Postal Service and General Government.
   DeConcini said Customs Service aircrews have told him that
problems in tracking and locating suspect planes are not being
addressed. ``What we may have is a breakdown where supervisors have
not responded to these complaints,'' he said in an interview.
   ``If they don't adhere to the suggestion (to fix the problems or
postpone delivery), I'll have a hearing and it won't be pleasant.
I'm very interested, being the chairman of the funding committee,
in not letting a new contract when we don't have one that works.''
   Customs Service documents show that the planes have been plagued
by an unreliable computer system that has trouble pinpointing the
location of targets and following their course and speed; faulty
on-board communications for the crew, and problems with a spinning,
metal radar dome. Most documents were written by crewmen at
Customs' Surveillance Support Center in Corpus Christi, Texas,
where the radar planes are based.
   The acting director of the Customs Service surveillance center,
Peter Kendig, has acknowledged there are a ``few glitches'' in the
computer systems, but said the P-3 aircraft ``works and it works
great.'' He said the two planes now flying were mainly responsible
for detections leading to 36 arrests from Jan. 1 to Aug. 10 this
year, seizures of 37,000 pounds of marijuana and 8,300 pounds of
cocaine as well as vessels, aircraft and vehicles.
   The Lockheed P-3 is a four-engine turboprop that was built for
detecting enemy submarines, but two of them were outfitted with the
most sophisticated electronics available and sold to the Customs
Service to detect airborne drug smugglers. Lockheed hopes to sell
the P-3 as a surveillance plane to other countries for military
use, as a competitor to existing detection aircraft.
   The first P-3 airborne early warning aircraft was delivered in
June 1988 at a cost of more than $27 million, and the second
arrived last April at a price of $30.6 million. The third plane is
scheduled to be delivered to the Customs Service next April at a
cost of $35 million, money already appropriated by Congress.
   The major electronics problem documented in Customs memos _ and
in interviews with Customs Service sources and Lockheed officials _
is the computerized tracker. The equipment is designed to
automatically plot the course and speed of a suspect aircraft, but
it is sometimes so inaccurate that the P-3 cannot reliably guide
interceptors to the suspected smugglers, according to Customs
service memos and interviews with agency sources.
   Lockheed's airborne early warning program manager, John
McGinnis, has said in interviews he hopes ``anomalous behavior'' in
the tracker will be fixed by ``the first of the year.'' He
contended that despite the discrepancies, ``The airplane and the
tracker are very capable and doing their job.''
   Meanwhile, Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., who has guided the P-3
program through the House, said the House Government Operations
Committee on which he serves will ask the General Accounting Office
to investigate the program. He also has asked Chairman John
Conyers, D-Mich., to schedule hearings.
</TEXT>
