<DOCNO> AP891113-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     11-13 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Kill Leader of Sinhalese Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities shot and killed the
captured leader of the Sinhalese anti-government uprising Monday,
the foreign minister said, despite previously guaranteeing his
safety.
   Government security officers killed Rohana Wijeweera, founder
and leader of the Sinhalese extremist People's Liberation Front, at
his group's Colombo headquarters, Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne
said.
   Wijeweera had led soldiers to the headquarters where another
member of the front fired a revolver at him, Wijeratne said. The
soldiers opened fire, killing Wijeweera and the other member, H.B.
Herath.
   A political leader considered sympathetic to the People's
Liberation Front warned that Wijeweera's death would lead to more
violence.
   ``The killing, if it is true, will certainly escalate violence
in the country because you can kill a man but not an ideology,''
said Samuel Dias Bandaranaike, leader of the Sri Lanka Progressive
Front.
   ``The people will not believe the government's version of the
killing of Wijeweera,'' he said. ``The killing took place after
President (Ranasinghe) Premadasa repeatedly guaranteed his personal
safety.''
   Premadasa has made repeated overtures to Wijeweera and the front
to cease violence and open talks with the government, but the
offers have been rejected.
   Wijeweera and Herath were cremated under emergency regulations
that allow security forces to dispose of bodies without a post
mortem, said Wijeratne, who is also the deputy defense minister.
Premadasa has ordered an inquiry into the shooting, he said.
   Authorities captured Wijeweera along with his wife and five
children Sunday in the central district of Kandy, Wijeratne said.
He was brought to Colombo where he cooperated with interrogators
and voluntarily videotaped a speech appealing for peace, Wijeratne
said.
   The People's Liberation Front has been waging a campaign of
terror and assassination since 1987 in its bid to overthrow the
Sinhalese-dominated government. The violence has escalated in
recent months with hundreds of suspected members of the group
killed by pro-government vigilante groups in revenge attacks.
   The government says 6,000 people have been killed in the
confrontation.
   The People's Liberation Front has attacked the government
because it claims too many concessions had been given to the Tamil
minority in an effort to halt a separatist insurrection in the
Tamil-dominated northeast.
   Sinhalese form 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
control the government and the military. Tamils, who make up 18
percent of the population, have been fighting for an independent
nation since 1983, complaining of discrimination in jobs and
education by the Sinhalese. The Tamil separatist war has claimed at
least 11,000 lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
