<FIRST>u a AM-People     11-13 0914</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0948</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Michael Jackson spent an evening at the
circus with a 4-year-old leukemia victim whose father earlier
triggered a court-ordered manhunt when he spirited the child away
from chemotherapy treatment.
   Darian Pagan of Brooklyn, and his family spent Saturday evening
in Santa Monica, Calif., with Jackson, 31, courtesy of a Long
Island-based charity, New York Newsday said in Monday's editions.
   Jackson, 31, his shoulder-length hair in curls, wore a black hat
and a black jacket with black-sequined cuffs and epaulets.
   ``He's shy, just like me,'' said the reclusive entertainer. ``It
makes me proud that this is his dream. I'm happy to fulfill it.''
   ``It's part of my gift to make everybody happy and to bring joy
to everyone, especially children like this,'' Jackson said. ``My
dream is to do a tour and see all the world's children, all the
hungry kids. Imagine that,'' he said.
   ``Just seeing his reaction made my day,'' David Pagan said
later, holding his sleeping son after Jackson left with two
shaved-head bodyguards.
   When officials from the charity, Wish is Granted, called, the
child's mother, Migdalia Pagan turned down offers of a bedroom set
or a Nintendo game. ``He wants to meet Michael Jackson,'' she said
she told them.
   Darian mimics Jackson's moonwalk dance step and watches his
music videos over and over, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matt Frewer, the offbeat actor whose
wackiness helped him pull off the lead in TV's innovative ``Max
Headroom'' series, has another vehicle for his warped antics _ the
CBS comedy ``Doctor, Doctor.''
   It isn't clear where Frewer leaves off and his TV character, Dr.
Mike Stratford, begins. His maniacal laugh punctuates his
conversation.
   ``I think I got my sense of humor from my dad. He's pretty
weird, too,'' said Frewer. Six episodes of ``Doctor, Doctor'' ran
during the summer and CBS returned it to the lineup this week.
   Frewer's character has a bizarre bedside manner. He's a
fledgling novelist and a clumsy talk show doctor, the creation of
``My Favorite Year'' writer Norman Steinberg.
   ``I happened to be looking for a vehicle to go bananas in, and
Norman called and said that he had this new show and that I could
ad lib and improvise any time I wanted,'' said Frewer. ``That's not
an offer you get every day in a series, and it's a tribute to
Norman. He's secure enough that his words aren't sacred.''
   Frewer describes his Stratford character as a ``guy who has
trouble keeping his head above water because he has too much on his
plate.''
   ``But he never gets too deep that he can't find the humor in any
situation,'' he added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laura Lord Scales, the oldest living
graduate of Smith College _ born when Rutherford B. Hayes was in
the White House _ turned 110 Monday, but she didn't see what all
the fuss was about.
   ``My age is absurd. I don't know where I get it,'' a frail but
vibrant Mrs. Scales said at a meeting Sunday with Smith President
Mary Maples Dunn.
   Mrs. Scales, who served as dean of students at the selective
women's college for 22 years, remains alert and still takes the
occasional stroll on fine afternoons. She lives at a retirement
home just a few miles from the campus she was a part of for so long.
   ``I am pretty sick today,'' she said. ``I wanted to make sure I
sound intelligent.'' In fact, the white-haired graduate, her face
framed by sturdy black spectacles, demonstrated a keen awareness,
asking about new developments at Smith and the welfare of ``the
girls.''
   Dunn congratulated the 1901 Phi Beta Kappa graduate on her
longevity and service to Smith. ``You are our most senior
citizen,'' she said.
   ``I hadn't thought of that,'' Mrs. Scales replied.
   She got a birthday card from President Bush, a letter from Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis and the introduction of a citation in the state
Legislature.
   Mrs. Scales was planning a low-key celebration, said Dorothea
Munro, an administrator at the retirement home.
   ``She said she's had too many birthdays anyway,'' Munro said.
``She said `I'll just come out for the dessert.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EST. Time set by source.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Willard Scott says he's a success on NBC's
``Today'' show because he's not afraid to clown around.
   ``Fall on your face, tell a dumb joke, be a little bit of a
buffoon,'' Scott said in the Nov. 18 issue of TV Guide. ``Even
though people will just barely tolerate you and almost
embarrassingly shake their heads and say, `My God!' they'll always
invite you to the party.''
   Scott has appeared on air wearing only a barrel and dressed as
Carmen Miranda.
   ``I do make some stupid mistakes and say some dumb things, but
there's an honesty. And people know that I love them and that I
love what I do. And that's the secret,'' Scott said.
   When the weather forecaster from Washington, D.C., was first
hired, mail was so negative, the NBC staff hid it from Scott.
   ``Today'' co-anchor Jane Pauley said Scott overcame that initial
rejection.
   ``In the beginning, he was the cornball with his 100-year-old
birthdays,'' she said. ``It was an act no one with any pretense of
sophistication would buy. But that only lasted about three days _
one by one they fell. He simply resonates with such a broad range
of people.''
</TEXT>
