<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Police     11-13 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Police,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Police Officer Arrested, Suspended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident policeman who accused
riot squad members of brutality was arrested and suspended from the
force Monday after leading a protest against orders to transfer him.
   One other policeman and 11 prison guards who recently joined a
new union headed by Lt. Gregory Rockman also were arrested at the
demonstration. Police Commissioner Hennie de Witt said the second
policeman also was suspended.
   All 13 were released without bail after brief court appearances
where they were not charged. They are scheduled to reappear Nov. 23.
   Three private citizens were arrested at the demonstration and
released on bail. Eight journalists covering their protest were
detained for two hours, then freed. They included a camera crew
from ABC News.
   The dissident security officers were protesting in the
mixed-race township of Mitchell's Plain, Rockman's hometown,
against police orders to transfer him to a quartermaster's unit in
a white area of Cape Town. Rockman is mixed-race.
   Police also ordered the transfer of Col. John Manuel, the
commander of the Mitchell's Plain police station, who had supported
Rockman.
   De Witt said Rockman failed to report for duty Monday at the
quartermaster's office, rejecting a transfer that was ``in the
interests of good order and discipline.''
   The arrests occurred after Rockman and the other dissident
officers marched through a shopping area of Mitchell's Plain,
chanting in support of their union and against Rockman's transfer
order.
   After the court appearance, supporters carried Rockman on their
shoulders to a public square and shouted, ``Viva Rockman!''
   Rockman become an overnight hero to militant youths in
September, when he accused members of an all-white police riot
squad of behaving like ``wild dogs'' when they beat anti-election
protesters. That protest occurred at the same shopping plaza where
Rockman was arrested Monday.
   Two white officers were charged with assault in the September
incident. They were acquitted last month, but the judge criticized
the behavior of some men in the unit.
</TEXT>
