<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Pay     11-13 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Pay,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nader, Common Cause Diverge on Raise Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KMOAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer activist Ralph Nader and the
president of Common Cause disagreed Monday on whether Congress
should take a proposed 33 percent pay hike, with Nader saying he'll
enlist talk-show hosts in his bid to kill the raise.
   Nader, who early this year successfully fought a proposed 51
percent pay hike, told reporters that Congress was ``at it again''
despite widespread public opposition to the earlier proposal.
   He said about 600 radio talk-show hosts would be contacted to
stir up opposition to the pay plan before leaders of the House can
bring it to a vote, perhaps late this week. The earlier raise
proposal was a favorite topic on talk shows.
   The new pay plan is more modest, with a 7.7 percent pay raise in
January and a 25 percent increase in January 1991. The raises would
apply to members of Congress, who are paid $89,500, and to top
executive branch officials and federal judges.
   The package was developed by a House bipartisan task force.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine said that a
majority of senators oppose the House plan and that the Senate
would consider accepting only the 7.7 percent January raise as a
cost-of-living adjustment.
   Congressional salaries were last increased in 1987, when
members' pay was raised from $77,400.
   The new increases would be tied to congressional ethics reforms,
including an end to members' padding their incomes by making
speeches to interest groups.
   Nader told a news conference he supported reform of
congressional ethics rules, but that should be done regardless of
the pay raise.
   ``I don't think people in this country like the idea of Congress
telling them that they will reform themselves only if they get a
pay increase,'' Nader said. ``That smells bad.''
   But Fred Wertheimer, president of Common Cause, said lawmakers
were entitled to a pay increase if they give up their other sources
of income, as would be required by the ethics reforms.
   ``Members of Congress should only be working for one employer _
the citizens of this country,'' said Wertheimer, whose organization
lobbies for more stringent ethics rules.
   Wertheimer said he expected public opposition to the raise.
``People don't like them as a general proposition.''
   ``My view is that it is very important now for the Congress to
look at the long-term consequences'' and not the ``momentary
reaction,'' he said.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., defended the plan but
declined to discuss details with reporters.
   Foley said the plan would be ready for unveiling Wednesday and
House leaders had no intention of trying to sneak anything past
them.
   ``As usual, Mr. Nader is wrong,'' Foley said. ``It won't be
coming up in the dead of night, snuck through without a vote.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     11-13 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROOKLYN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everyone's heard of Brooklyn, N.Y.
   Practically no one's heard of this Brooklyn, which consists of a
school and a tavern. And the tavern is closed.
   But Brooklyn, Wash., is having its day in the sun, even if it's
only because of name familiarity.
   The tiny town in the Willapa Hills of southwest Washington is
featured in a television commercial for Burgerville U.S.A.
   Also featured is Bob Tomisser, superintendent of North River
School.
   ``In Brooklyn, New York, you are conveniently located near Wall
Street, Yankee Stadium and Coney Island. Big Deal!'' Tomisser tells
the camera as he strolls out of the small school.
   ``You're also about 3,000 miles from one of these,'' he says,
holding up a large burger promoted in the 30-second spot.
   Then the camera pans back to Tomisser.
   ``Burgerville U.S.A. _ inconveniently located across the United
States,'' he says of the 31-restaurant chain in the Northwest.
   The commercial airs in Washington and Oregon, and Tomisser is
receiving royalties each time it's shown. Altogether, his one day's
work should bring in about $1,500.
   Incidentally, you can't get a Burgerville burger here, either.
The nearest Burgerville is nearly 100 miles away, in Centralia.
   The ad campaign for Burgerville plays off small towns that have
big-city counterparts.
   Another TV spot uses Detroit, Ore., in Oregon's Cascade
Mountains.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Third-grader Jessica Plank receives mail almost
daily from people she has never met in Winston-Salem, N.C.
   Last Friday was no exception. A correspondent sent a guidebook
and told her how the city's 300-year-old trees were destroyed by
Hurricane Hugo.
   Her fellow pupils get mail from other parts of the United States
in what has become a prodigious social studies project in the
third-grade class of Julia Shanabrook at Norman A. Trimmer
Elementary School in the West York Area School District.
   ``There are wonderful people in America who care enough about
strangers to go out, buy postcards, sit down and write to us,''
said Mrs. Shanabrook, 31, who has just begun teaching after
graduating from college.
   Each of the class' 25 students wrote to a newspaper editor in
two states requesting help in asking readers to send postcards and
share what makes their community special.
   On Friday, Mrs. Shanabrook distributed a 6-inch stack of mail
among the eager students. ``I get folders. I get boxes. I get
10-by-13-inch envelopes filled.''
   The mail helps the children learn about current events as well
as geography, she said.
   While the class has decided that ``Winston-Salem is probably the
most friendly town in the United States,'' Mrs. Shanabrook said
students had heard from people in 24 states.
   The children giggled at an Idaho postcard a picture of a single,
huge potato consuming the bed of a flatbed trailer.
   But Kushal Shah saw through the ruse.
   ``It's a regular potato,'' he said. ``They put it on a little
truck.''
   Twice one day last week students heard that Michigan is shaped
like a mitten. One person sent a foot-long mitten-shaped map.
Another wrote she lives in the thumb.
   Mrs. Shanabrook said a New Jersey television station producer
called about doing a story on what Morristown residents think is
special about their home. She told the producer ``they like General
Washington's headquarters.''
</TEXT>
