<HEAD>Lettuce Pickers Ratify New Contract, End Walkout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALINAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Field workers have ratified a new
contract with the nation's largest lettuce grower, ending an 18-day
strike that stalled the fall harvest.
   Bud of California, a subsidiary of the Castle &amp; Cooke
conglomerate, reportedly made a final offer that was similar to one
members of Teamsters Local 890 overwhelmingly rejected Nov. 2.
However, workers voted 2,240-248 for the ratification Sunday, said
union spokesman Raul Hernandez.
   Hernandez said workers agreed to the pact partly because of a
company commitment to increase the hours of senior employees. He
said many workers only worked three to four hours a day, and
sometimes only three days a week.
   Details of the agreement were not released. The company had
offered a raise of 8 cents an hour and overtime pay after nine
hours. Salvador Carrillo, Local 890 business agent, said workers
previously were paid $7.20 an hour.
