<FIRST>r a AM-HouseofLove     11-13 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House of Love,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tragedy Brings Out Community's Best</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALD KNOB, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diane and Rube Wilcox lost their home and
three sons to a fire. Days later, they had a new house _ loaned,
outfitted and refurbished by their friends and neighbors.
   A sign outside the new house calls it ``the little house love
built.''
   Wednesday's fire claimed the life of Justin, Jake and Jared
Wilcox, who ranged in age from 5 to 10.
   In the aftermath, the community rallied around the popular
couple, donating more household appliances than the Wilcoxes could
use and fixing up the new house with astonishing speed.
   ``Everything has been unreal,'' said Jim Harper, one of those
who pitched in. ``We are all going to miss those boys, but we have
to help their parents get on with their lives.''
   Harper joined more than 70 people who spent nine hours Saturday
whipping the house into shape. It is being loaned to the Wilcoxes
rent-free for the next year by Lynn and Verla Davis, who own a
local real estate business.
   ``People were saying that we couldn't get it done in a day,''
Harper said. ``We proved them wrong. There were so many people here
helping out that we had to turn away some people who wanted to
help. There were people here I didn't even know.''
   The volunteers cleaned the house; installed electricity, new
carpeting, a septic tank, bathroom facilities, appliances and
telephones; set up a butane tank, painted and much more.
   ``Nothing we could do would be anything when you consider all
that those children's parents have done in this community,'' said
Vicki Leonard. ``We have to help them pull through this because
those children were their lives.''
</TEXT>
