<FIRST>u i AM-Saudi-Space     11-13 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saudi-Space,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Group Calls For Rescue System For Wayward Space Travelers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronauts, cosmonauts and
scientists from around the world urged their nations Monday to
develop a way to rescue people who become lost in space.
   The Association of Space Explorers, whose members include space
travelers and scientists from the United States and the Soviet
Union, said a universal method of retrieving stranded astronauts is
crucial.
   ``Since search and rescue is a humanitarian effort, it should
not be difficult to achieve cooperation among national and
international organizations ...,'' U.S. astronaut Vincent White
told the congress.
   Fifty-five members from 14 countries held the group's 5th annual
conference in Riyadh to discuss ways to harness space technology
for peaceful purposes.
   The congress noted the growing number of space flights and has
been examining various ways to set up a space rescue system.
   ``The frequency and numbers of people traveling in space has
increased dramatically in the last three decades,'' the congress
said. ``Consequently, the likelihood of emergency situations
requiring a rescue effort has also increased.''
   Soviet cosmonaut Alexander Alexandrov told the congress that
nations must pool their resources to develop such a system.
   ``It is practically impossible for any nation to go it alone as
far as rescue in space is concerned,'' he said. ``Efforts of all
(spacefaring) powers must be united to attain this goal and avoid
loss of human lives in space.''
   The association, which has 72 members representing 17 nations,
was preparing proposals to govern the proposed space rescue system.
   U.S. astronaut John-David Bartoe suggested a worldwide
communications network ``ensuring contact with any point on the
earth's surface, airspace, and near space _ methods must be
developed to make possible the search for, and immediate evacuation
of persons involved in accidents, of extending first aid ....''
   U.S. astronauts and Soviet cosmonauts agreed on the necessity of
getting their governments to accept the idea of setting up an
integrated space rescue system.
   Soviet participants also told reporters that Moscow was ``ready
and eager'' to carry out a joint U.S.-Soviet flight to Mars.
   Alexei Leonov, chairman of the Soviet wing of the association,
said a joint flight to Mars would be less costly.
   Indian space scientist Yash Pal warned nuclear powers against
dumping toxic and nuclear waste in space. He said using space for
military purposes would lead to the ``end of the world.''
   The host for the meeting is Prince Sultan bin Salman, the first
astronaut from an Arab country. Salman, a major in the Royal Saudi
Air Force, flew on the U.S. space shuttle Discovery in 1985.
</TEXT>
