<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Germany     11-13 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Germany,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohl Says Reunification Not Only Issue for Germans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl told
Polish lawmakers Monday a unified Germany would be important and
precious for Poland.
   Kohl met with about 80 members of the Sejm, or parliament, and
the Solidarity-dominated Senate, for more than two hours. His
spokesman, Hans Klein, said about twice the number of lawmakers
than expected showed up for the meeting.
   Senate Marshal Andrzej Stelmachowski, a constitutional lawyer
and Solidarity adviser, said after the meeting he was satisfied
with the talks.
   Stelmachowski said Kohl told the Polish lawmakers the process of
democratization must be combined with the unification of all of
Europe.
   ``In general, he (Kohl) thinks that the process of reunification
would be a process connected with the general process of
unification of Europe, and the 21st century would not be a time of
national states,'' Stelmachowski said.
   He said Kohl had stressed that for Poland, a Germany integrated
with Europe would be ``important and precious,'' and outlined a
general concept in which ``freedom would be more important than
borders.''
   West Germany has pledged in a 1970 treaty to respect the Oder
and Neisse rivers as Poland's western borders, but a reunified
Germany is not committed to those terms.
   West German conservatives recently suggested reunification be
sought within the 1937 borders of the Reich, which included about
one-third of present-day Poland. Those statements have aroused
concern in Poland.
   Kohl told his audience more than 80 percent of those West
Germans who were asked said thay favored respecting the Oder and
Neisse rivers as Poland's western borders, the senator said.
   Klein said the chancellor also talked about economic aid, easing
Polish fears that increased West German financial help for East
Germany might force reductions in the level of aid for Poland.
   The spokesman assured the Poles that was not the case,
especially since Kohl was aware that without the prior events in
Poland and Hungary, reform in East Germany would not have been
possible.
   The Solidarity-led government believes Western aid is essential
for Poland to make the transition to a market economy and secure
democratic reforms.
   Klein had said Sunday night after Kohl met President Wojciech
Jaruzelski and Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki that more West
German aid would have to be concentrated on East Germany.
   Kohl had broken off his visit to Poland on Friday so he could
attend an emergency Cabinet session in Bonn on the events in East
Germany.
   Stelmachowski said Kohl stressed he had returned to Poland to
give a sign that his country planned to continue the policy being
implemented before East Germany opened its borders.
   Kohl said nothing should be changed in that policy, according to
the senator. Last week, both sides signed agreements worth $1.5
billion in economic assistance.
   Earlier Monday, Kohl traveled to the southeastern city of
Lublin, where he was awarded an honorary degree. He said that he
realized reunification, which would result in a nation of 80
million people, concerned not only Germans but their neighbors as
well.
   ``Today a new departure is announcing itself in the German
Democratic Republic. How could it be otherwise at a moment when the
wind of liberty unfolding on Europe,'' he said.
   Kohl thanked Poles who have come out in favor of reunification
as a way of overcoming totalitarianism.
   He appeared to be referring to Adam Michnik, a Solidarity deputy
and editor of the pro-Solidarity daily Gazeta Wyborcza and
Bronislaw Geremek, Solidarity parliamentary leader.
   The two historians have said a de-Stalinized East Germany would
be beneficial for Poland.
   Kohl said he ``was moved and profoundly grateful to see that
prominent Poles are among the first to demand naturally liberty and
the right to self-determination for East Germany. I would like to
thank them for such a frank engagement and courage in favor of
liberty.''
   But Kohl added that he realized the future of the two Germanys
``does not leave any one of our neighbors indifferent,'' and said
the German national destiny lies within Europe as a whole.
</TEXT>
