<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Protest     11-13 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Protest,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nearly 300,000 Jeer Communists in Leipzig, Demand Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 300,000 demonstrators
chanted ``We are the people!'' and shouted anti-communist slogans
as they marched through the center of Leipzig on Monday night,
vowing to press for more democracy.
   Whistles, jeers and shouts of ``Faules pack!'' _ German for
``lazy bunch _ rang out as the crowd marched past the city
headquarters of the once-dreaded Stasi, East Germany's secret
police.
   Two Communist Party officials who tried to address the crowd
were drowned out by boos, whistles and jeers.
   The crowd chanted repeatedly, saying ``Wir vind das volk!'' _
``We are the people!''
   ``The mood is getting a little bit too militant for me,'' said
party member Uwe Dreilich, 32. He said he had been present at all
the Leipzig demonstrations in the past two months.
   ``I am for free elections but I think we must be careful that
this does not get out of control,'' he said.
   Witnesses estimated the crowd at nearly 300,000 people.
   The demonstration was the seventh in as many weeks in Leipzig.
But the crowd was smaller than the up to 500,000 who have turned
out previously.
   Before the march, Leipzig leaders of East Germany's biggest
opposition group, New Forum, hailed East Germans' new freedom to
travel but insisted there be free elections and other moves toward
genuine democracy.
   Earlier in the day, about 2,500 people crowded in Leipzig's St.
Nicholas Church, the center of the mass pro-democracy movement that
has engulfed the country, forced the ouster of longtime communist
leader Erich Honecker and compelled promises of sweeping reform.
   Pastor Christoph Kaeler compared what he called East Germany's
``peaceful revolution'' and the resulting opening of the Berlin
Wall with the collapse of the walls of Jericho.
   ``For seven Mondays the people of Leipzig marched around the
city and called, `We are the people,' and then the wall fell right
down,'' he said to massive applause.
   He thanked nations in East and West _ but did not specify which
ones _ for supporting East Germany's pro-democracy movement.
   ``Without their contribution, our walls would not have
collapsed,'' he sai.
   Jochen Lessig, a prominent member of the New Forum in Leipzig,
also warned against swift German reunification when he addressed
the crowd in Karl Marx Square after the service.
   ``It would be easy after years of being told what to do by big
brother in the East just to link up with the West,'' he said, but
urged caution before rushing to imitate capitalist West Germany.
   ``Free elections, free elections,'' the crowd chanted in
response.
   To wild cheering, the next speaker, Michael Groetsch, said,
``We've grown to love these Mondays on the Leipzig streets. Monday
is the symbol of our liberation and it must stay that way.''
</TEXT>
