<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-EnergyStandards     11-13 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Energy Standards,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Sets Efficiency Standards for Fridges, Freezers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department on Monday announced that
refrigerators and freezers built after 1992 will have to use 25
percent less energy than today's models.
   The efficiency gain will save consumers nearly $20 a year in
electricity costs, the department said.
   The decision drew quick criticism from the appliance industry,
which contends the technology to meet the new standards does not
exist and is not likely to by 1993.
   ``Shell-shocked, that's how we react,'' said Frederick Hallett,
vice president of White Consolidated Industries, maker of Philco
and other refrigerator brands.
   ``This is akin to telling the automobile industry it has to have
a mileage standard of 50 miles a gallon,'' Hallett said, adding
that the tougher requirements ``will force some refrigerators and
freezer off the market'' by 1993.
   Henson Moore, the deputy energy secretary, said in announcing
the new standards that the department considered five possible
efficiency standards and chose a mid-point option that ``strikes a
reasonable balance between what is technologically feasible and
economically justified.''
   The new standards, effective Jan. 1, 1993, will raise the retail
price of refrigerators and freezers by an average 10.5 percent, but
the extra cost will be offset in less than 2{ years by savings from
a lower cost of running the appliances, Moore said.
   For the most common model of refrigerator _ those with
top-mounted freezers and automatic defrost, comprising 70 percent
of the market _ the average retail price will rise from an
estimated $513 for the basic 1990 model to $559 for the equivalent
1993 model, Moore said.
   However, he said it will take nearly $20 a year less in
electricity to run the appliance, which is the largest user of
electricity in many American households.
   The reduced power requirements will save the nation the
equivalent of 5,000 megawatts of generating capacity, or the output
of four large power plants, between 1993 and 2015, assuming the
efficiency standard remains constant over that period, Moore said.
   The department is also considering new energy efficiency
standards for television sets and 11 other types of household
appliances, as required by a 1987 law.
</TEXT>
