<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-NATO     11-13 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-NATO,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonn Reaffirms Commitment to NATO, European Community</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German officials, seeking to calm
fears of a possible reunification of Germany and its impact on
NATO, on Monday reaffirmed the nation's commitment to the alliance
and to the European Community.
   Defense Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg said the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization ``will be a cornerstone in the policy'' of West
Germany. He spoke at a meeting of the Western European Union, a
group of West European foreign and defense ministers.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher said that for West
Germany, ``the issue is membership in the European Community ...
and the issue is to stay in the Western alliance.''
   Finance Minister Theo Waigel told fellow finance ministers at
the European Community that West Germany remains in favor of the
trading bloc's push to create a single, or internal, market in late
1992.
   ``West Germany certainly reaffirmed in clear-cut terms its
commitment to the European Community, and I don't think there is
any doubt about that,'' said John Major, Britain's chancellor of
the exchequer.
   The community wants to dismantle by late 1992 the many trade
barriers that prevent the free movement of people, money, goods and
services among the dozen nations.
   At a regularly scheduled meeting Monday, the finance ministers
devoted much of their time to the difficult issue of how to forge
an economic and monetary union. But they took time out to discuss
the extraordinary changes in Eastern Europe.
   East Germany's unexpected opening of its western borders has
sparked debate over the possible reunification of the two Germanys
and its potential impact on Western alliances.
   Even before the developments in East Germany, there had been
discussion of the future role of the 16-nation NATO alliance in an
era of reduced East-West tensions.
   Belgian Foreign Minister Mark Eyskens said the foreign and
defense ministers of the nine-nation Western European Union
``agreed that the big clamor rising from the East must find an echo
in a more consistent, more solid, more coherent European
Community.''
   He said it was ``an absolute necessity'' for the Common Market
nations to move ahead with their plans for closer ties.
   Eyskens, who is chairman of the group, said it was in the
interest of all that ``the East has in front of it a solid partner,
steady, credible, with sufficient economic capacity to help it.''
   He said participants at next month's scheduled summit of
European Community leaders in Strasbourg, France, should give a
``signal to the East'' of a willingness to cooperate as they move
to more open economic and political systems.
   The Western European Union brings together foreign and defense
ministers of Belgium, France, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, the
United Kingdom, West Germany, Italy, Spain and Portugal, all of
which are members of the European Community and NATO.
</TEXT>
