<FIRST>r w AM-US-Bulgaria     11-13 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Bulgaria,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Met With Bulgarian Leader In September</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James Baker met in
September with Petur Mladenov, the new leader of Bulgaria who
served as foreign minister at the time, the State Department said
Monday.
   Baker met with Mladenov at the U.N. General Assembly as part of
a series of meetings with foreign ministers from around the world,
and the conversaton focused primarily on the expulsion of ethnic
Turks from Bulgaria, said spokesman Richard Boucher.
   Mladenov was Bulgaria's foreign minister until he was named
general secretary of the Communist Party to replace Todor Zhivkov,
the veteran party boss who resigned in a surprise move last week.
   Boucher discounted a report in The Washington Post on Saturday
which said the Baker-Mladenov meeting was held in secret. ``It was
laid on late in the week, and it was the last meeting before they
returned (to Washington) and nobody asked,'' he said.
   Baker consulted Turkey beforehand and the Turkish foreign
minister supported the meeting, Boucher said.
   ``It was a meeting during which the Secretary made clear, I
think in the strongest possible terms, that the United States
needed to see improvements in the human rights situation in
Bulgaria, particularly as regard Turkish nationalities.''
   More than 300,000 Bulgarians of Turkish origin have fled their
country this year to protest harsh treatment by Bulgaria and forced
assimilation. Most have gone to neighboring Turkey.
   Boucher said Baker and Mladenov also discussed the need for
political reform in Bulgaria.
   ``Then-Foreign Minister Mladenov spoke very positively about the
need for constructive change,'' Boucher said. ``But as for the
situation now, we feel that the new general secretary faces a very
difficult challenge in bringing needed reforms to Bulgaria, and we
hope that he will move vigorously to build a more open and
democratic Bulgaria.''
   Bulgaria has only a fledgling opposition movement, unlike some
of the other eastern European countries such as Poland and Hungary.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said ``it's too early to
comment on any new directions the country may be taking. We just
don't have enough information.''
</TEXT>
