<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 2007EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Congress     11-13 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Congress,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Next Soviet Congress to Convene Dec. 12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Congress of People's Deputies, the supreme
organ of the Soviet government and forum for televised diatribes
about all the country's ills, will convene Dec. 12, the legislature
decided Monday.
   The Congress is the centerpiece of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's political reforms. He called its first session in late
spring ``the most outstanding event in the entire history of the
Soviet state.''
   Its 2,250 deputies were elected in the country's first
competitive elections in more than 70 years, and many spoke out
against everything from the KGB to the empty shelves in Soviet
stores.
   The agenda for the coming session will include discussion of
radical measures to improve the economy and the fight against
rising organized crime, Tass reported Monday.
   The Congress will also consider changing the electoral system
and bills on ``constitutional compliance,'' a reference to the
growing number of parliaments in restive Soviet republics that have
passed laws contradicting the country's constitution.
   Deputies of the Supreme Soviet legislature, which was elected by
the Congress, also proposed Monday that the Congress address the
article of the constitution that makes the Communist Party the
``leading force'' in Soviet society, but their motion failed by
just a few votes, Tass said.
   The constitutional article on the Communist Party has come under
increasing fire in recent weeks, including among striking coal
miners in the Soviet Arctic, who included cancellation of the
article in their demands.
   The first Congress of People's Deputies was broadcast live on
national TV. Whether that practice would be repeated was in
question because Soviet leaders complained that the whole country
watched with such rapt attention that productivity dropped
significantly.
   Gorbachev lauded the first Congress as heralding ``a new stage
of perestroika,'' his program of reforms.
   Human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov, who was also a deputy
to the Congress, said on the final day that the session had failed
in its primary mission as he defined it: to establish an effective
new system of power.
</TEXT>
