<FIRST>r w AM-Iran-Contra     11-13 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Ending Appeals In Case Against CIA Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department will end its court
appeals involving the delayed Iran-Contra case against former CIA
station chief Joseph Fernandez, a department spokesman said Monday.
   Dan Eramian said the department would not contest a Sept. 29
appeals court ruling which concluded the power to appeal decisions
on classified material rests in the hands of Iran-Contra prosecutor
Lawrence Walsh.
   ``We are pleased that the Justice Department has decided not to
delay the Fernandez case further by additional appeals,'' Walsh's
office said in a statement. ``We are prepared to proceed to trial.''
   Eramian noted, however, that the Justice Department reserves the
right to file an affidavit in court in the Fernandez case barring
the disclosure of classified material that would damage national
security.
   Fernandez, an ex-CIA operative in Costa Rica, was scheduled to
go on trial July 24, but the Justice Department obtained an
emergency stay from the U.S. Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va.,
after the CIA said it needed to protect certain classified
information that Fernandez wanted to use in court.
   The material concerned three CIA locations, including stations
in Honduras and El Salvador, and three CIA programs in Costa Rica.
   Filing an affidavit in court could scuttle some or all of the
criminal charges against Fernandez. That, in turn, could lead to
court appeals by the independent counsel's office in an attempt to
save the case.
   The Justice Department appealed after U.S. District Court Judge
Claude Hilton rejected prosecutors' proposals to substitute numbers
for the names of the three CIA locations and to drop part of one
criminal charge against Fernandez to avoid mentioning the CIA
programs in Costa Rica.
   Fernandez, who assisted Oliver North's secret Contra re-supply
network, is accused of obstructing the Tower Commission and the CIA
inspector general's office and making false statements in the
Iran-Contra affair.
</TEXT>
