<FIRST>r w AM-SeabrookEvacuation 1stLd-Writethru   11-13 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook Evacuation, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0591,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Panel Approves Massachusetts Evacuation Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf: ``Massachusetts Attorney,'' with two grafs to
give AG reaction, eliminating now-outdated last graf pvs and adding two
grafs with Sens. Kerry and Kennedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal panel moved the Seabrook, N.H.,
nuclear power plant a step closer to opening by announcing Monday
it has approved evacuation plans for neighboring Massachusetts
communities.
   The Atomic Safety and Licensing Board had been told by opponents
of the plant that evacuating the densely populated coastal region _
particularly during busy summer months _ would be impossible in a
nuclear emergency.
   In a 571-page decision, the three-member board also approved an
evacuation exercise conducted last year in Massachusetts and New
Hampshire, saying it ``was adequate in scope and revealed no
fundamental flaw.''
   Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon within hours filed
a motion with the board's appeal panel to overturn the ruling.
   ``If the decision of the licensing board is allowed to stand,
and I don't think it can stand, then it would put at ristk the
safety of hundreds of thousands of citizens who live in
Massachusetts and New Hampshire,'' said Shannon.
   But the $6.3 billion reactor could still receive a full-power
license even before the appeals run their course, said Nuclear
Regulatory Commission spokesman John Kopeck. Seabrook officials
have said they expect the plant to be licensed around the first of
next year.
   ``This is a major development that brings Seabrook closer to a
full-power license,'' said plant spokesman Ron Sher. ``The
emergency plans for Seabrook have been evaluated by the experts _
the Federal Emergency Management Agency, the staff of the NRC and
the Advisory Committee on Reactor Safeguards _ and their
conclusions are that Seabrook's emergency plans are among the best
in the country.''
   Seabrook was originally planned to cost less than $1 billion and
begin operation in 1979. The plant has been plagued with repeated
delays due to financing problems faced by its principal owner _
Public Service Company of New Hampshire _ protests mounted by
neighbors of the plant, regulatory changes brought about by the
1979 Three Mile Island nuclear accident, and the opposition of
Massachusetts officials.
   In the licensing board's ruling, dated Nov. 9 and made public
Monday, the board found ``reasonable assurance that adequate
protective measures can and will be taken in the event of a
radiological emergency at the Seabrook station, in accordance with
the commission's emergency planning regulations and precedents.
...''
   The licensing board cleared away another potential obstacle to a
full-power license by ruling that a recent appeal board decision on
the New Hampshire evacuation plans posed no major problem in the
licensing process.
   Several flaws in the New Hampshire plans found by the appeal
board in a ruling last week, ``do not preclude the immediate
issuance of an operating license for the Seabrook station,'' the
board said.
   The next step in the complex process involves a 30-day review
period by the NRC, a public meeting held by the full commission at
which the NRC staff makes its recommendations on the plant and a
final decision on issuing a license by the commission.
   Shannon, who was in Washington for an attorneys general
conference, was joined in front of the Capitol building by
Massachusetts Sens. John Kerry and Edward M. Kennedy.
   Kennedy called the licensing board ruling, ``Perhaps the most
irrespoinsible action that I have seen taken by any administrative
agency in the 28 years that I have been in the United States
Senate.'' He called for a congressional investigation into the
process that led to Monday's announcement. Kerry called the
decision ``abusive'' and ``arrogant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
