<HEAD>Bulgarian Party Restores Dissident Memberships; Purge Predicted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with restoration of party memberships, purge
predicted, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Politburo restored Communist
Party membership to 11 advocates of reform Monday, and sources who
follow Bulgarian politics predicted a purge of top party ranks
within weeks.
   The sources, Bulgarians and diplomats, said a housecleaning also
was expected in the top levels of government as a result of the
removal Friday of Todor Zhivkov, 78, who led the party with rigid
orthodoxy for 35 years.
   He was succeeded by Foreign Minister Petar Mladenov, 53, who
served 18 years as foreign minister and is considered more open to
reform.
   Parliament is to meet Wednesday to choose a new president to
replace Zhivkov and the party Central Committee is expected to
order other personnel changes soon.
   BTA, the official news agency, said most of the activists whose
party memberships were restored were members of the Independent
Club for the Support of Glasnost and Perestroika, which
incorporates Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's Russian
catchwords for change.
   The Politburo also proposed that those who lost their jobs as a
result of unorthodox views be reinstated.
   Among those taken back into the party were Ivan Dzhadzhev and
Koprinka Chervenkova, the club's chairman and spokeswoman
respectively.
   Dzhadzhev, a professor of esthetics at the Higher Institute of
Theatrical Art in Sofia, said in an interview Sunday the group was
thriving despite intimidation and repression.
   He said its ``unifying aim'' was ``democratization of our
society'' and predicted that within five years, ``the political
landscape in Bulgaria will be totally different from what it is
now. ... Political pluralism will become a reality.''
   Also Monday, the Supreme Court said the Sofia city court must
reconsider the application for legal status of another independent
group, Eco-Glasnost, because it made procedural mistakes the first
time.
   Representatives of the environmental group said the decision
improved the chances of official approval. No date was announced
for the new hearing.
   One Bulgarian source described Mladenov as a well-connected
politician with good relations in Moscow, where he was educated.
   Mladenov stopped in Moscow on his way home from a recent trip to
China, but sources discounted rumours that Zhivkov was ousted at
Gorbachev's behest.
   A BTA dispatch Monday said Mladenov had spoken with Gorbachev by
telephone since becoming party chief and they pledged to strengthen
cooperation.
   According to the sources, Zhivkov's fate was decided at a secret
meeting of the 10-member Politburo on Nov. 9, the day before the
Central Committee announced his resignation.
   It had been rumored for years that Zhivkov was on the way out.
The sources, both Bulgarians and diplomats, said resistance to his
departure came from the men around him rather than the leader
himself.
   Bulgarian sources confirmed rumors circulating among diplomats
before Friday that Mladenov had offered to resign as foreign
minister earlier this month.
   They said he made the offer a few days before he was to lead a
Bulgarian delegation in talks with Turkish officials about the
dispute over 1.5 million ethnic Turks in Bulgaria. Zhivkov named
Deputy Premier Georgi Yardanov to head the delegation.
   One reason Mladenov wanted to resign was that hard-liners
criticized his successful efforts to have a 35-nation environmental
conference held in Sofia, the sources said.
   The conference gave several new Bulgarian reform groups their
first opportunity to express their views publicly. They held
rallies and news conferences to explain their objectives to
diplomats and journalists.
   Mladenov is said to have disagreed with methods the government
used to ``Bulgarize'' the ethnic Turkish minority.
   In Washington, the State Department disclosed Monday that
Secretary of State James A. Baker III met with him in September at
the U.N. General Assembly in New York. Department spokesman Richard
Boucher said their talks focused primarily on the flight of ethnic
Turks from Bulgaria.
   About 320,000 Bulgarian Turks fled religious and cultural
discrimination in Bulgaria, but nearly 60,000 have returned because
they could not find jobs or housing.
   ``Mladenov was ... against the methods'' applied to the ethnic
Turks, including the use of security forces in 1984-85 to force
them to take Bulgarian names, one source reported.
   Opinions differ about whether, or at what pace, Mladenov will
bring political or economic change.
   A Western diplomat said he ``has not been known to us as a
reformer,'' but Bulgarian sources said Mladenov was expected to
move cautiously in that direction.
</TEXT>
