<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms In Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Windy storms dumped locally heavy rain over parts of Texas on
Monday, and unseasonably warm air boosted temperatures to record
highs from Iowa to Georgia.
   Thunderstorms produced up to 1{ inches of rain and wind gusting
to 45 mph during the morning over the Hill Country and Edwards
Plateau of south-central Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued over parts of the area
during the afternoon and also spread over southern Louisiana.
   In the Northwest, a cold front produced showers over western
Washington state and northwestern Oregon. Rain and snow showers
developed along a stationary front curving through western Montana
and northwestern Wyoming.
   Unseasonably warm weather continued south and east of a cold
front crossing the central Plains and middle Mississippi Valley.
   Record highs were 81 at Beaufort, S.C.; 67 at Buffalo, N.Y.; 77
at Cape Hatteras, N.C., a tie; 70 at Cedar Rapids, Iowa; 82 at
Charleston, S.C.; 72 at Chicago; 72 at Cleveland, a tie; 75 at
Burlington, Iowa; 69 at Detroit; 71 at Erie, Pa.; 67 at Grand
Rapids, Mich., a tie; 64 at Mansfield, Ohio; 67 at Milwaukee; 73 at
Moline, Ill.; 82 at Montgomery, Ala., a tie; 61 at Muskegon, Mich.;
73 at Peoria, Ill.; 83 at Savannah, Ga., a tie; 72 at South Bend,
Ind.; and 71 at Toledo, Ohio, a tie.
   However, temperatures were mostly in the 20s and 30s from the
northern high Plains region to Upper Michigan, and were mostly in
the 30s across northern New England.
   Monday's low for the Lower 48 states was 9 degrees above zero at
Gunnison, Colo.
