<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Politics     11-13 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Politics,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Name Reformist Premier, Demand Free Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German legislators elected a reform-oriented
premier and discussed the idea of free elections Monday during a
frank debate that departed abruptly from Parliament's usual
rubber-stamp role.
   The new premier, Hans Modrow, likely will wield more clout than
his predecessor, Willi Stoph, who resigned last week. He is
expected to initiate a measure of political democracy and to
address growing economic problems.
   In an unusual development, Stoph, an unquestioning follower of
ousted Communist leader Erich Honecker since he assumed the
premiership in 1964, accused Honecker and other former ranking
Communists of misusing their powers.
   Stoph also acknowledged his government had erred in not
consulting with Parliament on major decisions, the state news
agency ADN said.
   Only one of 477 deputies present at the 500-seat Parliament
meeting voted against Modrow, an indication of the chamber's
support for reforms.
   The session was carried in full on state television.
   Modrow, 61, the former Communist party chief in Dresden, is
considered by many to be East Germany's answer to Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Central authorities singled him out in June for rare public
criticism, saying he failed to control ``bourgeois and enemy
views'' in Dresden after an early demonstration of citizens
demanding free travel to the West.
   Much of Monday's debate in the legislature was dominated by
normally docile non-Communist deputies, who criticized the
leadership for restricting their role.
   ``We expect that the constitutional rights of Parliament (will)
be strictly observed in the future, so that our Parliament will
never again be discredited,'' declared Michael Koplanski of the
Liberal Party.
   Parliament also picked a non-Communist speaker in the chamber's
first secret ballot and urged accelerated changes.
   Previously there has been only one candidate for the post of
speaker, and the candidate usually has been approved unanimously.
   Of those present, 246 deputies voted for Guenther Maleuda in the
second round, while his closest rival, Manfred Gerlach, gathered
230 votes.
   Maleuda is head of the Democratic Peasant Party of Germany, one
of four non-Communist parties that have been allowed to exist in
exchange for accepting the authority of the Communists.
   Some of the deputies urging free and secret elections were
high-ranking Communists, among them Werner Jarowinsky, a member of
the policy-setting Politburo. He also urged the formation of a
coalition government that would allow the non-Communist parties
more influence.
   ``Political arrogance'' of the previous party and state
leadership cost East German Communists the trust of the people and
plunged the country into its economic and social crisis, Jarowinsky
said.
   He also indirectly criticized the country's record on human
rights, saying international norms must be strictly observed.
   Some deputies, echoing the demands of pro-democracy activists,
also appealed for removal from the constitution of language
declaring the nation a socialist state.
</TEXT>
