<FIRST>u w AM-DrugWar     11-13 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug War,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Authorizes Anti-Drug Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Monday approved a series of
anti-drug bills giving legal shape to President Bush's war on
narcotics, from the Andean countries where coca is grown to schools
and neighborhoods where it is consumed.
   The legislation provides the authority for a list of programs
carrying out the drug war and putting Congress' imprint on the
initiative Bush announced earlier this year. The government will
spend some $8.8 billion on its anti-drug efforts this year, and the
money itself is provided for in other legislation.
   One of the measures the House passed authorizes $125 million in
military aid in fiscal 1990 for Colombia, Peru and Bolivia to train
and equip anti-narcotics forces in their law enforcement,
interdiction and eradication battle. Another $115 million is
authorized for the State Department's international anti-drug
operations.
   ``We cannot let (Colombian President Virgilio) Barco, and the
people of Colombia, Peru and Bolivia twist in the wind until next
year,'' said Rep. Lawrence Coughlin, R-Pa., arguing for quick
action on the bill.
   Addressing a major congressional concern, the bill specifically
bars U.S. military and drug-enforcement personnel from directly
participating in anti-drug field operations including arrests. But
American officials could be present during those operations, and
act to protect themselves in an emergency.
   Other provisions waive a ban on U.S. foreign aid to countries
that are behind in their repayment of U.S. government debt, such as
Peru and Bolivia, and express Congress' desire that the aid be
followed later with economic aid to coca farmers to entice them to
grow alternative crops.
   In separate legislation, the House also:
   _Separated the $1.2 billion Alcohol, Drug Abuse and Mental
Health block grant program into two parts, one for substance abuse
and one for mental health. Under the mental health grants, a new
program would provide $100 million to help rural communities
provide drug treatment. Another $75 million would be earmarked for
drug programs for pregnant women and their infants.
   _Directed most of the increased money for this year for the
Drug-Free Schools and Communities Act to local school districts and
disadvantaged areas. Some $500 million is expected to be spent
under the drug education program this year, about $180 million more
than in the year that ended Sept. 30.
   _Extended for four years the authority for the Justice
Department to transfer money from seized drug assets to the Office
of National Drug Control Policy.
   The legislation still must be approved by the Senate.
</TEXT>
