<FIRST>r p AM-YonkersMayoral     11-13 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yonkers Mayoral,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spallone Still Winner in Yonkers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recount of the votes in Yonkers' mayoral
election was completed Monday and confirmed the election of
Republican Henry Spallone, a vigorous opponent of the city's
court-ordered desegregation plan.
   Spallone had been proclaimed mayor on Election Night, ousting
Nicholas Wasicsko by 4,466 votes. But in the first stage of the
recount, Wasicsko suddenly picked up nearly 1,700 votes, and an
election commissioner said the result could be reversed.
   But on Monday, the final, unofficial tally showed Spallone with
29,294 for Spallone and 25,021 for Wasicsko, a Democrat who had
urged compliance with the desegregation plan, according to
Elections Commissioner Antonia D'Apice.
   That left Spallone ahead by 4,273 votes.
   ``That's the ball game,'' Wasicsko said.
   About 1,300 absentee and affidavit ballots remain, but Wasicsko
``can't overcome the difference,'' said D'Apice.
   The key issue in the race was the city's housing desegregation
order. Spallone has been its most vocal opponent and Wasicsko its
most aggressive supporter.
   The makeup of the City Council and its approach to the
desegregation order was also affected by the outcome of the mayoral
race. The council, without the mayor, was evenly split with three
people supporting the plan and three against it.
</TEXT>
