<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-IndianMuseum     11-13 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Museum,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Indian Museum Bill; Senate Expected to Concur</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved a bill Monday to transfer a
priceless collection of Indian artifacts from New York's Museum of
the American Indian to the Smithsonian Institution for display in
museums in Washington and New York.
   The measure may at long last make peace among politicians,
native Americans and archaeologists, first by resolving a
10-year-old dispute in New York over how to display and preserve
the Heye Foundation collection of more than a million Indian
artifacts.
   Second, it stipulates that the Smithsonian Institution, where
possible, return its collection of some 18,000 Indian remains to
their original tribes for burial.
   The question of the remains had been the last obstacle to
crafting a passable bill, and compromise came in September, when
Smithsonian Secretary Robert McCormick Adams reversed the museum's
long-held policy that the bones were necessary for study. Indians
nationwide, seeking to bury their ancestors, heralded his decision
as a watershed that will influence other museums.
   The House passed the measure on a voice vote. A similar bill
passed the Senate on Oct. 3., but because of slight differences in
the two bills' language, Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, planned
to ask the Senate to approve the House version Tuesday, said Inouye
spokeswoman Pat Zell.
   ``Sen. Inouye has asked for the consent of the Senate to bring
up the bill as amended and have the Senate approve that bill and
send it directly to the White House,'' Zell said Monday.
   Suzan Shown Harjo, a trustee of the Museum of the American
Indian, was confident that the Senate would go along with the plan.
   The bill passed Monday would establish a Museum of the American
Indian in the last available space on the Washington Mall, between
the National Air and Space Museum and the Capitol. There the
Smithsonian would erect an 82,500 square foot building financed
two-thirds with private donations and one-third with public money.
   The bill further states that a satellite museum, the George
Gustav Heye Center of the National Museum of the American Indian,
would be established in the old U.S. Custom House in lower
Manhattan. Both New York state and New York City have pledged to
contribute up to $8 million apiece toward converting the building
for that use. The federal government would chip in another $8
million under the bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Estonia     11-13 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Estonia,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estonian Parliament Annuls 1940 Decision to Join Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Estonian legislators issued their boldest
challenge to the Kremlin by annulling the Baltic republic's 1940
decision to join the Soviet Union, but did not actually vote to
secede, Tass reported Monday.
   The official news ageny said the legislature passed a resolution
Sunday accusing the Soviet Union of ``aggression, military
occupation and annexation of the Estonian republic'' and declaring
the vote in 1940 ``unlawful.''
   Legislatures of the Baltic republics _ Estonia, Latvia and
Lithuania _ already have condemned the Soviet-German agreement of
1939 that gave free rein to Hitler in Poland and to Stalin in the
Baltics. The Soviet Union absorbed the Baltic republics the next
year.
   Soviet historians maintain the Baltic states joined the Soviet
Union for protection against Hitler. Western historians and Baltic
activists say the unions were forced.
   A special commission of the national parliament, led by
Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, is reviewing the status of
the Baltic republics.
   The Estonian resolution passed Sunday specified that it did not
invoke Article 69 of the republic's constitution, which says
Estonia ``retains the right to freely leave the U.S.S.R.''
   Both the text and a top official of the Estonian Communist Party
said the resolution would be the basis, instead, for negotiating
greater independence within the Soviet framework.
   Estonia has led the Baltic states in legal and legislative
challenges to Kremlin authority. Its supreme court has asserted
Estonia's right to refuse national laws, and Estonians have been
most vocal in demanding more autonomy.
   Tass said the latest resolution caused stormy debate Sunday in
the Estonian legislature, and that 46 deputies walked out at one
point to protest the refusal to postpone the vote.
   Miik Tiitma, a ranking official of the Estonian party,
emphasized that the republic did not intend to secede, but that the
resolution would ``change relations between the republic and the
center,'' the agency said.
   Tiitma said the lawmakers understood the importance of President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform program, and would not to take
extreme steps that might jeopardize it and do ``irreparable damage
to the process of expanding the political and economic sovereignty
of the Baltic peoples,'' Tass reported.
   The resolution said Estonia would use it in negotiations ``on
the relations in the Soviet Union and in the world society of
sovereign Soviet states.''
   It also directed the legislature's Presidium to review laws
passed in 1940 ``under the pressure of a representative of the
Stalinist regime.''
   Izvestia, the government newspaper, printed a long list Monday
of Estonian laws that conflict with the national constitution, and
repeated a request from the national Supreme Soviet Presidium that
they be brought into line.
   On Monday, the national Supreme Soviet voted to put the question
of ``constitutional compliance'' on the agenda for the next
Congress of People's Deputies, scheduled for Dec. 12.
   Estonia has refused previous requests to modify its laws.
</TEXT>
