<FIRST>r a AM-DrugTests-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0682 11-13 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Tests-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Union Head Worries About High Court's Drug Testing Move</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 7th, `Boston police...' to UPDATE with
reaction from commissioner.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED GOLDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the city's police union vowed Monday
to continue to fight against random drug tests after the U.S.
Supreme Court let stand a ruling that forces officers to undergo
the tests.
   The nation's highest court, without comment, left intact a
ruling that the tests do not violate the police officers' privacy
even when there is no reason to suspect drug abuse.
   ``There are different legal avenues that we can follow. One is
to take the rule right back into the state courts and challenge the
constitutionality,'' said Robert Guiney, president of the Boston
Police Patrolmen's Association.
   Drug testing should be used only when there is probable or
reasonable cause to suspect an officer's drug use, he said.
   ``I'm very disappointed. I'm disappointed in the fact the
Supreme Court has said that police officers in this city and in
this country have different Constitutional rights than other
citizens,'' said Guiney, who has led the fight against random tests
for three years.
   Fighting testing in court, he said, ``might be an opportunity to
sit down and do some bargaining over this, which is originally
where we were when this thing started.''
   Boston Police officials say the tests are needed to assure
public confidence and to prevent officers from becoming susceptible
to bribery because of a drug habit.
   ``Over time I believe that this procedure will enhance the
health and safety for dedicated professionals of whom society
expects so much, in terms of the dangers they face and the risks
they undertake to protect the public safety,'' Police Commissioner
Francis Roache said in a statement Monday.
   In its first drug-testing rulings in March, the Supreme Court
upheld drug and alcohol tests for railway workers involved in
accidents and U.S. Customs Service employees applying for
drug-enforcement jobs or those positions that require carrying a
firearm.
   Neither ruling directly addressed the question of random tests.
   The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals nevertheless relied on
those decisions in May in upholding the constitutionality of random
urinalysis tests for Boston police officers who carry firearms or
enforce drug laws.
   The appeals court overturned a decision by U.S. District Judge
Robert E. Keeton that the tests violate the officers' rights.
   ``Since we can find no relevant distinction between a customs
officer and a police officer, we hold the police department's
drug-testing rule to be constitutional,'' the Appeals Court said.
</TEXT>
