<FIRST>u w AM-US-ElSalvador 1stLd-Writethru a0670 11-13 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-El Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Tops with 5 grafs of Baker remarks; picks up 2nd graf pvs: It's
a...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker on Monday
said Soviet action in Central America and Cuba ``has been the
biggest obstacle'' to that country's achieving better relations
with the United States.
   Baker blamed the Soviet Union for aiding El Salvadoran
guerrillas in their bloody offensive.
   ``The Soviet Union bears a special responsibility because its
arms and money, moving through Cuba and Nicaragua, continue to
support violence, destruction and war,'' Baker said in an address
before the Organization of American States. ``Shipments of soviet
rocket-propelled grenades to the FMLN are incompatible with the new
thinking.''
   He added, ``Soviet behavior toward Cuba and Central America
remains the biggest obstacle to a full across the board imporvement
in relations between the United States and the Soviet Union.''
   Baker joined other administration officials in condeming what he
called ``acts of terror'' by the leftist Salvadoran guerrillas,
known as the FMLN. Hundreds of people have been killed in the small
Central American nation in the fighting that began over the weekend.
   ``It's a very difficult situation with this very large and
organized and clearly calculated offensive under way,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said. ``And while it is being handled,
it certainly represents an escalation of the attacks from anything
we've seen in recent months.''
   ``The president stands with the freely-elected government of El
Salvador in condemning this senseless violence,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said El Salvador's president, Alfredo Cristiani, had
not asked for assistance to quell the fighting, the heaviest since
a 1981 offensive by the Marxist-led rebels. He said he would not
rule out U.S. involvement, adding: ``We can never predict the
future. But at this point, it's not anticipated.''
   The United States provides El Salvador with about $1.5 million a
day in economic and military aid. Fifty-five American military
advisers are assigned to train the Salvadoran troops but are not
supposed to take part in field operations.
   At the State Department, deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said
Christopher Babcock of Spokane, Wash., was killed Sunday when he
was hit in the head by a grenade fragment. He was a teacher at the
American School in San Salvador, the capital.
   Fitzwater cited reports of recent arms shipments to the rebels
from the Sandinista government in Nicaragua, adding: ``The latest
attacks show that much more of the Sandinista arms designed to
destabilize and overthrow the legitimate government of El Salvador
have been getting through.''
   At the Organization of American States, Nicaraguan Foreign
Minister Miguel D'Escoto introduced a resolution Monday calling for
an urgent appeal to the Salvadoran government ``to cease
immediately the bombing of the civilian population'' and other acts
of repression.
   The rebels launched the offensive Sunday after pulling out of
peace talks to protest a series of attacks on leftist political and
union leaders, which they blamed on the U.S.-backed government.
Cristiani, whose official residence was attacked, declared a state
of siege, rescinding basic civil liberties and imposing a 6 p.m. to
6 a.m. curfew nationwide.
   Boucher defended the move, saying: ``The imposition of a state
of siege of limited duration by the government, we believe, is a
responsible measure to protect civilians from the FMLN's (Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front) latest campaign of terror.''
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., the chairman of the foreign
operations subcommittee, said Cristiani's rightist government
should move with caution.
   ``They should be very careful that they not fall back into the
patterns that held the government in disrepute in the first
place,'' he said, adding that his criticizm of the administration's
handling of El Salvador has been justified.
   ``I have been critical of the administration for giving an all's
well attitude down there,'' Leahy said. ``And in view of the events
this weekend, it's not.''
   Rep. Robert Lagomarsino, R-Calif., said the guerrilla offensive
showed the rebels ``are obviously desperate'' and defended
Cristiani's suspension of civil rights by saying: ``I think we'd do
exactly the same thing if rebels were attacking Washington, D.C.''
   The spokesman said about 1,500 guerrillas infiltrated into San
Salvador for the attack and that fighting in the capital caused
significant civilian casualties. There have been attacks in other
cities and on armed forces brigade headquarters in outlying
provinces.
   Boucher said there were ``indications in the past that something
like this might happen.''
   U.S. Embassy personell and their dependants were staying close
to home, he said. The American School was closed. The Pentagon
declined to comment on whether the military advisers assigned to
outlying bases had been recalled to the capital.
</TEXT>
