<FIRST>r a AM-HepatitisEpidemic 1stLd-Writethru a0676 11-13 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hepatitis Epidemic, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Coast Suffering Hepatitis A Epidemic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 19th graf to CORRECT to Beecham, sted Beacham.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL ANN RIHA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West Coast is suffering an extended
epidemic of Hepatitis A, a virulent liver disease with flu-like
symptoms that has struck thousands this year.
   Health officials blame the disease's spread partly on
intravenous drug users and the fact that hepatitis can occur
undetected in young children.
   Although a Hepatitis A vaccine has been developed, it may be six
years or more before the U.S. Food and Drug Administration approves
its use.
   Through Oct. 28, 1,951 Hepatitis A cases were reported in
Oregon, 2,613 in Washington, 5,635 in California and 2,032 in
Arizona, according to Dr. Gary Schatz, hepatitis control officer
for the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta. Nationwide, 27,869
cases were reported during the same 10-month period.
   ``The West Coast is very high,'' said Dr. Harold Osterud,
chairman of the Department of Public Health and Preventive Medicine
at Oregon Health Sciences University in Portland. ``We're not at
all sure why that is true. Certainly the number of cases in the
Midwest and the East seem to be remarkably lower.''
   For example, Oregon, with a population of 2.7 million, has
recorded far more cases than larger states such as Virginia, with a
population of 5.9 million and only 255 cases, or Minnesota, with a
population of 2.4 million and only 139 cases.
   The disease spreads through fecal-oral transmission. ``It's from
using the toilet and not washing your hands,'' Oregon Health
Division spokesman Art Keil explained.
   The illness is marked by fatigue, flu-like symptoms, nausea and
vomiting, and pain in the liver, on the right upper side of the
abdomen.
   ``That's where it does its damage,'' Osterud said. ``If the
liver is involved, most older people will become jaundiced. Young
children and up through the teen-ager and so forth frequently don't
become jaundiced.''
   Schatz said one-half of 1 percent of Hepatitis A victims die,
all of them adults and many of them pregnant women.
   Prevention focuses mainly on promoting sanitary toilet habits,
but once the virus is introduced into a community, its spread is
difficult to control, doctors say.
   The disease often passes unnoticed in children, making their
family members and care providers likely victims. Day care centers,
where healthy and infected children may play together, provide a
prime setting for spreading the disease.
   ``With diaper-age kids, people are used to seeing them with
diarrhea anyway and you don't chalk it up to anything worth
worrying about,'' Schatz said. ``And they're rarely ill for any
length of time.''
   Oregon statistics show the most cases are reported among adults
under the age of 40. While they may be infected by others in their
household, the primary carriers among adults appear to be
intravenous needle users and food handlers, Keil said.
   Needle use is very high on the West Coast, especially among
methamphetamine users, according to Lt. Bob Miller, narcotic unit
commander for the Oregon State Police.
   However, while there also are a large number of intravenous drug
users in New York, that state reported just 344 cases of Hepatitis
A through Oct. 28, Schatz said.
   Once contracted, the virus simply runs its course, unless the
patient is aware of having been exposed before the symptoms occur
15 to 30 days later, Osterud said.
   Immune globulin can be injected within two weeks of exposure,
and will protect against the illness or at least make it less
severe. Although a vaccine has been developed by SmithKline
Beecham, an international pharmaceutical company, it has just begun
to be tested in the United States.
   ``It is still early in clinical trials, which run for three to
six years,'' spokeswoman Sharon Arnold said by telephone from
Philadelphia, where the company's Smith Kline &amp; French Laboratories
are located.
   Until the vaccine is available, the disease will continue to
spread, Schatz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
