<FIRST>u p AM-VaVote 1stLd-Writethru a0731 11-13 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Va Vote, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elections Board Begins Its Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to restore dropped word, `black.' ^By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elections official said Monday her staff
will check returns ``with a fine-tooth comb'' before certifying the
result of the tight governor's race, which apparently was won by
Lt. Gov. L. Douglas Wilder.
   Susan Fitz-Hugh, secretary of the electoral board, said the
state's 136 localities have finished their official canvass of the
Nov. 7 balloting for governor, lieutenant governor, attorney
general, the House of Delegates and local offices and referendums.
   Wilder, a Democrat who would be the nation's first elected black
governor, leads Republican J. Marshall Coleman, a former attorney
general, by a few thousand votes.
   A canvass of all local registrars Monday to obtain final figures
showed Wilder with 897,125 votes to 890,273 for Coleman, a margin
of 6,852 out of 1.78 million votes cast. Results from three
counties had not been verified.
   Coleman has said he will ask for a recount if Wilder's lead of
less than half a percent holds up.
   Ms. Fitz-Hugh said state law requires that the election results
be certified on the fourth Monday of November, which is Nov. 27.
She said her office needs the two weeks to recheck the results from
each locality.
   ``We go through the election precinct by precinct. We
computerize the figures,'' she said. ``If we find a problem, we
then have to call the locality, walk through the whole processs
with them to find out where the error is and get them to change
their figures if necessary.''
   Checking balloting will be no more painstaking than it would be
if one candidate won in a landslide, Ms. Fitz-Hugh said. ``We go
through it with a fine-tooth comb anyway.''
   If the state finds a problem that occurred on Election Night,
the officers of the election for that precinct are called in, Ms.
Fitz-Hugh said.
   ``We usually have at least 50 that have to be contacted and
officers called in,'' she said.
</TEXT>
