<FIRST>r a AM-Prosecutors-Drugs     11-13 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prosecutors-Drugs,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicago and LA Forge First Link in Prosecutors' Network</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top local prosecutors for Chicago and Los
Angeles forged an information link Monday in the fight against
drugs, a connection they want to expand into a national network of
prosecutors against crime.
   State boundaries are artificial ``when you're dealing with
narcotics,'' said Ira Reiner, the Los Angeles County district
attorney.
   ``Gangs and other large drug dealers are becoming multistate
enterprises,'' said Cook County State's Attorney Cecil A. Partee.
   The two appeared at a news conference where Reiner said Los
Angeles has become cocaine's number one point of entry in the
United States.
   ``And the cocaine that is sold on the streets here, in Chicago,
begins at one point in Los Angeles,'' Reiner said.
   ``So it makes a great deal of sense that Los Angeles and Cook
County come together as the first two offices in what State's
Attorney Partee envisions as a national network of urban
prosecutors.''
   Partee said he has contacted his counterparts in Miami and New
York about the idea, but has not worked out details with those
offices.
   He also plans to contact Dallas, Houston and Seattle, said a
spokesman for Partee, Dan McCullough.
   ``The recent infusion of crack into our community is believed to
be closely linked to a new alliance between gangs in Chicago and
Los Angeles,'' Partee said.
   Chicago had until recently been free of crack, a highly
addictive derivative of cocaine, authorities say.
   Partee said he and Reiner will soon name liaisons to each
other's offices, who will communicate by telephone.
   Prosecutors from different states have worked together before,
but not extensively, Reiner said.
   ``We will have in Los Angeles the head deputy of our narcotics
unit, the head deputy of our gang unit, in contact with their like
numbers in the Cook County office, where there will be ... a
constant and systematic exchange of information and intelligence,''
Reiner said.
   Before the news conference, Reiner and Partee met with
representatives of the U.S. attorney's office, the Chicago Police
Department, and with community leaders to discuss cooperation in
the drug war.
   The Cook County and Los Angeles County prosecutors began working
together after members of a Los Angeles street gang, known as the
Crips, came to Chicago in 1987 and killed a parking-garage
attendant.
   Two gang members were convicted of murder and sentenced in
recent weeks _ one to 60 years, the other to natural life. A third
defendant will be tried next month.
</TEXT>
