<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 2126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MissingDoctor     11-13 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Doctor,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Hunt for Missing Doctor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday joined a Virginia surgeon's
family in the search for the physician, who mysteriously
disappeared from his hotel last week.
   Todd Arcomano ``vanished into thin air,'' his older brother,
Keith, said.
   The 32-year-old surgeon from Arlington, Va., checked into the
Four Seasons Hotel a week ago, the day before he was to take an
American Board of Surgeons certification test.
   Arcomano never showed up for the test.
   People believed to be missing sometimes just don't want to be
found, police said, but Arcomano's family said the evidence in his
case indicates otherwise.
   The doctor's sports car is still parked in the hotel lot, and
the car keys were found on a table in his room. The bed appears not
to have been used, and Arcomano's shaving kit was still in the
bathroom.
   On Friday, hotel employees, noting that Arcomano had planned to
stay only a day and that the room appeared unused, notified his
Arlington office, which contacted the family Saturday, family
members said.
   Arcomano's parents, Nicholas and Ella Cecilia Arcomano, and
Keith Arcomano came from Long Branch, which is about 50 miles
northeast of Philadelphia, to look for him. They roamed the
streets, checked restaurants and bars and talked to taxi drivers.
   Detectives circulated the doctor's photograph, interviewed
relatives and other people, and alerted hospitals, police spokesman
Edward Tenuto said Monday.
   Keith Arcomano said the only clue the family has is a piece of
hotel stationery found in the room, on which the doctor had
scribbled directions from the hotel to 30th Street Station,
Philadelphia's main Amtrak station.
   Even if the doctor had planned to meet someone at the train
station, family members said, he would have eventually contacted
them. He was due in Long Branch on Saturday for a birthday party
for his father.
   On Nov. 3, another medical organization, the American Board of
Emergency Medicine, postponed certification tests for 2,000
emergency-room doctors in eight cities, including Philadelphia,
because of threatening letters sent to the physicians and those who
were to give the test.
   Philadelphia police said there appeared to be no connection.
   No arrests have been made in the medical test case, said Floyd
Wiltze, an FBI spokesman in New York City. Those tests will be held
sometime next year, said board Executive Director Benson Munger.
   Arcomano is a general surgeon at Arlington Hospital in suburban
Washington. In September 1988, he performed an emergency
appendectomy there on Washington Redskins quarterback Doug Williams.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
