<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-Politics     11-13 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Politics,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bhutto's Cabinet Offers to Resign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto's
Cabinet offered Monday to resign to open the way for a government
reshuffle after a no-confidence vote came close to toppling her
governing party, officials said.
   Government sources said the offer was mainly a formality but
that several advisers and special assistants were likely to go.
   ``I will make changes in the Cabinet at a suitable time,'' Ms.
Bhutto was quoted as saying by Pakistan's state television.
   Sources said the move was a response to criticism that the prime
minister, during 11 months in power, has surrounded herself with
officials who have alienated her from her own Pakistan People's
Party.
   Earlier Monday, a dozen lower-level appointees resigned from
posts in national security, political affairs and finance. The
source said Ms. Bhutto was expected to accept all 12 resignations
but some of the appointees might be reassigned to other government
posts.
   Ms. Bhutto promised changes in her left-leaning government
following a parliamentary no-confidence motion on Nov. 1. The
motion fell just 12 votes short of a majority in the 237-seat
National Assembly.
   The mainly right-wing opposition accused the government of
ineffectiveness and cronyism.
   Apparently shaken by the close call, Ms. Bhutto, 36, said she
would purge her government of controversial figures and reach out
to what she termed ``moderate elements'' of the mainly right-wing
political opposition.
   The Pakistan People's Party emerged as the nation's single
largest party last November in Pakistan's first free elections
after 11 years of military rule under late President Gen. Mohammad
Zia ul-Haq.
   Zia, who overthrew Ms. Bhutto's father in 1977 and had him
hanged two years later, died in a plane crash in August 1988.
   Ms. Bhutto's party claims about 111 seats in the federal
legislature but rules mainly with the help of independents.
</TEXT>
