<FIRST>u a AM-RiotTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0622 11-13 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Judge in Lozano Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with appeals court upholding judge's decision;
no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court Monday upheld a judge's
decision to seat a black juror over defense objections, allowing
the trial of a Miami policeman who shot and killed a black
motorcyclist to resume.
   The trial of William Lozano stalled Friday when the defense
targeted the juror for a peremptory challenge. Dade County Circuit
Judge Joseph Farina ruled the action was based soley on race, and
therefore illegal.
   The 3rd District Court of Appeal ruled that the defense
challenge was based on race alone, that the juror should be seated
and that there was no need to dissolve the jury and start jury
selection again.
   The trial will resume Tuesday afternoon, said Assistant State
Attorney John Hogan, the lead prosecutor. Opening arguments may not
begin until Wednesday, he said.
   ``Obviously I'm happy that we're able to proceed,'' Hogan said.
``We think it's a fair jury.''
   Telephone calls seeking comment from defense attorney Roy Black
were not returned immediately.
   The ruling came after three weeks of jury selection in the trial
of the Colombian-born police officer charged with two counts of
manslaughter in the Jan. 16 deaths of the motorcyclist and his
passenger. The killings set off three days of racial violence in
Miami's black neighborhoods.
   The three-judge appeals panel had stayed the trial while it
considered the issue. The court could have decided to throw out the
entire jury pool, following previous appellate court decisions.
   The defense had strenuously denied challenging the black juror,
Ezra Simmons, because of his race, noting they had already accepted
another black juror on the six-member panel. The jury consists of
two blacks, one Hispanic and three non-Hispanic whites.
</TEXT>
