<DOCNO> AP891113-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 2139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovak-Protest     11-13 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovak-Protest,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Official Meets With Protesters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 environmentalists
demonstrated in Teplice late Monday and a local Communist Party
official promised to meet with them next week, official media
reported.
   A dispatch from the official news agency CTK said the
demonstrators, most of whom were young, assembled outside party
headquarters in Teplice, 30 miles northwest of Prague.
   It said Antonin Vana, a party secretary, addressed the group and
said an open meeting to discuss the environment would be held at a
Teplice stadium next Monday.
   Palach Press, a publishing house in London operated by
Czechoslovak emigres, said police initially tried to disperse the
crowd, but Vana arranged for the officers to withdraw and told the
crowd he had not called them.
   His pledge of a public meeting was rare in Czechoslovakia, whose
Communist leadership has resisted the reforms now spreading through
Eastern Europe with the blessing of Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
</TEXT>
