<FIRST>r w AM-HUDSued     11-13 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Sued,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Lender Sues, Alleging Unfair Audits Tainted Its Reputation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lender on Department of Housing and Urban
Development probation amid allegations it inflated mortgages to pad
its fees filed suit against the agency on Monday.
   The plaintiff, Benton Mortgage Co. of Knoxville, Tenn., alleged
that shoddy auditing led to the charges and that HUD refuses to
give the company a chance to rebut them.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, contended that
department auditors violated auditing standards and ``violated
their duty to report accurately and fairly the findings of their
own investigation'' when they issued a report accusing the company
of inflating mortgages for more than a dozen projects.
   A second suit filed by Benton seeks a court order forcing HUD to
give its final endorsement to two Benton-financed projects that are
completed but have not received final clearance for financing in
HUD's co-insurance program.
   The projects are the 352-unit Pebble Creek Apartments in
Arlington, Texas, and the 312-unit Kingsley Park Apartments in
Essex, Md.
   That program is one of several criticized by internal and
congressional investigators during recent investigations of
mismanagement and influence-peddling at the department during the
Reagan administration.
   Benton was the co-insuring lender on a number of housing
projects that also participated in the Moderate Rehabilitation
Program, which auditors determined was riddled with influence
peddling involving former agency officials and prominent
Republicans.
   The audit of Benton that led to its being placed on probation
alleged that Benton had approved inflated mortgages on 14 projects
reviewed by the auditors, allegedly allowing Benton to reap higher
fees and developers of the projects to receive excessive rent
subsidies because those payments are based on the mortgage amount.
   Justice Department investigators have reviewed the audit and the
working papers used to compile it but have declined comment on the
investigation.
   HUD spokesman William Glavin said the department had no comment
on Benton's lawsuits.
   Benton Chairman Fred Benton said in a statement that all of the
projects cited in the audit had been approved by officials in the
department. He complained that the department has ignored repeated
requests for a meeting to discuss the allegations.
   ``It seems as if HUD just doesn't want to deal with the fact
that the audit findings are incorrect,'' Benton said. ``Apparently
HUD was fishing for scapegoats.''
</TEXT>
