<FIRST>r i AM-France-EC     11-13 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-EC,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Calls Special EC Summit to Discuss Changing Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand has invited the
leaders of the European Community countries to a special meeting
Saturday to discuss the rapidly changing situation in Europe, the
presidential palace announced.
   The announcement Monday said the 12-nation meeting would be held
Saturday evening at the Elysee Palace.
   The cascade of events in Eastern Europe in recent weeks,
culminating in the decision by East Germany Friday to begin
dismantling the Berlin Wall, has opened new questions for Western
European leaders on the continent's future.
   Former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, head of France's main
centrist political coalition, had urged Mitterrand to call an
urgent meeting of European Community leaders before the U.S.-Soviet
summit scheduled for Dec. 2-3 aboard ships off Malta.
   A European Community summit is set for Dec. 8-9.
   ``It would not be acceptable that the analysis of the situation
in Europe be made by the Americans and the Soviets and not by the
Europeans themselves,'' Giscard d'Estaing said in a radio interview
Sunday night.
   The statement from Mitterrand's office said, ``The president has
invited the chiefs of state or government of the 11 other countries
of the European Economic Community as well as the president of the
commission to the Elysee Palace Saturday night Nov. 18 to discuss
with them the recent developments in the situation in Europe.''
Jacques Delors is president of the European Commission, the
executive body of the European Community.
   Last week during a visit to Denmark, Mitterrand said that with
the opening of the Berlin Wall by East Germany, Europe was evolving
from ``the order established after the Second World War'' but it
was too early to set out ``a new balance.''
   Mitterrand is the president of the European Community under the
six-month rotating system. His term will end with the Dec. 8-9
summit in Strasbourg.
