<HEAD>Sandinistas Reports More 8 Combat Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUIGALPA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Monday that the
Sandinista Army had killed eight rebels during two battles in
southeastern Nicaragua.
   A military spokesman said that deaths resulted from
confrontations in Acoyapa, 45 miles southeast of Managua, and in
Rama, 200 miles southeast of the capital. The spokesman said the
fighting occurred Friday and Saturday. The government did not
mention losses by its own troops.
   The Sandinista government began a major offensive against the
U.S.-backed Contra rebels on Nov. 1, when President Daniel Ortega
suspended a 19-month-old cease-fire with the rebels.
   Nicaragua estimates 4,000 Contras have slipped over the border
in recent weeks. There are about 12,000 Contra rebels living in
camps in Honduras along with their dependents.
   Contra rebels have been fighting the leftist Sandinista
government since 1981. They say the government betrayed the goals
of the 1979 revolution that brought down President Anastasio Somoza.
   According to peace accords signed last August in Tela, Honduras,
by five Central American presidents, the Contras will have to be
relocated or repatriated by the first week of December.
   Some Contras have said they are unwilling to demobilize before
national elections set for Feb. 25.
