<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Politics     11-13 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Politics,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists to Try to Form Government After Others Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leader Harilaos Florakis
received a presidential mandate Monday to try to form a government
after both the conservatives and socialists failed.
   It was expected Florakis, leader of the Left and Progress
Coalition, also would be unable to arrange an alliance that would
have a parliamentary majority, extending Greece's political
stalemate indefinitely.
   Conservative leader Constantine Mitsotakis, whose New Democracy
Party won the most parliamentary seats in the Nov. 5 elections but
missed a majority, was the first to try to form a government.
   He met with Florakis and former socialist Premier Andreas
Papandreou last week but was unable to persuade either to join in a
short-term administration with his conservatives.
   President Christos Sartzetakis then issued a three-day
exploratory mandate to Papandreou but the unsuccessful Papandreou
returned without a mandate Monday.
   If Florakis cannot form a coalition, Sartzetakis will call the
leaders of the three major parties to a meeting to try to form a
joint administration.
   If that should fail, the president will call general elections,
which would be the third this year.
   Florakis has said the Left and Progress Coalition supports a
broad-based government. But it has made tough conditions, including
the removal of U.S. military bases from Greece and the rejection of
a U.S. request for the extradition of a suspected Palestinian
terrorist.
   New Democracy seeks closer ties with the United States and is
opposed to those conditions.
   Papandreou has said his socialists and the Left and Progress
Coalition are ``in almost total agreement,'' but Florakis rejected
his proposal to form a government that would exclude New Democracy.
   In the Nov. 5 elections New Democracy won 148 seats in the
300-member Parliament. Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement
won 128 seats and Florakis' coalition 21. Two seats went to
independents and one to an enviromentalist movement.
   The environmentalists declared Sunday they would not back
Papandreou.
   A socialist alliance with Left and Progress, with the support of
the only leftist independent, would control only 150 deputies _ one
short of a majority.
   The third independent represents a Moslem minority in northern
Greece and has not been approached by any party.
   Elections in June also failed to give any party a majority and
the conservatives and communists formed a short-term alliance,
ending eight years of government by Papandreou's socialists.
   That unusual alliance was formed mainly to investigate charges
of corruption in connection with a banking scandal against
Papandreou.
   Papandreou and five of his ministers were indicted and are
scheduled to be tried by special courts next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
