<HEAD>Magazine: The Boss Leaving E Street Band Behind, At Least For Now</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce Springsteen has told the E Street Band,
his backup group for the past 15 years, that he doesn't want to be
their Boss, according to a published report.
   The blue-collar rocker nicknamed ``the Boss'' telephoned all
seven band members to tell them he won't be using them on his next
album or concert tour, according to this week's issue of People
magazine.
   Springsteen told the band members they should feel free to
accept other offers, the magazine said.
   However, Barry Scott, an attorney who represents Springsteen,
said in a telephone interview in New York that he had not heard
anything about the personnel move.
   Phone calls to Springsteen's manager, John Landau, and Marilyn
Laverty, a spokeswoman for the band's label, Columbia Records, did
not immediately return messages left at their offices.
   People magazine said at least one band member probably got the
word in person _ singer Patti Scialfa, who is Springsteen's
girlfriend.
