<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Korea     11-13 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Hopes East Bloc Changes Force N. Korea to Open Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo said Monday he
hopes changes in Eastern Europe will prompt Communist North Korea
to open its closed society.
   In his regular radio address, Roh said his efforts to improve
relations with East bloc countries ``will at long last open the way
to national reconciliation and unification by inducing North Korea
to come out into the world.''
   Roh will visit Hungary as well as Britain, France, West Germany
and Switzerland Nov. 20-Dec. 2. He will be the first South Korean
president to visit a communist nation.
   The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since Korea was divided
in 1945 at the end of World War II when Soviet and U.S. troops
ended the Japanese occupation.
   The Communist North invaded the South in 1950, triggering a
three-year war involving troops from China and the 16-nation U.N.
Command. Borders are now completely sealed off and guarded by
hundreds of troops, and each side punishes its citizens trying to
cross the border without prior approval.
   Dialogue has been held on and off between the two Koreas to help
reduce tension, but little progress has been made with each side
insisting on its own initiatives.
   In a statement Monday, South Korea's Unification Ministry urged
the North to carry out reforms and adopt changes in East Europe.
``We hope relations between the two Koreas will develop to a stage
at which residents are free to visit each other.''
   ``We expect the North to end confrontation with the South and
make orderly and peaceful changes by protecting liberty and human
rights,'' the statement said.
   The question of human rights and freedom in North Korea was a
main topic at a policy meeting Monday of senior government and
ruling party officials. Party leaders also urged the government to
take a more flexible attitude in dealing with North Korea to help
the North become more open, officials said.
</TEXT>
