<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia 2ndLd-Writethru a0772 11-13 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0772,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Multiracial Coalition Leading in Early Namibian Returns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5, `With more...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with further
vote count. Picks up 6th pvs, `Results from...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multiracial coalition gained a
substantial lead early Tuesday as ballots were counted for the
election of an assembly to lead Namibia to independence from South
Africa.
   The black nationalist group South-West Africa People's
Organization (SWAPO), which is expected to win, was in second place
with results from its strongholds still not counted.
   Taking the lead in the 10-party race was the pro-capitalist
Democratic Turnhalle Alliance.
   With 45 percent of the 660,000 ballots tabulated, the alliance
had 134,181 votes, or 43 percent, to SWAPO's 108,532 votes, or 35
percent.
   The figures came from 21 of the territory's 23 districts.
Leftist SWAPO was expected to capture the two populous northern
districts still outstanding and surpass the alliance, which favors
a capitalist economy.
   Results from the two most populous districts, Windhoek and the
northern region of Ovambo, were not expected until Wednesday. More
than half the voters are from those two districts and the left-wing
SWAPO was expected to do well in both.
   About 95 percent of Namibia's registered voters cast ballots
from Tuesday through Saturday to choose a 72-member assembly that
will draft Namibia's constitution.
   The assembly also will declare Namibian independence after 74
years of rule by South Africa.
   SWAPO, which fought a 23-year guerrilla war against South
Africa, was expected to receive the most votes, but there were
doubts it would receive the two-thirds needed to write the
constitution without consulting other parties.
   The assembly seats will be allocated according to the proportion
of votes won by each party.
   The first two candidates to win assembly seats were SWAPO
president Sam Nujoma and Turnhalle Alliance vice chairman Mishake
Muyongo _ each the top candidate on their party's lists. Each
assembly seat represents about 9,200 votes.
   Officials said results would be announced district-by-district
as they were totaled.
   Votes were counted at the fairgrounds in Windhoek, the capital.
Territorial police and soldiers of a U.N. monitoring force barred
the public and press from the area.
   After voting ended Saturday night, U.N. Special Representative
Martti Ahtisaari declared the balloting ``free and fair.''
   SWAPO on Monday agreed the elections were free but said they had
questions about the fairness. They said some ballot boxes that
arrived in Windhoek did not have the U.N. seal on them as required.
   Territorial election officials denied any irregularities.
   South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha said Sunday that his
government will accept the results and ``is ready to work
constructively with the future government of Namibia.''
   He said the election ``ends the international dispute that has
raged for more than 40 years ... and which, aside from apartheid,
constituted the most important line of attack against South
Africa.''
   South Africa captured the territory from Germany in World War I
and ruled it under a League of Nations mandate subsequently
rescinded by the United Nations.
   South Africa refused U.N. orders to release the territory of
more than 1.3 million people until an agreement was signed in
December, which also provided for Cuban troops to leave neighboring
Angola.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
