<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Elections 2ndLd-Writethru a0759 11-13 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0759,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Gains in Nationwide Union Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with details, quotes, recasts.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The television...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's rightist Likud
bloc scored gains but failed to break the rival Labor Party's hold
over the national trade union federation in elections billed as a
referendum on Shamir's peace plan.
   Shamir had hoped a strong showing would strengthen his hand as
he heads for talks Wednesday with President Bush about Israel's
demand that the PLO be excluded from peace talks.
   According to national television projections, Likud garnered 28
percent of the vote compared to 22 percent four years ago in an
institution that has historically been a Labor Party stronghold.
   The left-leaning Labor, headed by Vice Premier Shimon Peres,
held onto its 55-percent majority in the 1.5 million-member
Histadrut Labor Federation, meaning it still maintains control over
the organization.
   Independent pollster Hanoch Smith predicted Labor would gain 56
percent of the votes and Likud 27 percent.
   Labor claimed victory, and one senior official said the results
were ``tremendously encouraging ... a turning point in the party's
morale.''
   But Likud leaders pointed out they had loosened some of Labor's
power base in the Histadrut, which governs Israeli labor policy and
also owns a significant chunk of Israeli farms and industries.
   The television said its projections were based on an exit poll
of 7,560 voters at 36 polling stations, with a margin of error of
two to three percent. Likud apparently gained from the losses of
three smaller left-wing parties.
   In past elections television projections have been accurate.
Final results were expected Tuesday morning.
   A stronger position in the labor federation also would help
Shamir defend his shaky coalition government against threats by
Peres to resign over peace policy and demand new elections.
   Peres claimed his party had made a comeback after losing
national elections to Likud last year.
   ``This shows the public has given renewed confidence to the
Labor Party and we will reach new heights,'' Peres told the
television. Labor favors making territorial concessions to the
Arabs for peace.
   In the union elections, 1,494,717 Israelis _ about half the
electorate _ were eligible to choose delegates to the Histadrut
Conference.
   Shamir made daily campaign speeches around the country, focusing
on foreign policy and Palestinian violence in the 23-month-old
uprising against Israeli rule.
   He warned repeatedly that talking to the Palestine Liberation
Organization or yielding any of the West Bank or Gaza Strip to the
Arabs would be ``national suicide,'' and urged support for his own
peace plan, introduced last April.
   The U.S.-backed Israeli plan calls for holding elections in the
disputed lands as part of an interim peace settlement. Arabs have
balked at accepting the idea because they want the PLO to represent
them in negotiations.
   Likud and Labor formed a coalition after inconclusive elections
in 1984 and did the same last year, when Likud won one more seat
than Labor in the 120-member parliament but neither won a majority.
   Histadrut, the Hebrew word for union, was founded in 1920 and
has continued to be Labor's domain despite the rise to power of
Likud in 1977.
   Most Likud supporters favor a free-market economy and shun the
Histadrut because of its socialist institutions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
