<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0737 11-13 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Colombians Plead Guilty to Drug Smuggling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS name and age of Jaramillo in 2d graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURTON, New Brunswick (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Colombians pleaded guilty
Monday to smuggling 1,100 pounds of cocaine into Canada and each
was sentenced to 22 years in federal prison.
   Jose Ali Galindo Escobar, 36, and Fernando Augusto Mendoza
Jaramillo, 27, entered the guilty pleas as their trial was about to
begin on charges of importing cocaine and possession for the
purpose of trafficking.
   They admitted they were flying a small plane carrying the
cocaine from Colombia to an airstrip in rural New Brunswick north
of Fredericton when the craft's landing gear clipped the top of a
tree and they made a crash-landing.
   They were arrested by Royal Canadian Mounted Police who had been
alerted by their investigation that the drug shipment would be
made. Fredericton is 50 miles northeast of the Maine border.
   Justice David Russell, in sentencing the two men, called them
lawbreakers who brought a cargo of drugs into Canada without
concern for the misery and crime it would create. It was the
largest amount of cocaine ever seized in Canada.
   During presentence testimony, the court was told that Colombia's
Medellin cocaine cartel planned to use New Brunswick as a
distribution base for its North American operations.
   Police Corp. Gary LeGresley said the scheme was approved by
Pablo Emilio Escobar Gaviria, considered by the U.S. Justice
Department as a major kingpin in the Medellin cartel.
   Police testified that some of the cocaine found aboard the plane
was destined for Toronto and Montreal but nearly 900 pounds was to
be smuggled to New York.
</TEXT>
