<SECOND>AM-Britain-Weinberger,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Throw Eggs, Tomatoes At Weinberger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student protesters hurled eggs and tomatoes at
former U.S. Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger Monday as he
arrived to accept an honorary degree at Leeds University.
   A police spokesman estimated the crowd of protesters at 2,000
and said one man was arrested.
   A spokesman for the National Union of Students said the honorary
degree ``seems to condone some of (Weinberger's) most unpleasant
actions, especially backing the Contras (rebels) in Nicaragua and
being behind the Star Wars program.''
   Weinberger, 62, was not hit by any of the eggs or tomatoes as he
entered and left the university hall where the Duchess of Kent
awarded him the honorary law degree. A bag of flour landed within
yards of the duchess.
   Leeds University students, staff and supporters of the Campaign
for Nuclear Disarmament chanted outside the hall during the degree
presentation, which took place under tight security.
   Weinberger was defense secretary from 1981 to 1987 during the
Reagan administration.
