<HEAD>Student Fatally Shot in City High School</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``The shooting ...,'' to DELETE now-outdated
reference to handgun not being found.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old boy was shot to death in a hallway
in a public school Monday, the first killing in a city school in
more than a decade, authorities said.
   Alexander Stephens was shot once in the chest in a second-floor
hallway at Alfred E. Smith High School in the Bronx, said Detective
Vincent Jones.
   He died on the way to Lincoln Hospital, Jones said.
   Police were questioning a suspect, and the handgun used in the
shooting was recovered, Jones said.
   The shooting occurred between class periods near an exit.
Stephens, a pupil, had been in an argument with another student,
Officer Laura Power said. The shooter fled.
   ``People heard a shot at close range,'' said Gloria Lesser, a
spokeswoman for the Board of Education. Though details were
sketchy, ``it seems that there were two witnesses who the police
were interrogating.''
   The city operates metal detectors at the entrances to 15 of its
more troubled schools to keep students from bringing in weapons.
Smith, which has about 1,500 pupils, does not have a detector.
   Lesser said the last killing inside a city school was a fatal
stabbing in an annex to John Adams High School in Queens in the
early 1970s.
