<FIRST>u w AM-US-EastGermany 4thLd-Writethru a0727 11-13 1007</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-East Germany, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0727,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caution Marks U.S. Policy; Democrats Call for Dramatic Moves</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 4 pvs: ``Busily preparing,'' with two grafs bgng:
``Administration officials,'' with word that Bush considering a NATO summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration held out the prospect
of stepped-up trade and diplomatic ties with East Germany on
Monday, while top Democrats in Congress called for far more
dramatic steps to signal support for the stunning reform
developments in the Communist world.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell urged President Bush to
travel to the Berlin Wall, convene a meeting of the Western allies
and suspend trade barriers against the Soviet Union.
   ``To acknowledge the tremendous significance of the symbolic
destruction of the Berlin Wall and to give voice to the
exhilaration felt by all Americans, I urge President Bush to travel
to West Berlin,'' said Mitchell, D-Maine.
   Administration officials who declined to be identified said Bush
was considering the convocation of a NATO summit in Brussels, after
his saltwater summit meeting on Dec. 2-3 with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, to discuss new political and military
strategy for the West.
   One administration official flashed two less dramatic signals.
He said the administration might boost trade with East Germany,
which totaled $220 million in 1988, and hold more frequent meetings
with East German diplomats.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater hailed the ``glorious''
traffic of more than 1 million East Germans streaming into West
Berlin to catch a glimpse of freedom, but said, concerning the
possibility that Bush might rush to the wall, ``We can't foresee
any set of circumstances at this moment that would induce him to
go.''
   Vice President Dan Quayle, meanwhile, said German reunification
was inevitable.
   ``East Germany is East Germany because of the Communist
system,'' Quayle told the Republican Governors Association at
Hilton Head Island, S.C. ``Do away with the Communist system and
it's Germany.''
   But the caution shown by Bush and Secretary of State James A.
Baker III amid last week's burst of new freedom in what was once a
rigid Stalinist state still permeated public and private statements
by U.S. policy makers.
   The U.S. government is not likely to take significant action
``until there are elections,'' said one official. ``You'd have to
see something like that happen before we would do something serious
other than to send friendly signals to the East Germans,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``If you are talking about assistance like we're giving to
Poland and Hungary, that's inappropriate,'' the official said.
   West Germany, to which the administration is deferring on most
East German decisions, is taking the same approach.
   Apart from holding elections, the official cited three
additional conditions for U.S. help. First is that the East Germans
do not backtrack on the announcement last Thursday that
restrictions on emigration and travel to the West had ended.
   Additionally, he said, East Germany must settle claims against
it by the Jewish community that derive from Germany's murder of 6
million European Jews during World War II and also compensate
Americans whose property was seized by the postwar Communist regime.
   ``These amount to several hundred million dollars each,'' the
official said. ``That's not a big thing but they are a big obstacle
in our relationship.''
   Quayle, meanwhile, rebutted Democratic accusations that the Bush
administration was slow in responding to the change sweeping
Eastern and Central Europe. He charged that ``the Democrats haven't
offered one creative idea on how to manage the evolving situation
in Eastern Europe or the Soviet Union except to criticize the
president.''
   House Democratic Leader Richard A. Gephardt renewed the
criticism Quayle was talking about, saying, ``At the very time
freedom and democracy are receiving standing ovations in Europe,
our president is sitting politely in the audience with little to
say and even less to contribute.''
   Separately, a dozen liberal congressmen said the changes sweping
Eastern Europe give the United States the chance to shift defense
spending to domestic programs.
   Members of the group, led by Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., told a
news conference that the level of U.S. spending and its military
presence facing the Soviet Bloc can no longer be justified.
   ``What you see emerging here is a coalition of people who want
to talk about realities,'' said Rep. George Miller, D-Calif. ``This
is our opening shot and we're going to be tough on the budget this
year. ... This is hardball politics.''
   While the quickening pace of change is pushing East Germany onto
the Bush-Gorbachev agenda, the White House and State Department
sought to dampen speculation the two leaders might settle the
country's future.
   Presidential spokesman Fitzwater told reporters at the White
House that ``we do not intend to have this emerge as a second
Yalta.'' He referred to the Black Sea meeting in 1945 in which
President Franklin D. Roosevelt, British Prime Minister Winston
Churchill and Soviet leader Josef Stalin deliberated on the postwar
future of Europe.
   Other U.S. officials said Bush would be prepared for an overture
by Gorbachev to consider the prospect of a reunified, neutral
Germany. But the officials stressed that Moscow had not signaled
through diplomatic channels that was the Soviet leader's intention
for the shipboard meetings with Bush in the Mediterranean.
   In any event, U.S. policy on East Germany is to act in concert
with the West Europeans rather than to take the lead, especially on
the reunification issue.
   Baker was in touch over the weekend with British and French
officials, and when Vernon Walters, the U.S. ambassador to West
Germany, met Sunday in Bonn with Soviet ambassador Vyacheslav
Kochemasov he also represented Britain and France, said Richard
Boucher, the State Department spokesman.
   As the Senate resumed debate on an aid package to Poland and
Hungary, just hours before the arrival of Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa, Democratic leader Mitchell said a meeting of the Western
alliance is essential.
   ``It is widely recognized there has begun a process of
transforming the political, economic and security arrangements on
the European continent,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
