<DOCNO> AP891113-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 2306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Somalia-Opposition     11-13 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Somalia-Opposition,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Seeks Peace Talks, Amends Constitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Somali government, battling
insurgencies in the north and south, is seeking peace talks and
amending the constitution to allow more political parties, a
Cabinet minister said.
   Foreign Minister Abd Al-Rahman Jama Barreh made the announcement
over the weekend in an interview broadcast by government radio in
Somalia's northwestern neighbor, Djibouti.
   ``The Somali government has decided to invite all those who hold
different views from ours to come and have talks with the
government,'' Radio Djibouti, monitored in Nairobi, quoted Barreh
as saying.
   Barreh, who was in Djibouti for talks with President Hassan
Gouled, said the multiparty system of government was not alien to
Somalia.
   He said the Horn of Africa nation had 88 political groups before
President Siad Barre seized power in a coup in October 1969.
   ``We are now involved in amending the constitution in order to
make provisions for the formation of (other) parties and to
establish ways in which they can compete in elections,'' Barreh
said.
   The Somali Revolutionary Socialist Party, formed in 1976, is
Somalia's only legal political organization.
   Barreh did not specify when the talks might take place or say if
any dissident group had responded to the government's invitation.
   The government tolerates no opposition and most critics have
been killed, detained, fled the country or joined the rebels.
   Human rights groups, including Amnesty International, have
accused Barre's government of human rights violations including
torture, indefinite detention without trial, unfair trials and
executions without trial.
   One of the government's strongest opponents is the Somali
National Movement of insurgents in the north who have been fighting
for Barre's ouster since 1981.
   The movement announced in a clandestine radio broadcast Saturday
that its fighters had cut the main road connecting northern Somalia
with the capital, Mogadishu.
   Another previously unknown group calling itself the Somali
Patriotic Movement has in recent months been fighting government
troops in southern Somalia.
</TEXT>
