<FIRST>r a AM-WilderAuction     11-13 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wilder Auction,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Director Billy Wilder's Art Collection Sold For $32.6 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Record prices were paid for works by 11 artists
Monday as Christie's sold 85 sculptures, paintings and drawings
collected by director and screenwriter Billy Wilder, the auction
house said.
   The diverse collection of Impressionist and modern works brought
$32.6 million, Christie's said. The highest price, $4.84 million,
was paid for a 1921 pastel by Pablo Picasso, ``Classic Head of a
Woman,'' which was not a record.
   Among the artists whose works sold for record prices were
Balthus, whose oil painting ``La Toilette'' brought $2.09 million;
Ernst Ludwig Kirchner, whose oil painting ``Two Nudes on a Sofa''
went for $1.54 million; and Marino Marini, whose bronze sculpture,
``Little Rider,'' sold for $671,000, the auction house said.
   Record prices were paid for eight lesser-known artists.
   Other notable items included ``The Farmer and His Wife,'' a Joan
Miro painting that sold for $2.695 million, and Joseph Cornell's
untitled pharmacy box, a 14-inch-by-13-inch cabinet filled with
apothecary jars, which sold for $495,000.
   The Austrian-born Wilder, 83, who directed films like ``The Lost
Weekend,'' ``Sunset Boulevard,'' ``Double Indemnity'' and ``Some
Like it Hot,'' watched the auction.
   ``We were really excited because we could share this with Billy
Wilder,'' said Doris Athineos, a Christie's spokeswoman. ``Usually
our collectors aren't present for the sales but we could really see
the expression on his face when his works brought nice prices.
   ``He said he wanted to be alive when they sold his collection,
that he wanted to have fun and he wanted to see it,'' she said.
</TEXT>
