<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Luscombe Adv17   11-13 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Luscombe, Adv 17,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, Nov 17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Young British Director ``Descending'' on New York Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a man who was tearing tickets at a West End
theater just a few years ago, 28-year-old director Tim Luscombe is
getting some impressive exposure.
   He is shepherding two London hits to New York this season, and
will direct Joan Collins' return to the London stage next year. Tom
Stoppard's ``Artist Descending a Staircase'' starts Broadway
performances Nov. 22 at the Helen Hayes Theater for a Nov. 30 bow.
Martin Sherman's ``When She Danced'' follows off-Broadway at
Playwrights' Horizons, where performances begin Jan. 25, 1990.
   ``There is no point in being in this business if you're not
directing plays you actually adore and have a real feeling for,''
said Luscombe, an Oxford University graduate.
   The pressured Broadway environment couldn't be more different
from the relaxed intimacy of The King's Head, the north London pub
theater where these productions originated.
   But Luscombe said higher stakes don't daunt him: ``If I started
thinking, `Oh God, what does a Broadway audience want from this
scene?' I would just go bananas.
   ``I can't ever think in terms of an audience; I do it for me.
The more you trust your instincts, the more successful you will be.
Also, how do I know what a Broadway audience wants? I've seen five
shows on Broadway, entirely musicals.''
   Broadway has traditionally warmed to Stoppard, the Czech-born
master of wordplay who won Tony awards for ``Travesties,''
``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead'' and ``The Real Thing.''
   His screenplays include ``Empire of the Sun,'' ``Brazil'' and
John Le Carre's ``The Russia House,'' now in production.
   ``Artist Descending a Staircase'' began as a radio play in 1972.
Written in 11 scenes covering 58 years, the play is organized
symmetrically around Scene 6 so that the action goes backward to
1914 only to reverse directions and end up where it started.
   It's about three aging artists, played by John McMartin, Paxton
Whitehead and Harold Gould, who decades earlier fought for the
affections of a young blind girl (Stephanie Roth).
   Its punning Stoppardian title pays homage to ``Nude Descending a
Staircase,'' Marcel Duchamp's 1911-12 Dadaist painting which, like
Stoppard's brief 80-minute play, is an exercise in perspective.
   Luscombe said it was ``a difficult play to do, but it's like a
poem. ... It's as beautiful and as taut as a poem.''
   He first read the play as a set text for his high school art
studies: ``I believe it saved my exam. It inspired me hugely.''
   When he set out to stage it, he tried changing the radio format
but ended up going back to the original and didn't change a word.
   ``People seemed to think it was as good a theater piece as it
was a radio piece,'' Luscombe said.
   He said the play has an emotional directness not always found in
Stoppard, whose latest London play, ``Hapgood,'' was dismissed by
some as cold and obscure.
   ``It has more to do with the heart than with the head,'' he
said. ``It is an intensely passionate piece.''
   ``When She Danced,'' his other New York play, marks the first
time the esteemed non-profit theater Playwrights' Horizons has
employed a foreign director, Luscombe said.
   The play, set in Paris late in the career of dancer Isadora
Duncan, is by Martin Sherman, the London-based American author of
``Bent'' and ``Messiah.''
   Luscombe grew up in the south London suburbs and, after Oxford,
spent a year teaching at a north London boys' school. He quit to
work in a theater box office and tear tickets, then studied
directing at the Bristol Old Vic Theater School.
   He made his London reputation staging 20th-century English
classics such as Noel Coward's little-known ``Easy Virtue,'' and
Terence Rattigan's ``The Browning Version.''
   Next autumn, he returns to the West End to stage Coward's 1930
``Private Lives'' with Joan Collins of TV's ``Dynasty'' as the
elegantly barbed Amanda.
   He regards Coward, who died in 1973, as Britain's Chekhov, and
says of Collins' return to the boards: ``She'll be wonderful.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Nov. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
