<DOCNO> AP891113-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-SouthAfrica-Communists Adv20   11-13 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Communists, Adv 20,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, Nov. 20 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Many South African Blacks, Communism Retains an Allure</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DAVID CRARY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While communist leaders
elsewhere are grappling with public discontent, the outlawed South
African Communist Party is gaining wide notice and unabashed
support.
   Because of President F.W. de Klerk's decision to ease
restrictions on anti-government protest, the communists' symbols
and rhetoric have emerged from the political underground into the
media spotlight.
   At a mass rally in October for freed leaders of the African
National Congress guerrilla movement, the Communist Party's red
flag and the ANC's gold, green and black banner were given equal
prominence as huge backdrops to the speakers' podium.
   A roar came from the mostly black crowd of more than 70,000 when
a message was read from the party's general secretary, Joe Slovo,
an exiled white lawyer who is depicted by the government as a
mastermind of terrorist attacks. The rally's keynote speech,
delivered by the 77-year-old ANC leader Walter Sisulu, ended with
an unmistakable message:
   ``Long live the ANC! Long live our alliance with the South
African Communist Party! Long live the working class movement!''
   The party's new stature comes at a time when its counterparts
are in varying degrees of retreat not only in Eastern Europe, but
also in Africa. The trend among leftist governments on the
Continent is to move away from dogmatic Marxism-Leninism and seek
expanded economic ties with the West.
   But in South Africa, communism holds a particular appeal for
sections of the disenfranchised black majority who view capitalism
as a partner of apartheid.
   The party has not issued a detailed platform on how it would run
the country. However, it has never publicly repudiated any aspect
of orthodox Marxism-Leninism and refers to Western countries as
imperialist.
   The Communist Party ``retains a romantic mystique ... to the
young lions who are searching for a revolutionary alternative to
the status quo,'' The Weekly Mail, an anti-apartheid newspaper,
said in a recent analysis. ``It has a vision and an ideological
coherence.''
   Some commentators have suggested that this mystique could be
lessened if the government lifted the ban on the party and let its
leaders compete openly in the ideological marketplace. As yet,
there has been no sign this might happen.
   ``Let me state it unequivocally,'' said Law and Order Minister
Adriaan Vlok in a speech Nov. 2. ``Communism is unacceptable to me,
it is unacceptable to the South African government and the large
majority of people in our country.''
   Some anti-apartheid church leaders have expressed dismay that
communist banners were displayed at recent protest marches they had
led. Yet many activist clergymen discomfited by communism's atheism
are sympathetic to the ANC, which uses as its anthem a moving hymn,
``God Bless Africa.''
   The ANC-Communist alliance dates to the early 1920s, when both
campaigned for black workers. The Communist Party was banned in
1950, and the ANC in 1960, and leaderhip has overlapped extensively
within the two exiled organizations.
   In 1986, the U.S. State Department estimated that about half of
the ANC's executive committee members were communists.
   Govan Mbeki, one of the released ANC leaders honored at the
October rally, said in his speech that the ANC-Communist alliance
has been a prime target of the South African government and ``its
supporters in the imperialist countries.''
   He declared that the alliance ``is going to continue until
apartheid ... is eliminated.''
   Few details about the Communist Party, including its size and
the composition of its politburo, are known. The ANC operates
clandestinely inside South Africa, and its guerrillas periodically
are arrested, but no evidence has turne up of comparable internal
activity by the communists.
   The most recent policy statement issued by the party takes a
more hardline stance than the ANC on the possibility of
negotiations with the government.
   ``Seizure of power will be the product of escalating and
progressively merging mass political and military struggle, with
the likelihood of culminating in an insurrection,'' said a document
adopted at a party congress earlier this year. ``We are not engaged
in a struggle whose objective is merely to generate sufficient
pressure to bring the other side to the bargaining table.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday PMs, Nov 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Uruguay'sPresident Adv21   11-13 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uruguay's President, Adv 21,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs, Nov. 21 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Uruguay's Outgoing President Had Successes But Leaves Under Cloud</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, Sunday in 1st graf is Nov. 26.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under the presidency of Julio M.
Sanguinetti, Uruguay's economy expanded, its employment rate
increased and workers' wages have risen. Yet as he prepares to
leave office his popularity is at an all-time low and the main
opposition party is poised for victory in the presidential election
this Sunday.
   ``There is a great sense of dissatisfaction in the country,''
the political analyst and pollster Luis Gonzalez said. ``If you
compare Uruguay with Argentina or Brazil, Uruguay has done well.
But that doesn't satisfy Uruguayans.''
   Sanguinetti, however, feels a sense of accomplishment.
   ``I think many things were done,'' he said in an interview.
``Above all, a descent into the bad things that characterize these
times on this continent was avoided.''
   Since he took office in March 1985, Sanguinetti has watched
neighboring Brazil sink deep into foreign debt, Venezuela face
riots, Argentina almost collapse under hyperinflation, and Peru
bleed in a guerrilla insurgency.
   Uruguay, with a population of just 2.9 million, has not been
free of the ills that plague its neighbors, but never did problems
overwhelm resources, undermine democracy or touch off violence.
   ``I would say, yes, the country is better after Sanguinetti,''
said Jorge Lanzara, director of the political science faculty at
the University of the Republic.
   Sanguinetti's critics say his economic gains shine only in
comparison with the recession of the early 1980s. His supporters
say he was kept from doing better by opposition in Congress.
   ``He provided peace, democracy and some economic growth,'' said
Gladys Presa, 59. ``I say, `Thank you, Dr. Sanguinetti.' In my
opinion, he did a very good job.''
   The polling agency Equipos Consultores recently gauged
Sanguinetti's public approval rating at 22 percent, down from a
high four years ago of nearly 70 percent.
   Equipos Consultores and the Gallup organization both project
that Luis Lacalle of the opposition National Party will defeat
Jorge Batlle of Sanguinetti's Colorado Party in the balloting.
   Sanguinetti, a 53-year-old attorney and career politician,
professes to be disturbed neither by the polls nor by labor unrest
that has resulted in strikes by teachers, garbage collectors, dock
workers and other public employees in recent weeks.
   ``Politics is not a thing of momentary popularity,'' he said.
   ``The main criticism they make of me is that I limited myself to
being the administrator of a crisis, that I was not a reformer.
Well, I accept that.''
   Political observers say Sanguinetti's accomplishments fell short
of public expectations because the economic improvements came
nowhere near to restoring the prosperity Uruguay had from the turn
of the century through the 1950s _ the years when it was known as
the Switzerland of South America.
   Public services that once were run with exceptional efficiency
now function poorly. Classrooms are overcrowded, teachers are
underpaid, hospitals and clinics are outdated, and retirement
pensions are paltry.
   Critics describe Sanguinetti's treatment of opposition parties
in Congress as high-handed, his support of amnesty for former
military rulers as overly aggressive, and his backing of Vice
President Enrique Tarigo over Batlle in the Colorado presidential
primary as meddling.
   ``He didn't make any mistakes until he said publicly he made no
mistakes,'' Lanzara said. ``Then he lost the Colorado primary.
There is a certain arrogance in him. He thought if he told Batlle
not to run, he wouldn't.''
   Even political opponents concede, however, that any accounting
of Sanguinetti's term must note he is honest, hard-working,
intelligent and eloquent.
   ``I believe he is the best of American presidents, north or
south,'' Lacalle was quoted as saying in a published interview.
   Sanguinetti is barred by the constitution from seeking a
consecutive term. While he refuses to speculate whether he'll run
again in 1994, the assumption is that he will.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tuesday PMs, Nov. 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
