<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, Nov. 25, the 329th day of 1989. There are 36
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On Nov. 25, 1963, the body of President Kennedy, who was
assassinated in Dallas three days earlier, was buried at Arlington
National Cemetery, following a requiem mass in Washington. At her
husband's gravesite, Jacqueline Kennedy lighted an ``Eternal
Flame'' that burns to this day.
   On this date:
   In 1758, in the French and Indian War, the British captured Fort
Duquesne at what is now Pittsburgh.
   In 1783, the British evacuated New York, their last military
position in the United States during the Revolutionary War.
   In 1881, Pope John XXIII was born Angelo Roncalli in a village
near Bergamo, Italy.
   In 1920, radio station WTAW of College Station, Texas, broadcast
the first play-by-play description of a football game, between the
University of Texas and Texas A&amp;M.
   In 1944, baseball commissioner Judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis
died at age 78.
   In 1957, President Eisenhower suffered a slight stroke.
   In 1973, Greek President George Papadopoulos was ousted in a
bloodless military coup.
   In 1974, former UN Secretary-General U Thant died in New York at
age 65.
   In 1980, Sugar Ray Leonard regained the World Boxing Council
welterweight championship when Roberto Duran abruptly quit late in
the eighth round of their fight at the Louisiana Superdome.
   In 1986, the Iran-Contra affair erupted as President Reagan and
Attorney General Edwin Meese revealed that profits from secret arms
sales to Iran had been diverted to Nicaraguan rebels.
   In 1987, Harold Washington, the first black mayor of Chicago,
died in office at age 65.
   Ten years ago: U.S. Rep. George Hansen, R-Idaho, on a private
trip to Iran, was allowed to visit some of the American embassy
hostages, later describing their condition as ``healthy.''
   Five years ago: William Schroeder of Jasper, Ind., became the
second man to receive a Jarvik 7 artificial heart during a 6{-hour
operation at Humana Hospital Audubon in Kentucky. He lived 620 days
on the device.
   One year ago: An earthquake centered in eastern Canada and
measuring 5.7 on the Richter scale was felt widely across Canada
and in the northeastern United States.
   Today's Birthdays: Baseball hall-of-famer Joe DiMaggio is 75.
Actor Ricardo Montalban is 69. Actor Rene Enriquez is 56. Actress
Kathryn Crosby is 56. Actor John Larroquette is 42. John F. Kennedy
Jr. is 29. Singer Amy Grant is 29. Football player Bernie Kosar is
26. Actress Christina Applegate is 18.
   Thought for Today: ``Self is the only prison that can ever bind
the soul.'' _ Henry van Dyke, American clergyman (1852-1933).
</TEXT>
