<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Gardening Adv16   11-13 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Gardening, Adv 16,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16 ^For release Thursday, Nov. 16, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Key to Difficult Vegetables May Be An Off-Beat Approach</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Bria retired from the AP in 1981 after 40
years that included coverage of World War II from Italy.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BRIA</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POUND RIDGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some vegetables give us a hard time in
the garden before, if ever, we win them over. The key may lie in an
off-beat approach.
   Directions on seed packets don't help much. They're generalized,
whereas a garden is a highly individual, quirky place.
   For a long time, parsnips stumped me. Parsnips are a
long-maturing crop, going from spring into fall frosts before you
harvest the delicious taproots, but I couldn't even get the seeds
to sprout. Homespun solutions, like covering the row with damp
newspapers, or wetting it down and putting a board on top to
prolong the moisture, did nothing for me.
   Finally, I moved the process indoors and started the seeds like
tomatoes, peppers and eggplants, with carefully controlled soil,
light, temperature and moisture. In six-pack cells, I planted seeds
in good potting soil and put them under my fluorescent stand. In
two weeks, all six seeds had sprouted.
   After the seedlings formed true leaves, I moved them out to the
cold frame for a week of hardening. On planting day, I punched deep
holes in the ground with an iron bar, filled the holes with compost
mixed with fertilizer and put in the seedlings. In a few weeks I
had strong, healthy plants.
   It's unorthodox with a root crop, but it worked for me. Carrots,
also poor sprouters, responded to the same treatment.
   Beets germinated in my garden all right, but I got dwarfish,
stunted crops until I read in a manual, ``Use wood ashes where you
grow beets.'' With ashes plentiful from fireplace and woodstove,
the situation improved dramatically; I moved up to plump, tender
beets in a single season. Wood ashes, rich in potash and the
alkalinity needed to sweeten the soil, also help many other
vegetables, flowers and shrubs. (Spread store-bought lime if you
don't have ashes but don't use either on plants that like acid.)
With beets, you mix the ashes into the soil before planting and
then make side dressings as the season moves on.
   Frustration comes from planting too early or in an unsuitable
spot.
   My garden, in hilly, wooded country 50 miles north of Manhattan,
tends to be cool. By trial and error, I learned that it was
unrealistic to plant warmth-loving things like beans before the
middle of May. An early day may be balmy, but the ground is still
cold and seeds just rot. My best bean harvests come from seeds
planted in June, July and August.
   And part of my garden gets some shade, fine for greens like
lettuce but not for sun-lovers like beans and tomatoes that need at
least six hours of direct sunlight.
   Homesick for the tropics, eggplants act moody in northern
climes. They like heat so much that some people put seed flats near
the furnace or on radiators to get them to germinate. In my
climate, we don't set the plants in the ground until well into
June. You've got to watch your harvest closely, too, picking the
fruit when it's young, firm and lustrous. When eggplants soften and
lose their shine, the taste goes ``off.''
   A retired person with time to experiment can challenge the
improbable, like raising artichokes in the Northeast, where winter
likely kills even the best-mulched plants. Horticulturists with
professional savvy and equipment have found a way. The secret is to
start the seed early in February in wet sphagnum moss in the
refrigerator. In this cold, but not freezing, temperature, you
``vernalize'' the emerging radicle (the first part of the root) for
at least two weeks before taking it out of the refrigerator and
planting it in a pot.
   Come spring, you transplant it outdoors. The process shortens
the artichoke's normal two-year life cycle; the luscious globes are
then obtainable in six months. A scientist friend gave me such a
plant and produced a globe in my garden. But I haven't had any luck
doing it on my own in the refrigerator.
   The seeds of some plants may defy all attempts to get them to
germinate.
   New Zealand spinach, a popular summer vegetable which flourishes
when other greens wilt in the sun, often maddeningly refuses to
sprout. You may soak the large seed before planting it, you may
baby it indoors _ nothing helps. But _ a lesson i irony _ New
Zealand spinach loves to seed itself and you'll find plants
springing up at unexpected places in your garden, the offspring of
summers past.
   Nature likes to keep you guessing.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 16</NOTE>
