<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-13 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Hit Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against the Japanese yen today,
while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose to a new high
in moderate trading.
   The dollar closed at 143.55 yen, up 0.80 yen from Friday's close
of 142.75 yen. It opened at 143.30 yen and ranged between 143.15
and 143.55 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 5.78-point
winner on Friday, added another 86.92 points, or 0.243 percent, to
rise to a record high of 35,750.12.
   Traders said the dollar rose against the yen on rumors Japan's
trade figures announced later in the afternoon would show a
reduction in the surplus. The figures showed Japan's trade surplus
in October shrank by $3 billion on a year-to-year basis to $4.658
billion.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's strength also followed its
rally in New York Friday, which was triggered by reforms in East
Germany and their uncertain impact on the economy of West Germany.
   ``Trading was centered around the West German mark,'' with
dollar-yen trading relatively light, said a dealer at a major
commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In the Sydney market, which opens before Tokyo, the dollar
dropped back against the mark, influencing the start of Tokyo
trading, but recovered later in the day, said Minori Takeuchi, a
trader at Chemical Bank.
   East Germany's move to open its borders Thursday prompted some
European and North American participants Friday to switch their
holdings from marks to dollars. Others were seen taking profits on
long positions in the mark.
   On the stock exchange, Eastern Europe and Soviet Union-related
stocks did well, traders said.
   Alexander Yakovlev, a top aide to Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, arrived in Tokyo on Sunday for a week of talks with
government and business leaders.
   Trading companies and heavy equipment companies seen as
potentially benefiting from warmer Japan-Soviet and Japan-East
Europe ties rose over attention to Yakovlev's visit, seen as
preparatory to a recently-announced visit by Gorbachev to Japan
expected to take place in 1991.
   ``Fishing companies could be big beneficiaries'' of warmer
Japan-Soviet ties, said a trader at brokerage Kleinwort Benson who
requested anonymity.
   Construction and steel stocks rose as the market believed giant
brokerage Nomura was pushing these sectors prior to a personnel
reshuffle at the firm, the trader said.
   Securities dealers said last week's bullishness on the Tokyo
market carried over to today's trading, but the volume of trade did
not rise proportionally with the Nikkei index.
   ``Most stocks are rising, but the (amount) each share gained is
not necessarily substantial,'' said a dealer at Sanyo Securites Co.
He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The previous high of the Tokyo's exchange's most widely-followed
index was 35,689.98, posted on Sept. 29.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
