<HEAD>Money Manager Aquires Quaker State Shares, Says He's Optimistic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OIL CITY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York money manager Mario J. Gabelli,
who has acquired a 5.1 percent stake in Quaker State Corp.,
believes the company's stock is undervalued and says he's
optimistic the motor oil refiner will return to solid profitability.
   Gabelli said Friday he acquired the Quaker State shares as an
investment for his stable of mutual funds.
   Gabelli said his analysis of Quaker State's operations runs
counter to that of other Wall Street analysts who have issued
negative reports both on Quaker State _ because of disappointing
profits _ and on the entire motor oil market.
   Gabelli, whose stake makes his company Quaker State's largest
shareholder, expressed confidence in Jack W. Corn, the company's
president and chief executive officer.
   ``We think Corn has positioned the company in a more sensible
way,'' Gabelli said. ``Previous management took some wrong turns.''
   Corn succeeded Chairman Quentin E. Wood as chief executive in
July 1988.
   Gabelli and other analysts credit Corn with shifting Quaker
State's marketing strategy away from heavy discounting, which was
aimed at retaining market share.
   Other analysts have said that by adopting higher prices, Quaker
State is losing market share and not gaining profits.
   During the first nine months of 1989, Quaker State reported a
profit of $9.45 million, or 35 cents a share, on sales of $613.98
million. That compares with a profit of $9.59 million, or 35 cents
a share, on sales of $673.4 million during the 1988 period.
   But Gabelli said Corn is building a solid foundation for future
profits and in time, Quaker State's performance will rebound.
   ``He has repositioned the product, telling retailers that
(Quaker State) will not be a loss leader,'' he said.
   Gabelli praised Quaker State's chain of 444 quick lube shops as
``extremely well run,'' and said the company benefits from the high
recognition of the Quaker State brand name.
   He said Quaker State's stock is undervalued at $14 or $15 a
share.
   The company's stock closed Friday at $14.87{ in consolidated New
York Stock Exchange trading, down 12{ cents. On Thursday it jumped
$1.12{ after Gabelli Group Inc. disclosed in a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing that it acquired the Quaker State stake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
