<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ComputerShow 1stLd-Writethru f0007 11-13 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Show, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0007,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giant Annual Comdex Show Expected To Draw 120,000 People, 1,740 Companies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to fix typo in lead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual showcase for the computer industry,
Comdex Fall, kicks off its second decade today with stronger
foreign participation than ever.
   Organizers say interest from abroad is a major factor in the
expansion of the show, which this year will attract a record 1,740
companies showcasing their wares to an expected audience of 120,000.
   The latest in computer technology will be spread over exhibit
space covering an area the size of 21 football fields.
   If attendance is as expected it will set a record for any trade
show in the United States, said Sheldon Adelson, the show's
originator.
   ``I'd never have dreamed it would grow to something like this,''
he said last week in a telephone interview while wrapping up final
details for the annual computer extravaganza. ``But, then, no one
expected to see the computer market grow the way it's growing.''
   A total of 365 foreign companies will be exhibiting this year,
up from 301 a year ago. They will represent 22 foreign countries.
About 15 percent of the attendees will come from abroad.
   Foreign participation is so strong that the organizers have
staff interpreters standing by.
   ``When an exhibitor comes to the show, he can put his product
into the worldwide distribution mainstream,'' Adelson said.
   Comdex officials say the relaxation of trade barriers around the
world is making a significant impact on the computer industry.
   ``Americans are finding they must compete with a rising number
of hardware and software suppliers from Europe, Canada, the Pacific
Rim and Latin America _ not only in these foreign markets, but
right here in the U.S.,'' says Ellen Glew. She is president and
founder of EGI, an international marketing consulting firm
specializing in the computer and communications industries.
   Laptop computers are expected to be a hot item again at the 1989
show. And some exhibitors are even moving down a notch _ showcasing
computers small enough to fit in the breast pocket of a sports
jacket.
   James Fisher, vice president of marketing for Atari Inc., says
business people are constantly faced with the decision of whether
to carry a laptop on trips.
   ``They don't want to lug it around for a two-hour flight,'' he
said.
   Atari's Portfolio is a one-pound computer that operates on two
AA batteries for 48 hours, fits in a jacket pocket and sells for
$400.
   Fisher says Atari's goal at Comdex will be to ``literally have a
computer for everyone.''
   Poqet Computer Corp. will be showcasing a similar product, an
IBM-compatible pocket-sized computer.
   ``Coat-pocket computers will be the Dick Tracy watch of the
1990s, the ultimate office extension,'' predicts Mark Eppley,
chairman of Traveling Software.
   George H. Conrades, a senior vice president at International
Business Machines Corp., will give the keynote address at the
opening session Monday morning. The show runs through Friday.
   Conrades' address, ``A Vision of the '90s: Creating Value in a
Global Marketplace,'' will discuss the challenges of competing on a
global scale.
   Adelson, chairman of Interface Group of Needham, Mass., the
convention's producer, hit upon the idea of Comdex while returning
from another trade show a decade ago.
   The first show in 1979 drew fewer than 4,000 people. Today it is
spread over 10 locations, including the sprawling Las Vegas
Convention Center, six major hotels and other convention facilities
in the city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 0900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ContinentalRecovery     11-13 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Continental Recovery,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman Charts Course From Near Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago's second-largest bank has come a long way
since its near collapse in 1984, but the highlight will be when it
is entirely back in public hands, the chairman of Continental Bank
said.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which holds 26 percent of
Continental stock as a result of bailing out the bank in 1984, is
preparing to sell the final chunk to the public, the Chicago
Sun-Times reported in Sunday's editions.
   The sale could be conducted as early as this month, the
Sun-Times said, citing unidentified sources.
   Thomas Theobald, Continental Bank chairman, has been saying
since early this year that he wanted a return to full public
ownership by the end of 1989. He said he is confident the bank will
reach that watershed in its evolution.
   ``I expect completion of the sale, absent extreme volatility in
the stock market,'' by the end of the year, Theobald said. ``It's
been pretty wild, with 100-point swings every day, to know how to
price an offering, but if it isn't done by Dec. 31, then it will be
Jan. 5.''
   The executive said the public offering should not affect the
bank to a significant degree.
   Theobald now is turning his attention to the 1990s, when
national interstate banking promises to shift restrictions and
gobble up smaller banks.
   ``All we can do is try to be better focused and more
efficient,'' Theobald said. ``That makes it more difficult for some
other ownership group to claim they can do the job better and get
financing to do the takeover.''
   Regulators and bank analysts said that Theobald, who came to
Continental in 1987, is the bank's best defense against unwanted
suitors.
   ``Continental is a Tom Theobald story right now,'' said
Prudential Bache bank analyst Lloyd Widom. ``And he is not going to
manage the bank for someone else.''
   FDIC Chairman William Seidman said Continental's fate is as hard
to predict as anyone's, but ``much depends on whether management
wants it to be acquired.''
   Much has changed since 1984, when federal regulators
restructured the bank and owned almost 100 percent of its stock
after the bank nearly collapsed because of $1 billion in bad energy
loans.
   Today, Continental is a sharply focused business bank,
specializing in controlling interest rate risk for its Fortune 1000
and middle-market customers.
   Under Theobald, the bank left retail banking, sold its suburban
banks and reduced its international operations. The bank, with the
exception of an 11 percent drop last quarter, has shown
quarter-by-quarter improvement.
   The bailout, originally predicted to cost $4.5 billion, is
expected to be as much as $3 billion less, thanks to good
collection efforts on the bad loans by bank employees, said FDIC
spokesman Alan Whitney.
   Still, not everyone thinks highly of Theobald.
   According to a recent ranking by U.S. Banker magazine, Theobald
ranked 38th out of 40 bank chief executive officers in terms of
total return to shareholders in capital appreciation and dividends.
   Theobald has returned 6.7 percent to shareholders annually, the
magazine reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
