<FIRST>r f PM-ArmandHammer     11-13 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Armand Hammer,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armand Hammer, New Pacemaker in Place, Leaves Hospital for Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrialist Armand Hammer was back home two
days after a heart pacemaker was implanted in his chest and was
expected to return to work on Tuesday, Occidental Petroleum Corp.
officials said.
   The 91-year-old chairman of Occidental was released Sunday from
UCLA Medical Center and his condition was described as good.
   ``He is at home now and he feels great,'' said Occidental
spokesman Frank Ashley. ``He expects to be back in the office on
Tuesday,'' said
   Hammer, who has had heart trouble for more than 20 years,
received the pacemaker Friday. The device regulates electrical
activity in the heart so that it beats normally in a person who
suffers abnormal heart rhythms.
   Doctors told Hammer the pacemaker should protect him ``for at
least eight years,'' Ashley said after talking with the
industrialist.
   Hours after the surgery by pacemaker specialist Dr. Peter Guzy,
Hammer was alert and talking on the telephone.
   ``Recently I had fallen and had some rib trouble,'' Hammer said.
``The doctor recommended I have a pacemaker put in. He said I would
function better and that the pacemaker would protect me from future
problems.''
   Hammer also said he hadn't suffered a heart attack.
   Nearly as well-known for his art collecting and philanthropy as
for his business acumen, Hammer considers himself a private
ambassador for world peace and has met every Soviet leader since
Vladimir Lenin.
   Trading in Occidental stock was suspended Friday on the New York
Stock Exchange because of word Hammer had fallen ill. The price of
Occidental shares has surged in the past when Hammer has been
reported to be in ill health.
</TEXT>
