<HEAD>Boeing Strike in Key Phase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by Boeing Co. production workers enters
a critical phase this week, appearing likely to become the longest
work stoppage at the aerospace giant in more than 40 years.
   With no negotiations scheduled since the Nov. 4 collapse of a
six-day effort, Saturday will be the 45th day of the walkout by the
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers.
   The last Boeing strike, in 1977, lasted 45 days and was the
longest since a 4{-month donnybrook in 1948.
   The only other post-World War II Boeing strike was a 19-day
walkout in 1965.
   Tom Baker, president of Machinists District Lodge 751, said
Sunday night that talks ``could happen'' this week, but he said he
has not heard from federal mediator Doug Hammond, who would
schedule any talks.
   There have been no indications that Boeing might want to resume
talks.
   Boeing spokesmen were unavailable for comment Sunday night.
   If the strike lasts much longer, Boeing could lose the faith of
its workers, Baker said.
   ``If they don't get this thing settled before too long, they're
going to have a very angry work force. ... The workers will feel
they're being cheated,'' he said, adding his words were not meant
as a threat.
   ``It's a concern. Really, over the years I've been with Boeing,
it's been a company that has enjoyed having a loyal work force. ...
It's just a concern that that might not be that way after this if
they're not careful. It's not a threat at all.''
   Baker said the union was willing to return immediately to the
bargaining table ``as long as it's not another charade,'' referring
