<FIRST>r f BC-Europe-Uemployment     11-13 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Europe-Uemployment,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>EC Unemployment Dips To 9.1 Percent in September</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment in the 12 European
Community countries dipped to 9.1 percent in September from 9.2
percent in August and from 9.8 percent a year-earlier, the EC said
Monday.
   According to Eurostat, the EC's statistics' agency, 14.2 million
people were out of jobs in August. A figure for September was
unavailable because of a new method of counting unemployment levels
in the Netherlands.
   Eurostat said the jobless rate showed the biggest declines in
Spain, Ireland, and Britain over the last year.
   Rates in France, Italy, and Luxembourg were little changed,
while the number of jobless in Denmark and Portugal rose slightly.
Unemployment in the Netherlands, Belgium, West Germany, and Greece
fell, in line with the EC average, Eurostat said.
   With some 17 percent of its potential labor force out of a job,
Ireland heads the EC's unemployment list. It is closely followed by
Spain with 16.4 percent unemployed.
   In contrast, Luxembourg has only 2 percent of its citizens out
of work, West Germany has 5.6 percent, and Portugal 5.7 percent.
</TEXT>
