<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today, picking up
where it left off in Friday's rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.72 to 2,630.33 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 579 up, 372 down and
530 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.50 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said stocks appeared to benefit from continuing hopes
that the Federal Reserve's gradual relaxation of its credit policy
would soften the impact of the recent slowing of economic growth.
   However, interest rates were flat to moderately higher in
today's credit market activity.
   Some observers believe the market in general has benefited from
the opening up of borders in Germany, which continued to make
headlines over the weekend.
   But the most notable response has been confined so far to stocks
of a few companies with extensive operations or investments in West
Germany.
   Among actively traded blue chips today, General Electric rose ]
to 55; American Express [ to 34}; McDonald's ] to 31|, and Philip
Morris \ to 42[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .26 to 188.16. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .56 at 372.03.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 21.92 to
2,625.62, closing out the week with a net loss of 3.90 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 890 up, 545 down and 503 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 131.80 million shares, against 143.39
million in the previous session.
