<FIRST>u f PM-Earns-Kmart     11-13 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-K mart,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>K Mart Profits Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cutting prices to improve market share
contributed to a 17.5 percent drop in K mart Corp.'s third-quarter
profits, while sales rose 5.5 percent, the company said today.
   K mart reported net income of $104.1 million, or 52 cents a
share, for its third quarter ended Oct. 25, down from $126.1
million, or 63 cents a share, for the same period last year.
Revenue totaled $6.71 billion, up from $6.36 billion a year earlier.
   For the first 39 weeks of the year, K mart earned $343.2
million, or $1.71 a share, down 16.2 percent from $409.7 million,
or $2.04 a share, in the comparable 1988 period. Revenue totaled
$19.78 billion, up 4.8 percent from $18.88 billion a year ago.
   Selling, general and administrative expenses remained stable
from one year to the next but K mart said interest expenses on debt
reached $50.9 million, up 34.5 percent, due to increased borrowing
in 1989.
   K mart Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Joseph E. Antonini
had told an Oct. 10 news conference that price-cutting would hurt
third-quarter earnings.
   ``While gross margins have been affected by this pricing
strategy and this has had a negative short-term impact on earnings,
we are fully committed to maintaining our price leadership in the
industry,'' Antonini said today. ``The lowering of prices is an
essential part of a long-term strategy to improve our market share,
and we are confident that this will benefit future results.''
   K mart was the second-largest retailer after Sears, Roebuck and
Co. in 1988 with sales of $27.3 billion. As of Oct. 25, K mart had
4,171 outlets including 2,288 K mart discount stores, 1,258
Waldenbooks, 141 Builders Square and 282 Pay Less Drug stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
