<FIRST>u f PM-GreatNorthern 1stLd-Writethru   11-13 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Great Northern, 1st Ld - Writethru,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Great Northern Rejects Takeover Bid by Georgia-Pacific</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 6th graf pvs, A response... to UPDATE
with stock price. Picks up 7th graf, Great Northern...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. today
rejected Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s $3.13 billion takeover offer,
saying the $58-a-share bid was too low, would violate antitrust
laws and would damage both companies financially.
   Great Northern Chairman William R. Laidig said the $4.5 billion
in debt the companies would incur would turn both firms ``into one
highly leveraged junk company.''
   ``Georgia-Pacific's tender offer represents no more than an
attempt to take advantage of the industry's current short-term down
cycle and to seize for its own benefit the long-term values that
should belong to all shareholders,'' Laidig said in a letter to
stockholders.
   In a second letter to Georgia-Pacific Chairman T. Marshall Hahn
Jr., who two weeks ago bid for the paper products company, he
called the unsolicited proposal ``surprising and disturbing.''
   ``Had you discussed your ill-conceived proposal with us, we
would have done our best to dissuade you from taking this
unilateral action,'' Laidig said.
   A response from Georgia-Pacific was not immediately available.
   Great Northern stock fell $1.50 to $60.62{ a share in midday New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   Great Northern, based in Norwalk, Conn., had sales of $3.6
billion in 1988 from its paper pulp, box, lumber and plywood
operations. The company owns 3.5 million acres of timberland and
has 20,000 employees at its mills and factories in Arkansas,
Colorado, Georgia, Maine, Mississippi and Wisconsin.
   The Atlanta-based Georgia-Pacific had $9.5 billion in sales,
making paper, other forest products and building materials. It owns
6.5 million acres of timberland and 380 plants and mills employing
44,000 workers.
   Georgia-Pacific proposed to buy approximately 54 million
outstanding shares of Great Northern's common stock for $58 a
share, a 50 percent premium over the market price before the
takeover rumors drove up the price. The company said acquisition
would cost a total of $4.5 billion, including refinancing, fees and
expenses.
   The offer was the first unsolicited takeover bid in the U.S.
paper industry. It ended a week of takeover speculation that raised
Great Northern's stock price 50 percent, and prompted analysts to
predict that other paper and forest products companies may bid for
Great Northern.
   Hahn said at the time of the offer that the bid was friendly and
open to negotiation.
   He said the merged company would be more competitive globally
and would offer more job stability to Georgia-Pacific and Great
Northern employees.
   Laidig, however, called the offer ``distinctly unfriendly.'' He
said an unstable company would emerge from such a merger that
``would be forced to eliminate important and highly promising
programs now under way or planned by Great Northern Nekoosa.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   11-13 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grains and Soybeans Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened higher in active
trading this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices are getting support from ongoing dry conditions in
winter wheat crop areas. There also is speculation that the Soviet
Union will soon make an offer for U.S. wheat.
   Corn and soybean futures opened strong despite fears of
profit-taking.
   The early strength of the market is basically an extension of
Friday's rally, said analyst Mickey Luth of Shearson Lehman Hutton,
Inc. in Chicago.
   Friday's rally, which saw soybeans close at a five-week high,
followed the release Thursday of a crop report by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture which estimates that the nation's corn
and soybean crop will be larger than expected.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to a { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.05 a bushel; corn was a
\ cent to } cent higher with December at $2.38} a bushel; oats were
1 cent to 1} cents higher with December at $1.44{ a bushel;
soybeans were 1 cent to 2{ cent higher with November at $5.77 a
bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent lower to .13 cent higher with December
at 74.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .28 cent
higher with November at 83.27 a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to
.40 cent higher with December at 48.35 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .30 cent to .50 cent higher with February at 63.60
cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled higher and pork futures were mixed in
Friday's trading.
