<FIRST>r f PM-MotorolaLawsuits 1stLd-Writethru f0024 11-13 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Motorola Lawsuits, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0024,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorola Agress to Settle Phone Patent Suits Against Tandy, Nokia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 2 to correct spelling of Schaumburg</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc. has agreed to settle its patent
infringement lawsuits against Tandy Corp. and a Finnish firm, the
companies announced in a joint statement.
   The electronics giant, based in suburban Schaumburg, Ill., had
alleged that Tandy and Nokia Corp. of Helsinki, Finland, had
violated its cellular telephone patents.
   Under the settlement, Tandy _ based in Fort Worth, Texas _ and
Nokia ``have agreed to a license under certain Motorola patents and
to settle with Motorola on its other claims,'' the companies said
in a statement Sunday.
   The other claims included damages for past infringement of
Motorola's cellular telephone patents and an injunction barring
importation and sale of the Tandy and Nokia cellular phones that
use technology protected by Motorola's patents, Motorola said.
   ``There were no admissions of liability on any side,'' the
companies said.
   Terms of the settlement were not disclosed.
   Motorola filed suit against the two firms before the
International Trade Commission in April and in U.S. District Court
in Chicago, alleging that seven of its cellular telephone patents
had been infringed upon.
   The ITC granted Motorola a temporary exclusion order against
Tandy and Nokia cellular phones in August after determining that
two of Motorola's patents likely were infringed, Motorola said in a
news release.
   The ITC proceedings and the federal court case will be dismissed
if the trade commission accepts the settlement, which is expected,
the joint statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
