<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   11-13 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>UPDATES throughout with closing prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shares on London's Stock Exchange closed modestly
lower in thin volume Monday, largely pressured by a downturn on
Wall Street.
   The FT-SE 100-share index settled 3.5 points, or 0.15 percent,
lower at 2,213.2, just off its session low of 2,211.5 and
substantially below the day's high of 2,233.8.
   Dealers said the market wasn't able to sustain its early
technical gains, which brought the key index back to where it stood
before Wall Street's Oct. 13 stock plunge and the subsequent
tailspin in world equity markets.
   The FT 30-share index finished 1.6 points lower at 1,771.4.
Volume was 286.8 million shares traded, down from 480.7 million
shares on Friday and among the thinnest sessions this year. The FT
500-share index was 1,216.03, down 2.13.
   ``The market moved up on extremely thin volume,'' a senior
dealer with UBS Phillips and Drew said. ``But there was a great
deal of expectation Wall Street would open weaker. It didn't take
much to knock London down.''
   Besides Wall Street's failure to move higher after Friday's
sharp gains, dealers said London's confidence was shaken late in
the session by at least one modest and broad-based program trade
executed by Phillips and Drew. The program, which the brokerage
said comprised the sale and purchase of an equal number of shares
amounting to total turnover of 6 million shares, was read as a
flurry of selling by the market.
   ``The market read it wrong,'' the Phillips and Drew dealer said.
``They thought it was more selling than it was. It just shows how
nervous London is.''
</TEXT>
