<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-HBJ     11-13 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-HBJ,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>HBJ Reports $102.7 Million 3rd Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. said Monday
it lost more than $100 million in the third quarter because of
cutbacks in public funding for educational materials and nearly
$176 million in write-offs.
   But the Orlando-based publisher and insurance carrier predicted
a large fourth-quarter gain after closing a $1.1 billion deal with
an Anheuser-Busch Co. subsidiary to acquire six HBJ theme parks.
   The sale, expected to be completed later this month, should help
HBJ reduce an estimated $2.9 billion in debt accumulated to fend
off a hostile takeover by British communications mogul Robert
Maxwell in 1987.
   For the three-month period ending Sept. 30, HBJ reported a net
loss of $102.7 million, or $1.41 a share, on revenue of $470.1
million. That compared with net income of $60.2 million, or 99
cents a share, on revenue of $463.2 million for the same 1988
period.
   The losses are calculated after issuing dividends on preferred
stock.
   The company blamed some of its losses on a sharp decline in
expenditures for public school textbooks and related materials.
   HBJ said more than half of its $176 million third-quarter
write-offs were linked to the development of the new school texts
and materials prior to the late-summer downturn.
   Efforts to streamline operations have included consolidating
textbook sales for HBJ and Holt, Rineheart and Winston, an Austin,
Texas-based subsidiary.
   On July 1, HBJ took over textbooks sales for kindergarten to
grade eight, and Holt, Rinehart was made responsible for grades
seven through 12.
   Both companies also have reduced the number of auxiliary
education materials offered to schools.
   HBJ's insurance division, which accounted for $120.7 million of
third-quarter revenue, recently signed a letter of intent for the
$27 million acquisition of American Pioneer Life Insurance Co.,
which would be its third acquisition this year.
   For the first nine months of the year, the company reported a
net loss $295.2 million, or $4.05 a share, on revenue of $1.04
billion, compared with a net loss of $54.8 million, or 91 cents a
share, on revenue of $966.9 million last year.
</TEXT>
