<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Retail     11-13 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Retail,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>K mart's Profit Drops 17.5 Percent; Dayton Hudson Has Strong Income
Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   K mart Corp. on Monday announced a 17.5 percent drop in its
third-quarter earnings as profit margins were squeezed by lower
prices on merchandise. The big discounter said revenue rose 5.5
percent.
   Department store operator Dayton Hudson Corp., which also is the
parent of one of the country's leading discount chains, reported
its income surged 39 percent on nearly a 13 percent gain in revenue.
   K mart, the country's second largest retailer after Sears,
Roebuck and Co., said its after-tax income was $104.1 million, or
52 cents a share, in the three months ended Oct. 25, down from
$126.1 million, or 63 cents a share, in the comparable 1988 quarter.
   Revenue totaled $6.71 billion, up from $6.36 billion a year
earlier.
   For the first 9 months of the year, K mart earned $343.2
million, or $1.71 a share, down 16.2 percent from $409.7 million,
or $2.04 a share, a year earlier. Revenue came to $19.78 billion,
up 4.8 percent from $18.88 billion.
   The gross margin for the quarter shrank to 26.5 percent of sales
from 26.9 percent and K mart attributed the narrowing to lower
everyday shelf prices.
   Most costs were stable except for interest expense on debt,
which reached $50.9 million, up 34.5 percent, due to increased
borrowings in 1989.
   The deterioration in K mart's profitability didn't come as a
surprise. Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Joseph E. Antonini
had told an Oct. 10 news conference that price-cutting would impair
earnings in the short run.
   He said in a news release Monday that K mart remains ``committed
to maintaining our price leadership in the industry'' despite the
negative short-term impact.
   ``The lowering of prices is an essential part of a long-term
strategy to improve our market share, and we are confident that
this will benefit future results,'' he said.
   At the end of the third quarter, K mart, based in Troy, Mich.,
had 4,171 outlets including 2,288 K mart discount stores, 1,258
Waldenbooks, 141 Builders Square and 282 Pay Less Drug stores.
   Separately, Dayton Hudson said its earnings rose to $64 million,
or 83 cents a share, in the quarter ended Oct. 28 from last year's
$46 million, or 54 cents a share.
   Revenue rose to $3.24 billion from $2.87 billion in last year's
third quarter.
   Nine-month earnings increased 52 percent to $160 million, or
$2.06 per share, from $105 million, or $1.24 per share, for the
corresponding 1988 period. Revenue through three quarters of this
year amounted to $9.16 billion, up 13 percent from $8.10 billion a
year earlier.
   Kenneth A. Macke, Dayton Hudson's chairman and chief executive
officer, predicted a strong fourth quarter.
   ``Our inventories are in good shape and we're excited about the
holiday season,'' he said in a news release.
   Operating profit of Dayton Hudson's three major divisions
increased 31 percent in the first nine months of the year, with the
performance of the Mervyn's chain leading the way. The company said
Mervyn's performance was due to strong sales, improved gross
margins and continued expense control.
   The company said its Target discount chain had a strong increase
driven by improved sales while the Dayton Hudson Department Store
Co. continued to show solid profit growth.
   During the third quarter, Dayton Hudson opened nine Target
stores and three Mervyn's stores, completing its 1989 expansion
program of 69 store openings. The corporation said it plans to open
28 more Target stores and seven Mervyn's in 1990.
   At the end of the third quarter, Dayton Hudson had 659 stores in
33 states.
</TEXT>
