<FIRST>u f AM-AFL-CIOConvention 1stLd-Writethru f0137 11-13 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AFL-CIO Convention, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0137,0886</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity, Militancy Take Center Stage at Labor Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS new 8th graf bgng, In a ... to include demonstration;
ADDS 3 grafs, bgng, The delegates ... to include other speakers. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO opened its 18th biennial
convention Monday basking in its contribution to the success of
Poland's Solidarity union and determined to adopt a more militant
stance at home as a difficult decade draws to a close.
   Opening the gathering on an upbeat note, Federation President
Lane Kirkland said, ``For all our failings and flaws and unmet
goals, the plain fact is that the American Federation of Labor and
Congress of Industrial Organizations is and will remain the largest
and most active body of free and democratic trade unionists in the
world.''
   Kirkland delivered a partisan speech to nearly 800 delegates,
denouncing policies of both the Reagan and Bush administrations and
predicting attitudes toward unions will improve as the legacy of
the 1980s becomes clearer.
   ``The bills are coming due and the ticking time bombs are going
off,'' Kirkland said. ``It is morning after in America,'' he said,
putting a negative twist on Ronald Reagan's morning-in-America
campaign theme of 1984.
   Kirkland attacked government corruption, federal deregulation,
debt-ridden leveraged buyouts in private business and what he said
was the exportation of American jobs to cheap labor markets abroad.
   The schedule for the week-long convention of the 14.1
million-member federation includes a mix of celebration and
solemnity, with the Tuesday appearance by Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa the highlight of a gathering that will also include
addresses by President Bush and Democratic congressional leaders.
   Also on tap are the elections of new officers, with Kirkland
assured of a sixth two-year term, the welcoming back into the
federation of the United Mine Workers 40 years after that union
pulled out of the umbrella organization, and renewed efforts to
assist workers involved in a number of major strikes, including
those against Eastern Airlines, NYNEX Corp., Pittston Coal Group
and Boeing.
   In a noisy demonstration of solidarity, hundreds of strikers
from those companies as well as striking Las Vegas musicians staged
a late afternoon march through the convention hall.
   With ``solidarity'' as the convention theme, Kirkland urged the
delegates to offer a warm welcome to Walesa and wished aloud that
the U.S. labor movement's part in the success of Solidarity and
trade unions in other Eastern European nations ``will provide a new
lesson for Americans regarding the role of trade unions in
promoting and preserving freedom in our own country.''
   ``In every quarter of the globe, events are in the saddle and
are driving the reluctant leaders they have overtaken,'' he said.
``The AFL-CIO has been a staunch ally and resource upon which these
movements have drawn and the demands upon us will multiply as more
and more of the world's workers rise to their feet and assert their
rights.'
   To that end, Kirkland and other federation leaders planned
private meetings with Walesa to determine how U.S. unions can best
help Solidarity now that it controls Poland's government and to
seek guidance on how to emulate in other nations the federation's
$5 million effort to help Solidarity during the past eight years.
   On the domestic front, Kirkland left little doubt that organized
labor planned to take a more aggressive stance both in organizing
in fast-growing parts of the economy and in trying to protect its
traditional base in industry.
   ``Solidarity has helped us weather the harsh climate of the
1980s, unimpaired in vigor and tougher in spirit and resolve for
the experience,'' Kirkland said.
   Bush is to address the convention Wednesday, with the recent
compromise with labor over raising the minimum wage providing a
positive note for his appearance, the first before an AFL-CIO
convention by a U.S. president since Jimmy Carter in 1979.
   But Kirkland, while avoiding mentioning Bush by name, left
little doubt that labor remained dissatisfied with him. He took
particular aim at the strenuous, though unsuccessful, efforts by
Bush and Republicans in Congress to pass a constitutional amendment
banning flag burning.
   ``Is it not time our elected representatives turn their
attention to the real flag burners in our country?'' he said.
``What about those employers who practice transitory allegiance to
the flag of any nation that will provide them with the cheapest and
most repressed labor in the world.''
   Kirkland said, ``We sound the call for attention to real
problems and away from the false alarms of diversionists who blow
the smoke of phony patriotism in the eyes of the public.''
   The delegates heard Monday afternoon from Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole and House Speaker Thomas Foley, both of whom hailed
the federation for its international activities.
   ``When the story of ourtime is written, it will reflect the fact
that fredom has to do with labor and that one of the motivating
forces influencing this tide of democracy was the AFL-CIO,'' Mrs.
Dole said.
   Foley thanked the federation for its support of Democratic Party
candidates and promised to push for passage of a labor legislative
agenda, specifically promising swift action on measures dealing
with child care, parental leave.
</TEXT>
