<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-13 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>Falling Interest Rates Push Gold Prices Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metal futures prices surged Monday on New York's
Commodity Exchange as investors reacted to recent economic
developments and indications that interest rates might decline.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures were mixed, energy
futures fell sharply, sugar prices declined and livestock and pork
futures mostly were higher.
   Gold settled $4.10 to $5.10 higher with the contract for
delivery in December at $392.70 a troy ounce; silver was 5.8 cents
to 6.5 cents higher with December at $5.318 a troy ounce.
   The buying trend for gold and silver started in Japan, continued
later in London when trading there began Monday morning and
followed through in New York, said analyst Stephen W. Platt of Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Platt said the rally in gold stemmed partly from the metal's
success in surpassing and remaining above technically significant
price levels.
   ``Buying also was linked to the impression that interest rates
are going down and uncertainty on the East European situation and
its impact on the European economy,'' Platt said.
   Platt said silver prices rose on spillover buying from gold and
on bargain hunting by investors.
   Energy futures were down on the New York Mercantile Exchange as
investors reacted to reports that the 13-member Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries exceeded its 20.5 million barrels per
day production ceiling by 3 million barrels last month.
   Michael Rothman of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York
said technical factors also came into play Monday, but the fall in
prices stemmed primarily from the production figures.
   The slowing in the growth in demand for OPEC oil could cause
crude prices to fall further if production remains at current
levels.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 17 cents to 25 cents lower
with December at $19.59 a barrel; heating oil was .76 cent to .90
cent lower with December at 57.68 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .76 cent to .97 cent lower with December at 51.06 cents a
gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures closed mixed in moderate trading on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat futures came under pressure because of an absence of
export business, said analyst Dale Gustafson of Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. in Chicago. Commercial selling sent new crop futures
lower, although Gustafson said reports of dry conditions in red
winter wheat areas helped prices.
   Corn rose fractionally on commercial buying and ongoing
speculation about increased export business to the Soviet Union.
   Gustafson said soybeans were strong, extending Friday's rally.
Soybean prices also were boosted by a strong cash market and
reports that Brazil's soybean planting was lagging well behind
normal.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 6{ cents lower with December at $4.02
a bushel; corn was a { cent lower to \ cent higher with December at
$2.38\ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{ cents higher with December
at $1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents to 3{ cents higher with
November at $5.78 a bushel.
   Sugar futures declined sharply on New York's Coffee, Sugar and
Cocoa Exchange as profit-taking set in following several days of
price increases.
   The decline may have been helped by reports that Brazil sold
sugar over the weekend. Prices rose last week partially on fears
Brazil would not be able to meet its export commitments.
   Sugar was .13 cent to .32 cent lower with March at 14.87 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and pork futures were higher in sluggish trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   The pork price rise was paced by frozen pork bellies, which
soared on commission house buying. Hog futures were supported by
expectation of steady pork product prices.
   Cattle futures were steady, supported by spillover strength from
pork and firm fed cattle prices.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .12 cent higher with December
at 74.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent to .30 cent
higher with November at 83.30 cents a pound; hogs were .42 cent to
.93 cent higher with December at 48.62 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.85 cents to 1.95 cents higher with February at 65.15
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
