<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Avon-Chartwell 1stLd-Writethru f0141 11-13 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon-Chartwell, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0141,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon, Possibly a Takeover Target Again, Seeks to Steer Away Potential
Suitor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing stock price in 8th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmetics company Avon Products Inc. on Monday
sought to repel unwanted takeover advances from an alliance of
powerful investors including oil heir Gordon P. Getty, a senior
Mary Kay Corp. executive and the Fisher real estate family of New
York.
   A limited partnership called Chartwell Associates, revealing its
intentions after it became known Friday that the group had bought a
stake in Avon, said it may propose a merger between Avon and itself
or one of its affiliates.
   In a summary of a document filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, Chartwell Associates LP disclosed that it owns
6.9 percent of Avon's common stock and intends to purchase
additional shares.
   An Avon spokesman said the company continues to believe that
Avon is better off on its own, a position the board of directors
steadfastly maintained when rejecting previous takeover proposals
this year.
   ``The board of directors' position is that the company is not
for sale,'' Avon spokesman John Cox said. ``The best interests of
the shareholders would be served by Avon remaining an independent
company.''
   Cox declined to comment on whether Avon's board had scheduled a
special meeting to consider Chartwell's interest. He said board
members had been advised about the situation over the weekend by
management.
   Wall Street reacted coolly to the latest developments in
contrast to the enthusiastic buying Friday after Avon announced it
had been notified that Chartwell held more than 5 percent of its
stock.
   Avon's stock dropped $1.50 to close at $35 a share in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading, erasing a portion of
Friday's $5.50 gain.
   Investors apparently were skeptical about the chances for a
significant increase in the stock value given that Avon seems
unwilling to enter any merger discussions.
   Earlier this year Avon spurned several suitors.
   It turned down takeover offers from Amway Corp., an Ada,
Mich.-based direct-selling concern, and from investor Irwin Jacobs.
Amway made a bid of $2.1 billion and Jacobs' was worth $2.85
billion. Together, Amway and Jacobs hold about 10 percent of Avon's
stock.
   Avon also shunned takeover feelers from Mary Kay Corp. Vice
Chairman John P. Rochon, who is involved in the newest advance on
New York-based Avon.
   The Chartwell group hasn't mentioned a price it would bid if it
decides to pursue Avon.
   In the event of a takeover, Rochon ruled out the possibility of
uniting the sales forces of Avon and Mary Kay. He also said in the
summary of the SEC filing that Avon wouldn't be merged with Mary
Kay, a Dallas-based door-to-door marketer of beauty products.
   Other options that will be reviewed by Chartwell include
purchasing more Avon shares and launching a tender offer to buy
stock from shareholders, seeking to influence the management and
policies of Avon in some unspecified way, or trying to put a
nominee on Avon's board. Another option would be to sell some of
its Avon stock on the open market or in private transactions.
   The general partners of Chartwell have been identified as Larry,
Zachery, Arnold, Richard and Anthony Fisher, a family of New York
property developers, and Argonaut Partners I, headed by Rochon. The
only limited partner is the Gordon P. Getty Family Trust.
   Within Argonaut is a group called New Arrow Corp., a wholly
owned subsidiary of Mary Kay Cosmetics Inc., the principal unit of
privately held Mary Kay Corp., which had revenue of about $400
million last year.
   There has been speculation on Wall Street that Avon could have
difficulty defending itself against Chartwell due to the
significant financial clout of Getty and the Fishers. Getty and the
Fisher brothers teamed up earlier this year in a bid for Emhart
Corp. that, though unsuccessful, was believed tohave earned the
partners tens of millions of dollars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ComputerConvention Bjt   11-13 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Computer Convention, Bjt,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>'486 Computers the Next Big Thing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What have been called the Maseratis of personal
computers, super-fast machines based on Intel Corp.'s new i486
microprocessor, took center stage at the world's biggest computer
expo Monday.
   The new personal computers on display at the fall Comdex show
are so fast they are expected to do work that otherwise would have
gone to larger and more expensive minicomputers and even mainframes.
   Buyers are learning to hook together and manage whole networks
of personal computers to run their businesses.
   ``In the beginning, PCs were considered toys, they were
automated typewriters,'' said Joe Nahil, the chief spokesman for
Compaq Computer Corp., which is at the forefront of the 486-based
computer invasion.
   486 is shorthand for Intel's i486, the central chip in the new
generation of personal computers.
   Compaq's new top-end 486 models can store up to 4 billion
characters of information at a pricetag from $15,000 up to $50,000
for specialized PCs that control networks.
   If that sounds expensive, consider that they are replacing
machinery that costs far more.
   ``We're talking about using them to replace mainframes,'' said
Alan Gregolot of International Business Machines Corp., which was
the first company to ship a commercial product using the 486 chips.
   But competitors including Compaq and Hewlett-Packard Co. say
that because IBM's Power Platform, which contains the chip, merely
replaces a 386-based board in an existing computer, it does not
take advantage of the speed and power of the 486 chips the way
their computers, specifically built around the 486, can do.
   Be that as it may, Gregolot was demonstrating Monday how the
entire property records for a small city, including changes in lot
lines over the years, the location of every power pole, and the
history of every piece of equipment attached to the pole, can be
contained and managed in a machine that sits on a desk.
   ``Right now property appraisers in many cities still have
draftsmen drawing lots by hand,'' Gregolot said.
   With a program managed by the 486-based computer, information
about, say, a zoning change could be called up immediately,
graphically displayed on a printout and fed into envelopes
addressed to neighbors who might want to object to the change.
   There were about a dozen of the 486-based PCs on display Monday
at Comdex, the huge annual trade show held in Las Vegas each fall.
   Still, observers expect many businesses to put off buying one of
the machines. Flaws in Intel's 486 chips forced delays in Compaq's
release schedule for the new computers, and IBM is working on
computers designed to specifically take advantage of the 486 chips
instead of merely putting them into a machine originally designed
for the Intel 80386 microprocessor, which works only about half as
fast.
   IBM got a bigger chunk of the 386-based PC market than Compaq
for the first time in the July-September quarter, and IBM's prices
for its computers based on Intel 286 and 386 chips are cheaper than
Compaq's, according to Stephen Smith, a PaineWebber Inc. analyst.
   But Compaq's move up with the 486-based computers appears to
position it squarely amid the market for the specialized PCs that
control networks. Sales of the so-called network servers are
booming at a time when sales growth of regular personal compters
has slowed to 10 percent a year.
   ``We think IBM is in big trouble,'' said Nihal, the Compaq
spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
