<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-13 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices declined Monday in light
trading amid persistent concern about reports of higher OPEC
production and lower oil demand.
   In futures trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the
December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade
of U.S. crude oil, fell 25 cents to finish at $19.59 per 42-gallon
barrel. Contracts for later delivery lost 17 cents or 18 cents a
barrel.
   In recent days, traders have turned their attention increasingly
to reports of overproduction by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
   OPEC is expected to discuss production strategy for 1990 as well
as reallocation of output quotas at its Nov. 25 meeting in Vienna,
Austria.
   ``The overall picture going into the OPEC meeting is quite
ominous,'' said Nauman Barakat, a first vice president of energy
futures at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Unseasonably warm weather in parts of the United States has
deepened the market's bearish sentiment, he noted.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
unleaded gasoline for December slipped 0.76 cent to 51.06 cents a
gallon. Contracts for later delivery posted steeper declines.
   Wholesale heating oil for December ended 0.77 cent lower at
57.68 cents a gallon, while most later-delivery contracts fell
further.
</TEXT>
