<FIRST>u f AM-Kodak-OpticalDisk     11-13 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kodak-Optical Disk,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Introduces New High-Capacity Optical Disk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. introduced a new
optical computer disk Monday that company officials said is capable
of storing 20 percent more information than the largest capacity
disk now on the market.
   The 14-inch optical disk will be capable of storing 8.2
gigabytes, equivalent to 8,200 megabytes, of information. Each of
the new disks will be able to hold the equivalent of 48 fully
loaded reels of magnetic tape, the company said.
   ``Our competitors _ even with their recent announcements of
increases in disk capacity _ have not been able to match the
performance or storage capacity of our first generation, 14-inch
optical disks,'' said John Batterton, a general manager of sales
and marketing in Kodak's Mass Memory Division. ``We're extending
our lead in the optical storage marketplace.''
   Kodak said the new disks would be fully compatible with hardware
components of the Kodak Optical Disk System 6800. The company said
the system's hardware will be able to write to the new disks, as
well as read from them.
   The disks are designed for use by institutions, including banks
or hospitals, to store images like X-rays or documents. Each disk
is capable of holding 2.7 million typewritten pages.
</TEXT>
