<FIRST>u f AM-MCA     11-13 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MCA,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCA Stock Surges On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainment giant MCA Corp.'s
stock surged higher Monday on renewed takeover speculation
following reports that longtime Chairman Lew Wasserman might be
willing to consider dropping the company's resistance to a buyout.
   However, a spokesman for MCA and some analysts said a statement
by Wasserman _ who reportedly told columnist Dan Dorfman that he
would ``consider anything in the best interest of my shareholders''
_ was consistent with past MCA policy.
   Dorfman commented on the possibility Friday night on a Cable
News Network show that was repeated Monday morning.
   MCA finished up $5.62{ at $67.50 a share in active New York
Stock Exchange trading.
   The conglomerate, which has interests in film, television and
music production and distribution, amusement parks, publishing and
real estate, fiercely has resisted buyout overtures in recent years.
   The entertainment and media industry has undergone tremendous
consolidation during that time.
   In the latest major deal, Sony Corp. and Columbia Pictures
Entertainment entered a $3.4 billion takeover agreement in
September. Earlier this year, Time Inc. and Warner Communications
Inc. agreed to a $14 billion merger which would create the world's
largest media and entertainment concernm, Time Warner Inc.
   A number of industry analysts have assessed MCA stock as
undervalued, saying the company could be worth as much as it could
rise to as $80 a share.
   A secretary for Wasserman, who owns 7 percent of MCA's
outstanding shares, declined a call seeking an interview Monday and
said the 76-year-old chairman did not give interviews. President
and Chief Operating Officer Sidney Sheinberg also declined an
interview through his staff.
   Harold Haas, an MCA spokesman, said Wasserman's statement to
Dorfman was ``consistent with the policy of MCA'' regarding
takeovers.
   Analyst Steve Rosenberg of Rose Media agreed, saying the stock
surge was not big enough and Wasserman's reported statement to
Dorfman was not conclusive enough to speculate that MCA is for sale.
   ``They are a perennial takeover target and speculation after
Columbia going to Sony is rife,'' Rosenberg said. ``But I certainly
wouldn't read any tea leaves into it. ...Believe me, the stock will
move a lot more than about four points if something is really
happening.''
   Unsubstantiated reports last March indicated Sony was a possible
interested buyer for MCA.
   In 1985, MCA shareholders agreed to increase the number of
common shares by 50 percent to 150 million on the basis of reports
that RCA was moving on the company.
   The company strengthened its ``poison pill'' takeover defense in
early 1988 after New York developer Donald Trump announced he had
purchased a small stake in MCA. The plan takes effect once a raider
acquires 10 percent of MCA's outstanding shares.
</TEXT>
