<HEAD>Jacor To Buy 3 Texas Radio Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jacor Communications Inc., which operates
radio stations and a cable television system, announced Monday it
has agreed to buy three Texas radio stations.
   The media compoany also said it had ended talks with one
potential buyer for two other radio stations. It also reported it
lost $1.8 million in the third quarter.
   Jacor announced it had entered a formal agreement with the Rusk
Corp. to buy radio stations KTRH-AM and KLOL-FM of Houston and
KSMG-FM of San Antonio, Texas, for $70.6 milion in cash. The
purchase involves assets that include the accounts receivable of
those stations, Jacor said.
   The deal is subject to approval by the Federal Communications
Commission, the company said.
   Terry S. Jacobs, Jacor's chairman and chief executive officer,
said the purchases are part of the company's continuing strategy to
buy major-market stations with growth potential.
   Meanwhile, Jacor said it has terminated negotiations for the
sale of its Jacksonville, Fla., and Knoxville, Tenn., stations with
Media Properties Inc. and is now talking with other potential
buyers.
   Jacor and Media Properties could not reach a final agreement,
the Cincinnati company said.
   Jacor owns 13 radio stations, including stations in Cincinnati,
Cleveland, Atlanta, Denver, Nashville, Knoxville, Jacksonville and
Tampa. It also owns a cable television system, as well as the
Georgia Radio News Service, Eastman Radio Inc. of New York and
Critical Mass Media Inc. in Cincinnati.
   Jacor also reported it lost $1.8 million, or 29 cents a share,
in the three months ended Sept. 30 in contrast to a profit of
$124,000 in the same period a year ago.
   Third-quarter revenue rose to $22.5 million from $22.3 million a
year earlier.
   For the first nine months, Jacor lost $12.7 million, or $1.58 a
share, in contrast to a loss of $3.4 million,or 51 cents a share, a
year ago.
   Nine-month revenue rose to $63.3 million from $56.4 million a
year ago.
   The losses were attributed to increased administrative and
interest expenses, refinancing of debt costs and growth expenses _
including the purchase of two Tampa, Fla., radio stations.
