<FIRST>u f AM-Griffin-Resorts 1stLd-Writethru   11-13 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Griffin-Resorts, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0262,0816</SECOND>
<HEAD>Griffin and Bondholders Reach Tentative Agreement on Resorts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT one new graf after 4th graf pvs, As part ... to include
bondholder lawyer comment. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Analysts disagreed ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Merv Griffin announced
Monday he was offering Resorts International Inc. bondholders 78
percent of the casino's equity in a restructuring plan to reduce
the company's nearly $1 billion debt.
   Bondholders on Sunday filed suit in Camden to place Resorts in
involuntary bankruptcy under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy code,
said Alison MacDonald, a New York-based spokeswoman for Resorts.
   Resorts said in a release that it had reached agreement in
principle with ``a number of substantial holders'' of its debt
about a recapitalization plan.
   As part of the agreement, bondholders said they would keep court
proceedings friendly and make the company's survival their ultimate
goal, according to Resorts officials who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Marc S. Kirschner, a New York attorney representing the senior
bondholders, said the agreement remains to be approved by
two-thirds of both sets of bondholders, a process he said could
take up to three months.
   Analysts disagreed on the merits of the deal, with one calling
the casino's future doubtful and another saying the restructuring
will allow the gaming hall time to rebound from a $34.9 million
third-quarter loss.
   Resorts has said it does not expect its operations to be
affected.
   Bondholders had until Wednesday to file in bankruptcy court if
they wanted to protect certain claims against Griffin.
   Wednesday is the first anniversary of Griffin's victory over
Donald Trump in a struggle for control of Resorts. Under federal
law, bondholders have one year to force Resorts into bankruptcy if
they want to claim they were defrauded when the casino changed
hands.
   The deal would leave Griffin with 22 percent of the gaming
company's equity. He would also retain the chairman's job and the
right to appoint a majority of directors.
   Under the agreement, Griffin would invest $15 million in cash
now, and another $15 million a year from Monday. He also would set
aside a $5 million fund to leave open the possibility of legal
action against Trump.
   John Barry, an attorney for Trump, was not in his office Monday
and could not be reached for comment.
   Marvin Roffman, a gaming analyst for Janney Montgomery Scott in
Philadelphia, said Griffin agreed to that portion of the deal to
avoid the prospect of a bankruptcy judge finding him liable for his
$50 million withdrawal plus a $10 million in a personal letter of
credit to Resorts.
   In August, the company suspended interest payments on $925
million in bonds and the following month announced a restructuring
plan aimed at preventing a bankruptcy filing.
   Bondholders attacked the plan and have since split into two
groups, one holding $600 million of subordinated unsecured debt and
another representing $325 million of senior secured debt.
   Those senior secured bondholders will receive $187.5 million in
new notes with a four-year term bearing interest of 6 percent in
the first year, 9 percent in the second, 12 percent in the third
and 15 percent in the final year, according to the restructuring
plan. They also will receive 2.5 percent of Resorts stock.
   Rent payments on property owned by the Showboat Hotel and Casino
will also finance $100 million in new 10-year bonds to those
bondholders.
   Junior bondholders will swap their debt for 75.5 percent of the
company's equity and $113.5 in new bonds.
   Roffman said the senior bondholders ``have a much better chance
of coming out smelling like a rose,'' because Resorts' debt will be
reduced by more than $600 million as a result of junior bondholders
exchanging their debt for 75 percent of the company's shares.
   ``What's 75 percent of nothing, though?'' Roffman asked,
questioning the long-term viability of Resorts, which faces the
opening next door of Trump's massive Taj Mahal casino in the spring
as well as the prospects of a declining economy.
   Resorts also needs millions of dollars worth of renovation,
which casino officials attributed as a factor in the third-quarter
financial results.
   Casino analyst John Uphoff, of Raymond James &amp; Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla., said Griffin made key concessions which could
save Resorts.
   ``In the long-term, the Taj could create more activity at that
end of the Boardwalk,'' Uphoff said. ``There'll be 4,000 people
there each night and they'll be wandering one way to the Showboat
and one way to Resorts.''
   Many analysts think Griffin paid an exorbitant price for
Resorts, the oldest casino on the Boardwalk. Trump ended up with
the unfinished Taj Mahal mega-casino for $230 million, less than
half the $500 million Resorts poured into its construction.
</TEXT>
