<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-DetroitJOA-Reax 1stLd-Writethru f0263 11-13 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit JOA-Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0263,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit Newspapers `Joined at the Wallet, But Not at the Heart'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The tie...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with JOA
to begin Nov. 27, first combined issue Dec. 2, quote; picks up 7th graf,
`The Michigan...' SUBS 15th graf, `Some Free...,' to ADD number of employees
at each paper. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus-Detroit JOA, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detroit Free Press Executive Editor Heath
Meriwether walked out into his newsroom Monday and saw a sea of
smiling faces.
   Meriwether told the 70 or so employees what they already knew,
but were waiting to hear from him: The U.S. Supreme Court, by a 4-4
tie, had cleared the way for the Free Press and The Detroit News to
partially merge their operations.
   ``Whoever said a tie was like kissing your sister didn't have it
quite right,'' Meriwether said.
   Since 1986, Knight-Ridder Inc., owner of the Free Press, and
Gannett Co. Inc., owner of the News, had been seeking to merge
their business, circulation and advertising departments. Editorial
departments would remain separate.
   ``We're joined at the wallet but not at the heart,'' said Joe
Swickard, a Free Press court reporter.
   The joint operating agreement, or JOA, will begin on Nov. 27,
and the first joint issue will come out Dec. 2, said William
Keating, president of the Detroit Newspaper Agency, which will
handle the newspapers' combined operations. The newspaper will
publish joint issues on Saturdays and Sundays.
   ``This guarantees that there will be two editorial voices in the
Detroit community for a long time _ 100 years, according to the
terms of the contract,'' Keating said.
   The tie vote by the nation's highest court meant that earlier
court decisions upholding the joint operating agreement would
stand. Justice Byron R. White had excused himself from the case for
undisclosed personal reasons.
   The Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press, an organization
which challenged the arrangement, will not ask the court for a
rehearing, said group Vice President Matt Beer.
   However, Beer said, giving up the Detroit fight didn't mean the
door was open for other newspapers to form such mergers. ``We've
created enough thin ice that anyone else who applies for a JOA will
do so carefully,'' he said.
   Another opponent, the Public Citizen Litigation Group, may seek
a rehearing, organization attorney William Schultz said in
Washington. Such a rehearing is seldom granted, Schultz
acknowledged.
   He and Beer noted that the court's decision came without an
opinion, so no one knows the justices' thinking behind their vote.
   Michigan Attorney General Frank Kelley said he was disappointed
that the court didn't issue an opinion. He said his office was
considering asking for a rehearing.
   The JOA request, brought under the Newspaper Preservation Act of
1970, said the Free Press would fail without the deal.
Knight-Ridder had said if the plan were not adopted, it would close
the 158-year-old Detroit newspaper.
   Louis Mleczko, president of Local 22 of The Newspaper Guild,
said he was disappointed with the decision. The Guild was the last
of the newspapers' unions to drop opposition to the arrangement.
   ``No more separate papers on weekends, no more morning Detroit
Newses, nor more Sunday Free Presses they've known it in the past,
no more Detroit News as they've known it in the past,'' he said.
``Advertisers are going to see skyrocketing advertising rates after
a short period of time.''
   Some Free Press employees expressed relief and joy, as well as
concern for about 500 workers who will lose their jobs when the JOA
takes effect. The Free Press has 2,200 employees, and the News
about 2,300.
   Officials with some suburban newspapers said the partial merger
would be bad news for them, too. Joining the two Detroit papers
advertising departments could present smaller papers with a huge,
near-monopoly on newspaper advertising, forcing them to boost
advertising rates, opponents have said.
   ``What it means is that like all news publishers in southeast
Michigan, we will be busy reprinting our (advertising) rate
cards,'' said Ed Wendover, publisher and editor of The Community
Crier, a weekly paper serving Plymouth and Canton, 25 miles west of
Detroit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891113-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-13-89 2224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EC-MonetaryUnion     11-13 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EC-Monetary Union,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Finance Ministers Consider British Plan for Monetary Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European finance ministers on Monday
listened sympathetically to Britain's alternative approach for
closer European monetary ties but did not wholeheartedly endorse
it, according to a British official.
   John Major, Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, told a news
conference that the plan would be discussed next month at a summit
in Strasbourg, France, of the leaders of the 12-nation European
Community.
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that the British paper was taken
very seriously ... by the delegations,'' he said.
   He acknowledged that ``it wasn't universally applauded. There
were mixed views about it. But it had a good deal of support.''
   Major, attending his first EC meeting as Britain's top treasury
official, replaced Nigel Lawson, who quit last month in a policy
dispute with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher. Lawson's resignation
rocked the British government.
   Other European finance officials have expressed concern that the
British approach could slow the movement toward full economic and
monetary union of the dozen nations of the trading bloc, also
called the Common Market.
   Earlier this month, the British government unveiled what it
described as its ``market-based'' approach to the development of
closer monetary ties. It calls for removing restrictions so that
all the European currencies would be legal tender _ acceptable for
savings and transactions _ throughout the community.
   The British have offered their plan as an alternative to
sweeping proposals that would lead to a common currency and central
bank system. The recommendations were laid out in a report drawn up
last spring by a panel of European central bankers. The committee
was led by Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission,
the community's executive body.
   The Delors plan sets out three stages for implementing monetary
union. Leaders of the EC nations agreed at a summit last June in
Madrid to go ahead with the first stage, generally calling for
closer economic and monetary ties.
   At Monday's meeting, the finance ministers gave a green light to
proposals setting the framework for closer consultations among the
nations on economic and monetary matters. That framework would be
part of the first phase of the monetary plan, which is scheduled to
begin July 1.
   As part the first phase, all currencies would be linked in the
exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System, which
keeps their values roughly steady within certain bands. The
currencies of Britain, Greece and Portugal remain outside the
linkage.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who has long resisted entering the pound into the
system, agreed at the Madrid summit to do so but only under certain
conditions. She gave no timetable.
   Major reiterated Britain's objections to the later stages of the
Delors report. ``I made it clear ... that the United Kingdom has
very considerable worries about stages two and three,'' he said.
   Mrs. Thatcher has argued that the radical moves to a joint
currency and central bank system would force nations to give up
some of their sovereignty to new institutions.
   The move toward monetary union would enlarge on the community's
push to create a single market in late 1992 by lifting the barriers
that bar the free movement of people, money, goods and services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
