<FIRST>u f AM-UAL 1stLd-Writethru f0286 11-13 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0286,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condor Partners Launches Effort To Remove UAL Board</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with directors' comment, stock
price; picks up 8th graf pvs, `Samuel Buttrick ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investment group Condor Partners took a step
Monday toward wresting control of UAL Corp. from its board of
directors, which in turn authorized its financial adviser to
explore alternatives to a takeover of the parent of United Airlines.
   Condor, formed as a takeover vehicle by the New York investment
group Coniston Partners, gained access to a list of UAL
stockholders Monday by submitting certain documents to the company.
This enables the group to send consent solicitation materials to
the stockholders, seeking their approval for removing certain board
members.
   The documents ``did not disclose the terms or financing of any
proposals that Coniston might contemplate,'' the board said in a
statement after it met Monday.
   The board said it has authorized its financial adviser, First
Boston Corp., ``to explore potential transactions with third
parties, including actively determining available alternative
transactions'' such as employee ownership or recapitalization.
   The board said it has not received any offers from third parties.
   Coniston announced Nov. 3 that it owned 9.7 percent of UAL and
wanted to direct a sale, recapitalization or other ``extraordinary
transaction'' involving the Chicago-based company.
   Coniston also wants to reduce UAL's board from 16 members to
five, three of whom would be Coniston principals.
   The board said Monday that the two directors Coniston wants to
retain, Stephen Wolf and Frank Olson, have indicated they would not
serve on any UAL board controlled by Coniston. Wolf is UAL's
chairman, president and chief executive officer.
   Monday's board meeting was the first since directors freed Wolf
to explore new options following a collapsed employee effort to buy
the company.
   UAL's shares closed Monday at $193.25, up $3.75 in consolidated
New York Stock exchange trading.
   Samuel Buttrick, an airline analyst with Kidder Peabody &amp; Co. in
New York, said that given the failure of the $6.75 billion buyout
bid by United's pilots, a management team and British Airways PLC,
there are significant numbers of UAL shareholders who are
sympathetic toward Coniston.
   Speculators want to see UAL sold or recapitalized quickly to
minimize their losses following the Oct. 13 collapse of the
$300-a-share bid from the pilot-management group.
   ``If I were on the board, I would assume that there are
sufficient shares held by accounts sympathetic to Coniston that
would result in a majority vote against the board,'' Buttrick said.
   Analysts said UAL began its defense against Coniston's attempt
to seize control of its board when it gave Wolf permission to seek
a buyout or recapitalization.
   ``It would seem that one obvious alternative (to Coniston) is
for Wolf to put together a management-labor team to buy out the
company,'' said analyst Louis Marckesano of Janney Montgomery Scott
Inc. in Philadelphia.
   ``Failing that, he could put together a restructuring similar to
what happened with Allegis.''
   Allegis Corp., the former parent of United, was broken up in
1987 after Coniston obtained a 14 percent stake in the company and
demanded an end to its diversification within the travel industry.
   In response to the pressure, Allegis sold its Westin and Hilton
International hotel operations and its Hertz car rental business.
   Marckesano said there are difficulties associated with a
recapitalization because UAL has few assets to sell to raise cash.
   He noted that UAL has cash on hand, and could sell its aircraft
and lease them back.
   ``The best alternative is a management-labor buyout,''
Marckesano said.
   Officials of the Air Line Pilots Association chapter at United
met last week with Coniston principals and financier Saul
Steinberg, a friend of Wolf who is seeking government permission to
buy more than 15 percent of UAL.
   Pilots said they have discussed a revised bid with UAL
management, but they hinted last week that they might resume a work
slowdown in effect earlier this year unless the UAL board recommits
in the next two weeks to majority employee ownership.
   United's Machinists, who opposed the failed buyout bid, also met
last week with Coniston principals.
   They say they won't support any highly leveraged deal that could
threaten the airline's viability or that would involve Wolf.
</TEXT>
