<FIRST>r f BC-OptionsViolations     11-13 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Options Violations,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Options Exchange Disciplines Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California options broker was barred
permanently from membership in the Chicago Board Options Exchange
for trading on a customer's account without permission and refusing
to cooperate in the investigation, the exchange said Monday as it
announced five disciplinary actions.
   According to the CBOE, Paul Weirather, a former registered
representative in the Modesto, Calif., branch of Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc., consented to a ban on membership and from
associating with any exchange member.
   Weirather was accused of making ``numerous transactions ...
without prior written authorization from the customer and prior
written approval by the firm.''
   The exchange said he also refused to respond to requests for
information on the transactions. Weirather and the four other
people disciplined neither admitted nor denied the allegations
brought by the exchange, and all consented to the punishment.
   Also disciplined was Jonathon E. Gross, a former registered
representative of Oppenheimer and Co., who allegedly made
misrepresentations to a public customer. He was censured and
suspended for six months from associating with other members.
   Richard V. Seffren, a former exchange market maker, was accused
of a transaction that failed to contribute to the maintenance of a
fair and orderly market. He was censured and suspended for three
days.
   Mark C. Williamson, a former registered representative in the
Burlington, Mass., branch of Dean Witter Reynolds, was censured and
suspended from association with other exchange members for two
weeks. He was accused of making trades on a customer's account
without permission.
   Charles D. Tom, a former registered representative in the
Chicago office of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., allegedly guaranteed
a customer's account against losses in return for sharing in the
profits. He was censured and suspended from associating with other
members for five days.
</TEXT>
