<HEAD>Amoco Vice-Chairman Named To Replace Bays At Whitman Corp.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS overline, recasts first 2 grafs to clarify. Picks up
3rd graf, `Until Cozad ...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whitman Corp.'s board of directors announced
Monday it had elected Amoco Corp. Vice Chairman James W. Cozad as
chairman and chief executive officer of the Chicago-based
conglomerate, effective Jan. 1.
   Cozad, 62, who also is chief financial officer of Chicago-based
Amoco, will succeed Karl D. Bays at Whitman, who died of a heart
attack last week.
   Until Cozad takes office, the company will be led by Miles L.
Marsh, its president and chief operating officer.
   Cozad joined Amoco in 1969 as financial vice president. He
became a vice president of Amoco in 1971, a director in 1976 and
was elected vice chairman in 1983.
   ``Jim Cozad has made a major contribution to Amoco's success,''
said Amoco Chairman Richard Morrow. ``While I regret his leaving
Amoco, I certainly understand his decision to accept the position
at Whitman, where he has been a director for several years.''
   Morrow said Cozad will be succeeded by Frederick S. Addy as
Amoco's chief financial officer. Addy, 57, is vice president of
finance.
   There had been speculation that Marsh would be named Bays'
replacement. Marsh, 42, previously headed General Foods Corp., a
subsidiary of Philip Morris Cos. Inc. He arrived at Whitman nine
weeks ago.
   Whitman's operations include Pet Inc. foods, Pepsi-Cola General
Bottlers, Hussman Corp. food service equipment, and Midas
International Corp. auto service centers.
   Shortly before his death last week, Bays told a meeting of
bankers and investors in London of his outline for a strategy of
pumping funds into Whitman's operations to increase production
capacity and improve profitability.
   Acquisitions will play an important role in Whitman's expansion,
he said.
   Analysts say Bays' strategy likely will be followed by his
successor.
   Since selling the Illinois Central Railroad and shedding its
defense, aerospace and heavy manufacturing units, the former IC
Industries _ renamed for the candies Pet Food produces _ has
concentrated on consumer goods and services.
