<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0293 11-13 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0293,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Share Prices Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was slightly higher against the
Japanese yen Tuesday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange erased earlier gains and inched down.
   The dollar ended the morning session at 143.73 yen, slightly
lower from its opening. The currency started trading at 143.80 yen,
up 0.25 yen from Monday's close here of 143.55 yen, and ranged from
143.60 to 143.83 yen during morning trading.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 19.01
points, or 0.05 percent, to end the morning session at 35,731.11.
It closed at a record 35,750.12, up 86.92 points, on Monday.
   The index fell as participants expressed fear that stock prices
had gone too high, said Kazuyuki Suzuki, a dealer with Daiwa
Securities.
   ``The trading was just directionless,'' he said, adding that
uncertainties over foreign exchange rates also discouraged stock
buying.
   Institutional investors were reluctant to make major moves prior
to the auction of 30-year U.S. government bonds scheduled for later
Tuesday in Washington, other dealers said.
   In currency dealings, the dollar-yen rate was moving narrowly,
as market players were reluctant to make major moves ahead of a
series of releases of the U.S. economic indicators later this week,
as well as the auction for the U.S. government bonds, said a
foreign exchange analyst with New Japan Securities Co.
   Among the major releases was the U.S. retail price index for
October, due out later Tuesday.
   The analyst, speaking anonymously, said the West German mark,
which had been bought earlier, was lower due to sellings for
profit-taking.
</TEXT>
