<FIRST>r f AM-Yugo-Bankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru f0276 11-13 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugo-Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0276,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reorganization Plan Distributed to Creditors for Consideration</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Commisa, sted Commissa, in 2nd and last
grafs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Creditors of Yugo America Inc. have until
Dec. 6 to vote on a final reorganization plan for the Upper Saddle
River-based company, according to a lawyer for the U.S. agents of
the Yugoslav car manufacturer.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Vincent J. Commisa approved Yugo America's
disclosure statement last Thursday, said Robert A. Baime, a lawyer
for Impex Car Corp.
   Baime said the disclosure statement, along with the
reorganization plan, would be distributed to Yugo America's secured
and unsecured creditors, who have until Dec. 6 to vote on whether
to accept the plan.
   The disclosure statement serves as a prospectus of the
reorganziation plan, Baime said, and is designed to give creditors
information about the plan.
   The plan would provide for a 21-cent per dollar payment to
unsecured creditors over three years or nine cents on the dollar if
they elect not to wait three years, Baime said.
   Dealers who continued to serve as Yugo dealers would receive 100
percent payment under the plan, Baime said. Dealers who elected to
stop selling Yugos or were dropped by the company would be treated
as unsecured creditors.
   Manufacturers Hanover Trust, the main secured creditor, would be
paid in full, Baime said.
   Under the reorganization, Zavodni Crevna Zastava, the car's
manufacturer, would become the wholly owned parent company, Baime
said.
   Commisa set the next hearing in the case for Dec. 13, Baime said.
</TEXT>
